Shall I read a book?
(There is a scene where the demon king attacked the human world. The demon king kidnapped the princess.)
(Our hero, Don Julius, met a bunch of companions while on a quest to defeat the demon king and save the princess.)
(In the end, Don Julius defeated the demon king and brought peace back to the world.)
That’s a wonderful story.
Isn't that just a murder case?
I read it again and found that the princess was only mentioned in the first half.
Could it be that the princess fell in love with the demon king?
Then, it would be understandable that they couldn't say so in the book.
Or maybe one companion who joined on the way was the princess?
That’s also interesting.
(It's a story of a man who loved Jane.)
(But Jane didn't love anyone. She just wanted to be free.)
(Jane realized her feelings only after the man died.)
That’s such a sad story.
Sounds like a horror novel.
It’s so sad even after reading again.
It’s even more scary to see it again.
Pietro was a shoe shiner.
He then received a great reward from a fairy, and lived happily for the rest of his life.
What's the lesson?
The service industry is hard?
I read it again and it didn't mention what would happen if the fairy won the bet.
His shoe polishing skill was so good that people even came from neighboring villages.
When word of the shoe shiner reached the ears of a fairy living in a nearby forest, it wanted to play a prank.
The fairy went to Pietro and said,
"Can you make any pair of shoes sparkle and shine beautifully?"
"I can."
"Let's make a bet. Polish the next three customers' shoes to perfection, and you'll get one wish."
"Okay."
Then the fairy poured water on the main road in the village without Pietro knowing and made it muddy.
The first customer came in wearing shoes that was muddy from stepping on the mud.
Pietro skillfully brushed off the mud with a brush and shined the shoes by applying shoe polish.
The shoes became clean and shiny instantly. The first customer was satisfied and left.
This time, the fairy made the sun scorching.
The second customer's shoes were covered with mud that hardened like stone because of the sun.
Pietro smashed the mud with a hammer and grinded down the rest with sandpaper.
After shining them, the shoes sparkled even more than before. The customer was satisfied and left.
The fairy, who was so annoyed, transformed into a beggar this time and went to see Pietro himself.
Pietro was surprised on seeing the third customer's shoes.
Looking closely, what he thought were muddy shoes were just feet covered in a lot of mud.
Pietro, after much thought, baked the mud into pottery.
Glazing the pottery made it shine brighter than any other shoe.
Enchanted by the elegant shoes, the fairy forgot about the bet.
If you work hard, good luck will come?
What would the fairy have taken if Pietro lost?
Isn't it usually the wrist here?
Oh, Virgil! That's gross.
<Mud Shoes>
<Life with Mushrooms>
Preface
Turn to a random page
Epilogue
Mushrooms are everywhere, and not a single one is a bad mushroom.
Unless you're a small child who takes anything interesting and puts them into your mouth.
But such a passionate and pure inquiry process is indispensable.
We stand upon the bodies of the pure-hearted explorers. No need to join them. They don't want us to either.
In that sense, this book was not written only with my own effort.
In honor of Sherry, the purest and most passionate explorer.
I know this book. They recommended it to me at school.
But why didn’t you read it?
Mara Smith wrote it...
My classmates said she died from eating poisonous mushrooms.
That’s why I didn’t read it.
She was also a passionate and pure explorer.
Where should I look this time?
Black dragon scale mushroom
This is a black mushroom that looks like dragon scales. The surface is very hard and rough.
It usually grows from tree bark, with at least 10 bundled up together.
When roasted, it is great to have as a snack because it becomes crispy.
It has the effect of making the skin firm. Be careful as it will cause keratin if you eat too much.
This I know. During festivals, they cut it into bars and fry and sprinkle it with sugar. It's crunchy and delicious!
Golden wine glass
It is a cup-shaped mushroom with a bright golden color.
It usually grows in places with occasional sunlight, such as the inside of rotten tree trunks.
Death if you eat it and eternal life if you drink the dew within, as they say.
It's toxic when eaten directly, but when made into medicine, it becomes a potent antidote.
A mushroom that looks like a wine glass made of gold?
A stupid witch is worse than a poisonous mushroom.
And red blood-like dews will form in it? How can you pass up this?
Actually, blood-red dews form within the mushroom at dawn, and unlike what the rumors say, the dews are fatally toxic.
You won't want to drink that unless you're mad!
No one will drink it. It doesn't have a skull mark, but you can tell it will kill you.
But someone must have drunk it to know that you'll die, right?
Must have been the most naive and passionate explorer.
Rain cloud mushroom
It is a mushroom that looks like a pure white cotton ball.
It usually grows by sticking to living trees.
If it absorbs enough nutrients, it will gradually turn black. If it absorbs enough water, it will spray water down like rain.
After it rains like that, the color returns to pure white again.
It is widely used as medicine because it helps digestion and has pain killing effect.
That’s because a poisonous mushroom kills just one person.
Dice mushroom
It’s the size of a thumb, and comes in red, blue, or yellow. Small and cute.
A number between 1 and 6 will vividly appear in your mind if you eat it.
It’s an interesting mushroom that has a very strange effect of manipulating the human mind.
But it is normally used only in gambling games where the person with the larger number wins.
There was a time when I bet with a friend, and the number 6 didn't come out even after I ate 20.
Can't you just reject the number that comes to mind and say 6?
The effect is stronger than you think. You can't just lie.
I tried really hard to say 6.
It is a short and powerful epilogue.
Ellie.
Virgil, first of all, I'm not stupid.
Secondly, don’t compare me to a mushroom.
Stop reading
The dark purple book cover is slightly soft but sturdy. It says the author is Mara Smith.
Where should I look?
I don't need to sleep.
I have to return to the train.
Let's go to the village first.
Let’s meet the village chief first and then rest.
I shouldn’t sleep now.
I’m not sleepy yet.
I should clean this place up first.
Load
Any unsaved progress will be lost. Do you wish to load the most recently saved progress?
What should I do?
We are in the [em1]village[/em1]! At last!
Yeah, it's a village.
What kind of village would it be? I hope a lot of fun things happen here.
I'm not sure about the fun things, but we apparently have some trouble.
This is the life I've always dreamed about.
Let's hurry up and go.
Uh...
It’s quite a dull sight.
Virgil...
So, this is the village you're going to spend 3 years in. You like it?
Do you feel like going back to Highlion again?
What the heck happened here?
What are [em1]all these prickly vines[/em1] doing here?
I don't even know how to comment.
I’m so excited.
Let’s find [em1]Rubrum[/em1] first.
And... Something seems strange.
Everyone would find it a strange sight. Why do these [em1]prickly vines grow only on houses[/em1]?
No, that's not what I meant.
It feels like [em1]I've been here[/em1] before for some reason.
Is that some sort of cliché and meaningless foreshadowing?
There's no way you've ever been here.
They don’t come this far for the witch school picnic.
But something [em1]feels familiar[/em1], really.
Did you meet the flying carpenter?
I don't know. It seems like I did have a [em1]dream[/em1] but...
I don't remember anything.
Are you nervous or something, since this is your first day as an apprentice witch?
Of course not.
So, are you ready to start your first day as an apprentice witch?
Of course!
Do you know what to do?
Let me ask what Enite thinks first.
Although she will naturally approve, I shall wait until I actually hear it.
We’ll check out the [em1]carpenter’s house[/em1] and try to [em1]get rid of the prickly vines[/em1].
Remember that we don’t have any [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Phoenix_Collect_Name"))][/em1] left.
It will work out somehow.
Let’s go to [em1]Enite[/em1] first.
Try to summarize what you have heard.
Enite said it has [em1]similar characteristics[/em1] as White Prickly Vine.
Rubrum said it [em1]smells like [lua(GetLocalizedString("InteractableObject", "LittleHoneyPumkin"))][/em1]. Then it's probably also [em1]similar[/em1] to the[lua(GetLocalizedString("InteractableObject", "LittleHoneyPumkin"))].
Arden... didn't tell me anything in particular.
He said it was "[em1]someone’s malice[/em1]".
Seeing a prickly vine that can destroy and get rid of a house is enough to make you think so.
It seems that Arden thinks it is the [em1]witch’s work[/em1].
Witch's curse? In a world like today? That's an old-fashioned way of thinking.
He wouldn't think so if he's been to Lucerine Ortu.
But the witches of the old days are still alive.
Heh, let's find the culprit later and think about [em1]Kyla's house[/em1] for now.
In summary, the prickly vines in the village are a combination of the [em1]characteristics of several plants[/em1].
Alright. I think I've asked everyone.
I think I might have seen something related to the prickly vine on the [em1]witch bookshelf[/em1] on the first floor.
Let’s also go look through the [em1]witch's house[/em1] like Arden said.
Let's go check.
Wow, it's so dark.
If you're scared, we can go back to the train.
I love it!!!
Let's hurry.
It's a [em1]secret passageway[/em1], Virgil!
I don't think it's a secret or a passageway.
I bet there's a path beyond here.
A mountain!
You're yelling because you hate it, right?
I always hated mountains.
My leather gets worn out from all the wind.
I must find the handle to use the Roaster.
Should I use the metal handle I have for the Roaster?
Don’t use
Good, now I can use the Roaster.
Good work. You'll be able to make more potions.
I must change the glass bottle to use the Extractor.
Should I use the glass bottle I have for the Extractor?
Good, now I can use the Extractor.
We can finally make potions properly.
Then what do I do now?
Didn't you want to go to the village?
You should remove the giant prickly vines then.
That’s true but...
It seems impossible to get rid of that huge thing with the recipe I have now.
The basic recipe does seem kinda inadequate.
What’s your plan?
Now that the [em1]Extractor[/em1] has been fixed, you'll be able to make potions from the [em1]basic recipes[/em1].
If you make [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "BadGrassPotion_Name"))][/em1], you can get rid of [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("InteractableObject", "LittleHoneyPumkin"))][/em1]...
A little more... Yeah, so the forest...
I’ll be able to go to the places that have been blocked!
Let's look through the forest! There must be something!
That's what I'm saying.
The village is to the right.
The village should be around here.
Let’s meet the village chief first.
Let’s go to sleep for today.
Someone must be living here.
Then wouldn't it be best if you left them alone?
Besides, you're about to leave.
I wonder if Rosie lives here?
Seems so, based on that fishing rod.
She really does live in the woods.
Is this my dream?
It's darker than I thought.
Virgil isn’t here either.
Woohoo! The [lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "MoonTear_Name"))] is ready!
Now all I have to do is remove the core.
Now I must find the core.
Ready?
Okay.
Okay. Here goes!
Alright, now I also removed the bird cage that was protecting the core.
Let's focus on what we're doing now.
I had some kind of [em1]weird dream[/em1]. I’m sure.
You've been saying that for the past few days.
What kind of dream was it?
That's the problem.
I don’t remember what the dream was.
It must be an ordinary silly dream then.
No! I mean something’s strange.
Isn't it because the bed has changed?
Something... Something feels strange.
Maybe so. But I’m getting some kind of [em1]feeling that it's important[/em1].
I should try asking other people too.
Rubrum?
Hey Ellie!
Let me try guessing this time.
Roy’s house is complete, right?
How did you know?
Because you came to pick me up like this last time, too.
Teehee, exactly. Let’s hurry up and go, Ellie!
Welcome, Ellie.
Wow...! I love the scent of the flowers!
It's still unorganized and messy inside, but...
I put what I brought outside for now.
I'm glad you like them.
The witch helped me a lot once again.
You can thank her properly later. Hahaha!
Hello, Roy. My name is Ellie.
Yes, nice to meet you. I heard about you from Enite.
You helped to get rid of the prickly vines in the village and restore the house.
Thank you. I owe you one.
It was nothing.
Me too! Me too! I helped too.
Thank you as well, Rubrum.
Hehe.
When Kyla returned, it felt like a dream.
But now, Roy is back, too.
It made me feel excited again to see Kyla building Roy’s house.
Everyone really gave their all this time, too.
Ellie, here! Let's pop this together!
One, two, three!
Oh.
Ah.
What’s the matter?
It's a person we saw on the train...!
I thought you were going to Highlion... This is an unexpected reunion.
Yes. How fascinating.
Hmm... I suppose I should introduce myself properly.
It's been so long since all of us got together.
The fountain is restored too, and I wanted to celebrate our reunion.
Thank you all for coming.
Come to think of it, I didn't give Ellie a proper welcoming.
Granny's giant pie!
Then I’ll leave it to you, Arden.
Hmm, don't get too close.
This is fun.
Right?
From the bottom of my heart, thank you, Ellie.
It feels like only good things are happening to the village since you arrived.
I’m also super happy because Ellie is here!
I was surprised when I got your letter.
When I left the village, I thought the prickly vines would never be removed...
Thank you again, Ellie.
I just did what a witch should do.
By the way, Arden is absent again, right?
Right. Arden says he has to make stew.
He’s strangely diligent although there aren't many customers. Hahaha.
Thanks for everything, Ellie. Keep up the good work.
Keep up the good work!
I'll go out of my way to help if you're asking.
Nice to make your acquaintance.
Me too!
Oh, Ellie. Let me talk to you for a minute before you go.
What’s up, Enite?
I looked around the village yesterday.
Ever since the giant prickly vines covered the houses and villagers started to leave, I have lost hope that this day would come.
It brings back old memories to see Kyla's house and Roy's house in their previous state.
Thank you so much, Ellie. It wouldn't be enough to thank you a hundred times.
No, not at all. It's something that I wanted to do.
The ruins back here used to be a fountain.
We used to gather here to chat, share snacks, and sing.
I want to have an area like this ready for the others that may return in the future.
I really shouldn't ask... but could you help me?
Sure. I made a promise to help the villagers return.
Thank you, Ellie. You can talk to Kyla for the details.
Please leave it to me.
[em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "FirecrackerPotion_Name"))][/em1] is ready!
I finally made one with my own hands...
Be careful handling it. It’s probably supervised by the Administration for a reason.
Yes, of course. Because no one should get hurt.
Let’s take the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "FirecrackerPotion_Name"))][/em1] to Enite.
Haha! I passed the Gaga Bird safely!
Has anyone seen Virgil?
Why are you talking nonsense after a good night's rest?
What...? You weren’t there.
Stop sleep talking and wash your face first.
What’s the...? Was it just a dream?
I'm right on your head.
What's this?... This uncomfortable feeling...
Did you have a nightmare or something?
No, it wasn't a nightmare... I'm sure I had a dream but can't remember anything.
Hmmm... Since I’m a witch…
It's morning. Stop sleep talking and wake up.
Since I'm a witch…
<shake>Miracle morning!</shake>
Ahhhhh!
What's wrong with you? You had a weird dream or something?
Huh? You're right. What kind of dream was that?
Very strange.
I had a strange dream.
What kind of dream?
Ugh... I don't remember.
Ellie, it’s time to get up.
Get out of bed if you're awake.
*Groan*...
You just woke up. Why do you look dead already.
I think I had an important dream, but I can't remember it.
It seemed like something important...
Like the principal's sermon?
That's something I don't want to think about again...
Dammit! I can't catch it by hand!
Did you really think a butterfly is stupid enough to just get caught willingly?
Then, what do you want me to do?
You said you would fill the [em1]Encyclopedia[/em1]. Use your brains.
Oh! The quill!
First, I'll [em1]add them to Encyclopedia[/em1] with it.
Let’s use the [em1]quill[/em1] to register [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Encyclopedia", "MoonButterfly_Name"))][/em1] in the [em1]Encyclopedia[/em1] and try [em1]opening it up[/em1].
Alright, who's the next villager?
Only one has returned so far.
The first one is always the hardest. It'll be quick from now on.
Should I start from what's right in front of me?
Maybe I should plan this out first.
Well... Even if I want to look elsewhere...
with the [em1]bridge[/em1] in this state, I can't go anywhere.
You have a point. Better do what's at hand than try fixing the bridge.
It's decided! The next villager will be whoever that lived in this house south of Kyla's.
First, let's talk to [em1]Enite[/em1].
This is simple for someone like Ellie Blueriver!
Let's talk to Kyla about it then.
Great. It's finally time to explore.
Please don't use that word "explore"...
That word gives me anxiety, thanks to your mother.
Woah!
It's so pretty! Ellie, you’re the best!
Wow, seeing the fireworks from Wisteria is great too.
Gorgeous.
Those are some great fireworks.
They are so beautiful.
The ones I saw with my husband a long time ago were just like these.
Thank you, Ellie.
I'm so glad everyone likes them.
Now, let's all have some pie.
It's been a while since I baked a pie this big, so I'm not sure how it'll taste.
Rubrum, will you please help?
Yup!
Wow... It smells amazing.
It's the giant pie that Granny occasionally talks about!
Wow, it's been a really long time.
I couldn't find this flavor even in famous bakeries in Highlion.
Ahem, it seems to be baked well.
Ellie also prepared something amazing this time.
Here, Ellie. It’s your turn.
Here goes! A refreshing [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "FirecrackerPotion_Name"))][/em1]!
Wow, what is this place?
Looks like some kind of puzzle, Virgil!
It's a very suspicious and unnatural sight.
Let’s solve this puzzle first.
For Kyla, right?
Of course. Don’t ask twice.
That looks like a [em1]seesaw[/em1] and a [em1]weight[/em1]...?
Who made it?
It feels similar to something we saw in the forest...
It got bigger!
I smell something fishy here.
Look around you.
Wow, it worked!
Good. This probably got rid of the village's prickly vines as well.
Now I can bring Kyla back to the village.
Let’s hurry up and go to the village.
The prickly vines have gone all the way up there, blocking the path.
There has to be a way to get across. Get closer and take a look.
Did you see that? It grew instantly!
That's why people look for witch potions.
I can step on that to get through now.
Let's continue to follow the prickly vine traces.
If only this one were fine like the one next to it. I would be able to cross it.
It's withered, so find a way to [em1]revive it[/em1].
If you really don’t know, it’s okay to ask others.
Hmm... [em1]A way to make it grow[/em1]...
<shake>Ah, I can’t take this anymore!</shake>
It's too noisy. My ears hurt.
Just hold on a little bit longer.
You're fine because your ears are just flaps of leather!
To be fair, your ears are just leather before dressed.
Ugh... Virgil. Don't give me that look. It causes me goose bumps.
Think of a way to get past that noisy Gaga Bird.
Hmm... What should we do?
<shake>[em1]Go away!!![/em1]</shake>
Great, no big deal.
That's being a bit cruel to the Gaga Bird, no?
You mean, that thing is being cruel to me.
I missed the train because of that bird.
It's not like the bird made you miss the train...
Let’s hurry and find the [em1]Prickly Vine Core[/em1].
What is this sound?
<shake>It’s too noisy!</shake>
The Gaga Bird would make a sound like this if we hang it upside down.
Wait, that one isn’t hanging upside down, though.
After all, Gaga Birds are known for being insane...
Maybe for the bird, that's upside down.
The [em1]prickly vine traces[/em1] continue to the [em1]forest[/em1] beneath the Gaga Bird.
It’s a real Gaga Bird.
<shake>Do you think we can get through...?</shake>
We can, as long as we put up with that [em1]terrible sound[/em1].
I don't think I'll get a wink of sleep on the train.
I wonder if there's anywhere I can sleep for tonight.
What about the ground? The dirt and rocks should make for a nice bed.
That's not funny, Virgil.
Look, this place is also inhabited by the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Encyclopedia", "MoonButterfly_Name"))][/em1] we saw at the peak.
You might as well collect some for study purposes.
You think I could just sneak up and grab it?
Let's take a look at the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Encyclopedia", "MoonButterfly_Name"))][/em1].
Let's check information about [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Encyclopedia", "MoonButterfly_Name"))][/em1] since they're registered in the [em1]Encyclopedia[/em1].
Let’s use the [em1]quill[/em1] to register [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Encyclopedia", "MoonButterfly_Name"))][/em1] in the [em1]Catalogue[/em1].
Wait. Don't you remember what Mr. Gravier said?
[em1]Draw it before you touch it![/em1]
Exactly.
Firstly, use the quill to draw it in the Encyclopedia.
Death lives under the bed?
No, not that...
I can’t go out with the weights.
Wait, what's wrong with this?
Looks like we need to dig a grave for your 12th broom...
Not that bad! That only knocked a bit of durability off it.
I barely rode it too...
Well, what can you expect from a free gift.
I think there was a good workbench at the workplace. I can fix it there.
All I need is a [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Branch_Name"))][/em1] or a [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Mud_Name"))][/em1].
I finally reached the highest level!
What is a [lua(GetLocalizedString("EncyclopediaAchievement", "Benefit_Collection"))]?
Don’t get your hopes up.
Let’s ask Diane.
Shall we check in the Witches' Catalogue?
None of the items in this space can be taken out.
Whoa, what's this?
It's a reward for working so hard for the Encyclopedia.
It's pretty.
But where should I keep it?
The Witch's House is too small right now.
We can use it to decorate the Witch's House.
I'll hang on to it for now.
Huh, the second floor is smaller than I thought.
I suppose there's still work left to do.
There's nothing we can do here, then.
I think there are more rooms here, but they're blocked.
Oh, Virgil, do you see that?
There's a colorful lizard-like thing.
I've never seen something like that before.
Let's go check it out!
The second floor can be expanded once it's repaired like the first floor.
I guess I have to talk to Kyla again...
Arden’s soup must taste good.
I didn't gain weight!
This Witch's House is too old to begin with.
I guess so.
I should repair the house.
You’re thinking like that only after you broke the floor.
I should tell Diane, right?
Wouldn't it become official once you tell Diane?
What does that mean?
It's an execution of budget.
She'll upload a document and a witch will come.
And they'll find out that there's no master witch here.
Then what should I do?
The Witch's House can also be fixed by a skillful artisan.
Then I should ask Kyla.
I mean once I get out of here.
Isn't it too squeaky?
Did you gain weight?
Hey! That’s not it!
Good, I got out somehow.
Isn't this bad?
There's a huge hole there, though.
Let’s ask Kyla and the others.
Squeak-squeak-squeak.
If I'd gone to Highlion, I wouldn't be listening to this.
It's better to make noise than to die of boredom, isn't it?
I've finished my inquiries.
But I haven't learned much.
What do you mean? Didn't we learn a lot?
Like her hating mushrooms... Sleeping with her back against the wall...
Or eating bread for a meal.
I mean, outside of those things!
So was Lisa really responsible for these prickly vines?
I'm certain that's what she was studying.
But I don't understand what she intended to do.
Yes, so let's not jump to conclusions yet.
We should focus on finding Lisa.
But we don't know where she is.
Didn't Rubrum give us a useful tip?
Let's go ask the [em1]Black Cat God[/em1]?
I don't think it'll be much help.
A god should know something.
It's hard to interpret the words of a god.
Let's give it a try anyway.
Then let's first go to the [em1]temple[/em1] Rubrum mentioned.
Let's restore the [em1]temple[/em1] first then.
If we pray at the temple in the day, the Black Cat God will appear.
Virgil.
What.
We don't need to pray now.
If we want to summon the Black Cat God, we should pray during the [em1]day[/em1].
Woah...! It really is done.
Yup. Thanks to you, it came out quite nicely, if I may say so myself.
It's amazing.
I helped Kyla build her house, too.
The little tyke Rubrum sure did help.
Although, his sand castle skills could use some work.
It fills me with joy to see Kyla back and her home restored.
Ellie, Kyla, and Rubrum. Your combined efforts are what made this possible.
It's such a joyous day, so I wanted to celebrate with everyone.
Granny gave me this, too!
We're all gonna pop it together!
You're here early. What's up?
You're not hurt, are you?
Nope. Granny told me to come get you.
They've finished building Kyla's house, so she wants everyone to come and celebrate.
Alright, let's go now.
Aww, so cute!
Teehee!
I never thought this day would come.
I can't recall the last time I've been this excited.
I'm glad to see Kyla again too!
Everything you do is so cool, Ellie.
I got your letter. It filled me with joy.
If you need help restoring the village, just let me know.
Thank you, Ms. Witch.
By the way, where’s Arden?
Arden couldn't come. He said he had to prepare for the business hours.
But, he told me to tell you that you did a good job.
Aw, shucks.
We’re forever in your debt, Ellie dearie.
Keep up the good work, Ellie!
You got this.
I'll try my best, so that the other villagers can return.
Try using the [em1]Furnishing Clock[/em1] beside the [em1]recording notebook[/em1]. Firstly, [em1]place[/em1] the [em1]furniture[/em1] that Kyla's provided.
Let’s take a look on the second floor.
Let’s check out the workshop in the basement.
Let’s talk to that strange lizard.
First, let’s pick up all the scattered furniture.
Whoa, there really is a room!
What a waste to leave it like this. Let's decorate this part too.
It's always like this at the beginning...
Wow, there's a room here too.
Don't make a mess just because you've got lots of rooms.
I'll doll the place up, just you wait!
Someone's at the door. Go downstairs to check it out.
Over there, I think someone came.
Wow. You're right.
Let's go to the [em1]Witch's House[/em1].
I should ask the people closest to me before going further.
Take a look at that giant prickly vine.
I think something fell off just now.
You should pick up the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Encyclopedia", "MoonFlower_Name"))].
Pick up two of them while you're at it.
We can't just leave.
Let's look around a bit more.
Let’s go through the door where a bridge has appeared.
Let’s pick up the floating object.
Let's talk with Enite!
Great, now we've got all the materials for the bricks.
Let's head back to Kyla.
Good morning, Rubrum.
Good morning, Ellie!
Now you aren't even surprised anymore.
I was thinking that you would be here any minute, Rubrum.
Work on Vinch's house is nearly done.
That's right. And we've got a gift for you today.
A gift? For me?
Yes! Here, take it!
This... Is this me? Did you draw this, Rubrum?
Yes! I used the crayons Vinch gave me.
He gave them to me before he left and I couldn't bear to use them.
But you brought Vinch back home, Ellie!
So I used the crayons to draw a picture of you.
This is amazing, it's the spitting image of me!
Hehe, let's go! They said everyone was gathering.
Great, let's go together then!
Hurry, everyone's just arrived too.
Wow, what's all this? There are so many of them.
They are paints.
Why are the paints lying around?
Because I make my own paints, and they filled the place before I noticed.
It's a bit messy, so watch where you step.
Should I start off the introductions?
Hello, you must be the new witch in the village.
Oh, hello. You must be Vinch.
Yes, I'm Vinch and I'm an artist. Pleased to meet you.
I'm Ellie. Nice to meet you too!
I heard it was all thanks to you that I could come back to the village, Ellie. Thank you.
It was nothing, really.
Ms. Witch here is very talented!
That's right! No matter what it is, Ellie always delivers.
It's been so long, can you still do that trick, Vinch?
Make that nice sound with your hand, like a bell.
You mean the lyre? There are so many people around. It feels a little embarrassing...
If it's a musical instrument performance, I want to hear it.
I'd like to hear it too, it's not everyday we get a chance to.
Hmm... Then I'll play just a small piece. Like Enite said, I don't get to do this all the time,
But don't laugh at me if it isn't any good.
<shake>Too late, witch!</shake>
The early bird gets the worm!
<shake>And the early explorer gets the treasure!</shake>
Whatever are you talking about?
Hello, Rubrum.
Um, this person is...
<shake>I'm Rex!</shake> Not "this person"!
Sorry, Ellie. He ran over when I came to get you.
<shake>Hahaha.</shake> We're having a party, can't let you have all the fun, kid.
So I've come to see the witch for myself!
Ellie!
What?
It's Ellie, Ellie Blueriver!
Oh, alright, Ellie! <shake>Hurry up and welcome us then!</shake>
Arin is waiting for you too!
Arin? Who's that?
Hm? Has no one told you? Another person came with me, and that's Arin.
So you're saying two people are replacing Brad?
Yes! The library can't function without Arin!
Now's not the time for idle chitchat, let's go! <shake>Let's hold a welcome party first!</shake>
Urgh, my eardrums...
Feels as though Rex's got the rumbling of a whole train inside him...
Hm? Why are you here too, Arden?
No thanks to that redhead over there. He banged on my door at the crack of dawn.
We're going to be living in the same village after all. Got to say hello, right?
Sorry... Once he gets worked up, not even me can stop him...
Wahaha! Pleased to meet all of you!
I'm Rex! Edward Rex Eastchip! Just call me Rex!
Hello... I'm Arin.
The locals recommended this place to us...
Are you an explorer, Rex?
Yes! I'm a rising star in explorer circles!
Little kid over there, what was your name again, Rubrub? Are you interested in exploration? Come see me anytime!
My name's Rubrum.
We sure have a very... lively person here.
Welcome, I'm Enite, the chief of this village.
If you encounter any difficulties, or have any questions about life here, please let me know.
What a great village! I love it already.
I'm glad to hear that.
We're not even villagers here... Thank you for welcoming us.
Honestly, that person said he could not come and I was getting worried.
Who would have thought he would send such an interesting young man instead.
If Rex is an explorer, are you also an explorer?
Oh, I haven't had the chance to introduce myself... I'm a librarian.
If you have any books you'd like to read, come to the library... Though I may not be much help...
Here, let's round off the introductions. Since this is a welcome party, let's get things fired up!
<wave>Everyone, take one of these.</wave>
Is this a... paper cracker?
Enite and Rubrum told me that this was what you used to welcome returning villagers.
Though we're not returners, we hope we can experience the same welcome ceremony too!
The village is going to be a much more bustling place, that's for sure.
More things to do too, haha!
<shake>I'm going to become a great explorer someday!</shake>
I was wondering what to do with all those valuable books Brad had collected. I suppose I can hand it to Arin for safekeeping now.
Yes... I'm researching forgotten languages and ancient tongues.
If you would like to know about [em1]things to do with linguistics[/em1]... Please come to me.
I said there would be two people attending... Looks like my letter didn't get here in time...
Though this may have come rather suddenly for you... I hope we'll get along.
Though I'm a bit surprised by the fact there are two of you, you've come to the right place, Arin.
More people joining our village is something to be happy about, don't worry. We are all glad to see you.
Hm, Enite?
Did you sleep well, Ellie? There's a nice breeze outside today too.
Hello Ellie! The wind feels great!
Why have you come to see me together?
Alvin's back.
I've been sending Rubrum here alone all the time, and I thought I'd come with him this time.
Ellie, before you came, I never imagined the village would grow so much in my wildest dreams.
I'm a bit excited. It feels like the day before going on an outing, when I was small.
Granny, are we going on an outing?
Not right now, maybe next time?
It will be nice if you can come with us too, Ellie.
Sure, I'm craving the pies you make, Enite!
Apple pie for me!
Alright, alright. We can't only have pies. I'll make whatever both of you want to eat.
Alvin's back. Let's go and meet him.
C'mon, let's go already!
Honestly, I'm just an old man. There's no need to get everyone here so early to meet me.
Welcome back, Alvin. You look like you're in the pink of health. That's great news.
Goodness, Enite. I've been away for so long and you haven't changed at all.
It must be thanks to you that the village was rebuilt so nicely. I'm so happy to see you again.
I'm not the one you should be saying that to, but our Ellie here.
Ahem, good day. I'm Ellie Blueriver, the apprentice witch at the Witch's House in Wisteria.
Oh! You must be the witch they mentioned in the letters. An honor to meet you.
May I ask what the name of the great witch who saved our village is?
Oh, Enite's always lavished praise on you in her letters, Ms. Witch. I've been dying of curiosity.
I see many familiar faces too. I'm very pleased to meet everyone again.
And new faces too. Seems that apart from the repairs, something else has happened in the village.
I'm Alvin, and I run a [em1]sundries store[/em1].
Alvin's sundries store is always full of surprises.
You better sell good stuff around like you did before. Even better if you can stock my stuff, haha!
One can tell a person's taste from the smallest details.
One more good place to go in the village.
Yes, that's right. We don't get together like this often. It would be a pity if we all just went off now.
Let me show you something from my collection.
Looks like we'll still need to get rid of the prickly vines first.
The prickly vines seem to connect to the cave.
If we reach that cave, we should be able to get to [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))].
Then the prickly vine core should be at [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))].
Wow, just the sound of the name [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))] alone makes my heart beat faster.
Tell me when you've gotten rid of the prickly vines.
I'll help you restore houses again.
If you need help, all you have to do is say the word.
I will!
Kyla, do you have a moment?
Haha, of course. What's the matter?
Can you repair the bridge in the village?
The bridge?
Yes, the bridge near the fountain that leads to the bank opposite the village.
Oh, yes. The people near the fountain have all come back.
You've been busy as a bee lately! Haha!
Of course! I'm giving it my all.
Now it's time to get the people on the other side of the bridge home,
before I search for leads on Lisa in [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))].
That's right, there's a road that leads to [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))] on the other side of the river.
Hm, very good. But...
What is it?
Oh, nothing. It's just that the bridge is a little unique.
Repairing it may be a little troublesome.
Oh, really? But it doesn't look like it!
What's special about it?
Some of the bricks in the bridge are with special powers.
Only by using the original bricks can we repair the bridge successfully.
So if we're missing those bricks, we can't fix it!
No one should have touched the bridge after it was broken. The bits of the bridge should be in the area.
That's fortunate.
So don't worry too much, haha!
Then let's go take a look right away!
It's dark outside, not good for working.
Come again tomorrow during the day, okay?
Yes, I'll be sure to do that!
Hm...
Uh... we seem to be missing quite a few bricks...
Mmhm...
We seem to be short of bricks here, and here! Kyla!
Haha, sure looks like it.
Then what do we do now? Does that mean we can't repair this bridge?
Let me think.
I've seen these bricks.
Really?
Yes, they're household bricks.
Household?
This is a kind of brick that doesn't need adhesive to stick together tightly.
I don't know the details.
Kyla, can you make household bricks too?
Not really. That's out of my scope. I don't know how to make that.
So, then...
It's time for The Guide to shine then.
Virgil? Do you know how to make household bricks?
No.
Then pipe down, will you? We're discussing something important.
But I can create something to that effect.
We just need things that possess an affinity with others to make bricks out of.
In that case, even if it's not household bricks, they should have a similar effect.
Have you forgotten when Aria was repairing her roof?
Oh, the one that was plugged with Dad's socks.
I was wondering what on earth you were babbling about.
Then what do we need to do?
Hm... Because this is Wisteria's bridge. It needs things that encapsulate affinity between the residents of Wisteria.
So we can use that to fire some bricks and that'll work?
Yes, that's right. But you're not a pro at this, will it be okay?
Haha! Though I'm no professional, firing a few bricks is no problem.
I used to do all kinds of things.
You're amazing.
Then will you go gather some materials from the villagers, Ms. Witch?
Treasured items filled with affinity will work the best.
A blue flower pot, that's pretty special.
Yes, this is the one you made for me after seeing the color of my eyes.
You even said the blue flower pot would look good with yellow flowers planted in it.
Wow, that's really romantic. Who gave it to you?
Kyla. you did.
Huh?
Wow, that's really...
Kyla! Why have you forgotten about it!
Um, well... That is...
Isn't it enough to give the gift?
You messed up.
Kyla!
Alright, I'm sorry. I forgot.
No, no. I don't mind. As you said, I was very grateful to receive a gift like that.
See?
Alright, alright.
I don't receive many gifts, so I was very happy.
Though it might sound like I'm being nosey, is it really okay to give away something so precious?
It's alright, I'll be happy if it makes the bridge stronger.
I will always remember Kyla's kindness in my heart, so it's alright.
You're an even better person than I thought.
Ahem, ahem... Aren't you interested in the metalworking stall?
I'm managing the flower shop, so I can't help you there, Kyla.
But if you need help, please let me know.
Pity.
Let me go ask the other villagers then.
Bring them to me once you have them all.
You're back? The bricks are finished.
Then all we have to do now is make the repairs, right?
Yes, won't take long. Let's go!
Oh, I'll go get the other villagers.
Because this is the bridge everyone built together.
Great idea. Bring them to the bridge then. I'll repair it.
Ta-dah!
Wow! It's a bridge!
Enite, say a few words.
Kyla, Roy, and Ellie. You've all worked hard to repair the bridge.
And thank you to all the other villagers who so graciously contributed their treasured possessions.
When prickly vines sprouted in the village, I was at my wit's end...
Now that the village has been restored to its former glory, words cannot describe how happy I am.
Thank you so much, Ellie.
That's because the other villagers have helped me so much.
Come say a couple of lines too, Kyla.
Huh? Me?
We've made the bridge strong. Feel free to run about on it! Hehe!
What about you, Roy?
This was my first attempt at repairing a bridge, it's thanks to Kyla's instructions I could do it.
I hope the bridge is now strong enough.
Rubrum, would you like to say something?
Can we run across it now?
What if you get hurt?
The bridge is as tough as Rubrum. It should be fine. Haha!
Then off I go!
Let's try crossing the bridge too.
I haven't been on the opposite side in a long time.
What are you trying to do?
Enite is right. It requires a lot of imagination to call this place a village.
Says who? It's still a [em1]village[/em1] even if there are no houses!
Fine, but it's by no means a village if there are not even [em1]people[/em1].
The people will come back.
How can you be so sure? This is your [em1]first time[/em1] in this village.
If you're just being ridiculous...
No, I definitely heard their mind! The villagers want to come back!
Where did you hear it? You haven't met any of them.
That... I don't know. Maybe I heard it in a [em1]dream[/em1].
So, you're being ridiculous.
You are.
<shake>No, it isn’t!!</shake>
Who would fix the houses even if the prickly vines are removed?
There are only two seniors and one child in the village.
You're right, Virgil.
Correct.
We also need a [em1]carpenter[/em1] to fix the houses.
Have some sleep.
You'll find such a carpenter in your dream.
Stop being sarcastic!
Okay, find a carpenter capable of flying, then.
And they probably need six arms.
Stop being sarcastic, Virgil, okay?
It's the village that Enite has lived in for all of her life.
Other people must be as fond of it as she does.
You know, you also just met Enite for the [em1]first time[/em1].
I can tell even if we met for the first time. My heart was <shake>beating so fast</shake>!
Anyway, the first villager returning has to be a [em1]carpenter[/em1].
It's not spacious,
but it's much cleaner.
Now I can decorate it however I want.
But where has all the furniture gone!?
It seems to be on the floor beside you.
Oh, great.
I need to sort the basic tools first.
Whoa! It's so much bigger!
Kyla expanded it?
That's how houses built by witch craftsmen are.
Remember what happened when you knocked down the walls at home?
Yeah, my room became half its size.
Because you destroyed the walls.
And when they were fixed, Dad's room became bigger all of a sudden.
Houses have feelings, too. I bet it hated you because you destroyed it.
Try to get along with this house this time.
Yes, I'll be friendly to it.
This house will like me.
Look over there. Stairs! I guess there's a second floor now.
Let's [em1]place[/em1] the furniture, then go see the second floor.
Maybe it's because the house is now bigger, but it looks rather bare.
If you'd like to get all your matching furniture in one go, you'll have to leave it to a carpenter witch.
That's going to cost way more Luna Coins than I can afford.
Besides, I don't think your crappy acting's going to cut it with a carpenter witch. She's not going to be as easy to deal with as Diane.
Watch your mouth, you're the crappy one.
I'll buy the furniture bit by bit... The problem is arranging them.
Isn't the answer right in front of you?
What? Oh, yeah! I've got the [em1]Furnishing Clock[/em1]!
Back home, Mom wouldn't let me near it, now I can finally do whatever I want!
Let's use it to place the [em1]furniture Kyla gave me[/em1].
Restoring the houses of the former villagers was just an unrealistic dream for me.
But the day has actually come for us to discuss how to use this area.
Just do it as you see fit. Why do you have to involve me in this?
But, Arden, you're also a member of our village.
Tsk.
Hehe, it's nice to have everyone gather together.
Let's talk about what to build here!
<shake>Me! Me me me!!!</shake>
What about a museum? Used to exhibit the shiny relics! And mysterious objects!
Wow... That must be lots of fun!
...no, wait, shouldn't we first figure out whether there is enough space?
It can be hard, considering the village's size.
Generally speaking... Aren't facilities like parks more common?
A park sounds nice. I can help if you guys want a field of flowers.
But the land here is bumpy. It's probably hard to find the right location.
I want a place for playing!
Looking at the terrain here, I've come up with a good idea.
What do you say, Mister Alvin?
Hmm,
A village with a rich culture can't go without any cultural facility.
Ah, are you talking about an outdoor theater?
That's it, young artist. A giant one can be hard, but a small one may be possible.
A theater... I've only seen them in large cities.
That's nice! Who says a small village can't have one?
What is a theater?
It's large area where you can perform plays, sing and dance.
When I was at the School for Witches... I wasn't a big fan of performing, though...
It must be fun!
Looks like we all agree on building a theater.
If so, it's decided.
<shake>Let's throw another party!</shake>
To build such a grand structure, how can there be no party!
Of course, of course, it's always good to have fun together.
Let's divide the work then.
Kyla, can you do this?
Haha, who else can do this if not me?
Rest assured. I'll build a spectacular stage.
I'll be decorating the stage and cleaning the surroundings.
To throw a party, we must have food.
Arden... and Arin, can you lend a hand too?
Just don't interfere with the operation of my restaurant.
Ah... As long as you don't think I'm too clumsy.
But since we're building a stage, we need performances, right? Like, operas? Or singing?
Well, I believe Mister Alvin can handle this,
since he has a top-class violin.
For your information, I will only play a supporting role at most.
I don't want to be the protagonist.
I want to perform too!
It's time to show off my dazzling talents!
Vinch, you should come too! You have a lyre!
Oh... You're embarrassing me... But since there's nothing else I can do, okay.
So, everyone has got their duty?
Emm... what should I do? I can't play any musical instrument...
Ellie, you can simply enjoy the performance.
You've always been contributing to the village.
We owe you so much, and we want to do something for you.
Yeah, and we now have more hands to do it.
Granny says that to sleep well is as important as to play well! And to eat well!
Just leave it to us, Ellie.
Haha, you're making me shy... But if you insist, okay.
Okay, that's all for the discussion.
When you're ready, let's gather and have the party.
Why does this suddenly feel like a vacation?
How does it feel to have a sweet vacation during your apprenticeship?
Well... so leisurely...
So boring!
You get bored in no time, huh?
I just find waiting boring.
Although they didn't ask me to work, it's not like I'm banned from participating, right?
Since Kyla is responsible for repairing the stage, let me go ask her first.
Kyla should soon finish repairing the stage. Let's go have a look.
Potions are ready.
Tell Enite the party can start now.
We've got a backup plan even if the random ingredient stew fails.
Preparation for the work as the concert emcee is also perfect.
Playing the trumpet alone is kind of embarrassing...
Alone? No way, you've got me here. Just play with my accompaniment however you like.
Go ahead. I want to hear it too.
Didn't you make deafening noises in front of the restaurant every day? What was it for if you don't play now?
Okay... Here I go, hehe.
By the way, why is Rubrum so quite?
I've been curious. Didn't you practice hard for the parade?
Now, it's [em1]Rex and Arin[/em1]'s turn. Please come with me, Rubrum.
Not everyone has arrived yet!
Now, let the concert begin.
Ahem, dear villagers of Wisteria,
good evening. I'm Ellie Blueriver, your emcee tonight.
Hehe, Ellie looks quite professional.
Cool, Ellie.
She's not bad at imitating.
To celebrate the return of the villagers and the restoration of some facilities in the village,
we've decided to build this stage and hold this concert.
Let's greet the villagers performing tonight with applause!
Time for the Attention Potion!
That was sooo... amazing.
It was like a dream.
Hmm, it was worth listening.
Enite is right. It was a marvelous performance.
Hehe, I was a bit nervous, but I had fun.
Haha, I think I'm actually quite talented.
It's been a long time since I played with someone else like this.
Wahaha! How was my flute? I believe even birds passing by were impressed!
This experience is completely new for me...
The performance was good enough. At least Ms. Witch can be proud of us.
Now it's time for the random ingredient stew! Everyone should toss their ingredient into the pot!
Arden! Please do the preparation!
So much trouble.
Everyone, like I said before, you just need to put your ingredients in.
It won't go wrong, right? I hope so...
Okay, they are all cooked. We can eat now.
Please... First principal of the School for Witches, Dad, Mom, please bless the stew and ensure it's tasty.
<shake>Hmm!</shake>
Arden has prepared the basic stock. You can now add your ingredients one by one.
A bit of sweetness will boost the taste. I've brought sliced apples and peaches.
I like sweet food! I'll add some colorful and lovely candies!
How can a dish have no meat in it? This is meat I use at the restaurant.
I've brought dried sardines.
The spicier, the better! I'll add a great deal of peppers, and also a great deal of preserved meat!
Well... I've only got crusty bread at home, so I'll add some crusty bread and cheese.
I've brought red wine. It's simple, but I bet it suits this occasion the most.
I've brought catchup! It'll absolutely add to the taste!
I've got pickled green gage plums. They improve digestion.
That's... not smooth at all.
Told you that this plan was doomed.
Ellie, what have you brought?
Huh? Since... since I'm a witch, of course I've brought a potion!
Don't tell me that it's a potion that will make any food delicious.
<shake>Cer-cer-certainly not!</shake> This is just a luck potion.
<wave>I, I'll do this!</wave>
Hmm? What did you say?
<shake>Haha! I didn't say anything!</shake> Wow, I can't wait to eat this!
Here lies Ellie Blueriver, aged sixteen...
Hey, don't treat me like I'm dead! Got it? <shake>Ah!</shake> It's gonna be alright. I'm familiar with that smell.
It's a success...
Is it the nasty taste in your memory?
It's the best memory for this moment.
I should ask the others what they think.
How should I put this... This taste is hard to describe.
What do you say, Virgil? Do you want to try it?
I will never break my vow.
Indeed, any ingredient will taste nice when added to the basic stock.
But why does the taste feel so familiar?
Is it because there are too many other ingredients? I added so many peppers, but it doesn't taste hot at all.
Yo, Ellie, have you tried this mess of a stew?
It tastes messy?
Ah, isn't that its name? It doesn't taste messy though.
The first time I learned about this plan, I thought it was gonna be a gross dish.
But it actually turned out interesting. I guess we can cook it from time to time.
My beef stew is much better than this,
but this is edible.
Well, Ms. Witch, since ancient times, food has been divided into simple meals and art pieces.
Now I know that you're a fan of pranks.
Does that mean... passing by the skin of my teeth?
It's probably hard to meet the taste of adults.
Red wine produced in that region is of good quality.
Oh, you are an expert in this area. If you want to purchase some for your restaurant, I can be your middleman.
But that blacksmith is the only drinker in this village.
Hey, Mister Alvin, please do stock this wine. I want to drink it.
Now you remember to be polite.
Haha, in such a small village, doesn't too much politeness feel cold?
I love beer more than red wine, but I won't say no to any alcohol as long as it is good.
You won't look good when intoxicated.
You don't understand, sir, that's the fun part of drinking.
Beef stew tastes better than alcohol.
What about we switch to another dish after finishing this?
You want your usual drinking snack?
Oh yes, that will do. I love Arden's Restaurant, haha!
Mister Alvin, what about you? You mustn't think about escaping such a situation. You should learn to enjoy it.
Alright, but I'll bring my own alcohol.
<wave>Whoa, it's so good.</wave>
It tastes like what my husband and I once ate at a street stand.
The taste is quite interesting. Ah, Ellie.
Have you tried this? It's such a unique taste.
My helping is full of candies. It's so crunchy and fun.
And Arden filled my bowl with meat!
Can...Candies, that's great.
I've tried it too. The taste is not bad, right?
The taste is attractive because it doesn't seem to belong to healthy food.
Can I really take that as a compliment?
Ellie, you've really brought me an interesting experience.
Ellie is the best after all!
Are you having meals regularly?
Sure, I make sure I eat at least one meal a day.
Just one? That's not enough. Young people especially need to eat at the right time.
Exactly! Your bones will rot if you don't eat properly!
Haha, but I never forget to eat the pies you give me.
Enite, your pies are super good. I always enjoy them.
You like fruits, right? I'll pick some for you from the forests from time to time.
I'll go with you! I'm skilled at picking fruits!
Tell me whenever you want some. I can bake pies and bread for you.
Vinch, your house makes me dizzy, and there's a pungent smell.
It's because I also draw at home.
Looks like you've been busy drawing for as long as you can remember.
Shall I clean your house for you?
Thank you, but I'm good. I do clean it regularly, to be honest.
Rubrum and I will be playing in the garden and elsewhere. Don't worry.
It's tasty. I didn't expect it to be so good, since we just tossed in random ingredients.
This is just my presumption, but Ellie must have done something!
But even if you have, it's curious! We wouldn't get to taste such a dish elsewhere! <shake>WAHAHA!</shake>
If we were at the mansion... we would have been scolded for playing with food.
Did you guys enjoy it?
Ellie... To be honest, such a dish is unheard of. It is too... unique.
I like such free-style stuff! Tell us, Ellie, you did something with that potion, right?
<shake>Wh-wh-what could I have done?</shake> Anyway, I was allowed to add whatever ingredient I wanted!
It reminds me of something. I've had such a stew before, where people also tossed in whatever they had at hand.
Ah, I see! Roy, you said you were in the army, right?
The food there... must be awful.
Back then, we called that dish dog food. It looked almost inedible.
Ah, I'm not saying that this random ingredient stew is dog food.
Haha... as long as you guys like it.
You two are childhood friends, right?
Yes, we've known each other since we were little!
How I envy you. I've been moving around a lot, so I didn't grow up beside any particular friend.
But I do have met many nice people here in Wisteria.
Not only childhood friends are called friends.
Roy, you can also be my friend. Right, Arin?
A friend of Rex's... is also a friend of mine.
That means two more friends for me!
Wow, so this is the dish you cooked? It's impressive!
I'm flattered.
I have confidence in roasting meat, at least!
I... can make pickled fruits and jam at most. I'm hardly making any progress in cooking...
That makes Enite's pies the delicacies we can't do without, wahaha!
Enite's pies are really great. I love them too.
I want to know what your dishes taste like too! Could you have me over sometime?
I will. And I want to read. Can I visit the library?
Sure... Anytime.
Go chat with Enite, and enter the next section of the party.
[lua(GetLocalizedString("Choice", "Yes"))]
[lua(GetLocalizedString("Choice", "No"))]
Enite, it's your turn now.
Hehe, time surely flew when I was busy chatting.
Arin, and Roy, could you lend me a hand?
Yes...
Sure, Enite.
Then, we've got only one household left!
One household? Which one are you talking about?
Emm... Aren't there more ruins down here?
Someone must have lived there as well.
That place has long been unoccupied.
It had been empty for a long time even before prickly vines started to grow.
Although there was a house, it was idle.
The swing at the gate was fun to play with, though...
A swing... Was it a family with a child?
Not a child my age! But there was an old lady Granny's age!
Ah, I remember her too. She said that her grandchildren would visit from time to time, so she asked me to make a swing.
Can't we bring her back anymore?
She moved away to live with her children, so she probably won't come back.
She had left this land at our disposal... But we haven't figured out how to use it, so we've left it idle.
Which means this plot of land is ownerless!
Yeah... What about building a fountain or something?
You mean a public facility?
Good idea. Since everyone is here, you can voice any suggestion you have.
Oh, what is this?
Was it here before?
It has been left in the corner of the workshop, hasn't it?
Hmm... It looks somehow familiar. Where have I seen such a thing?
Ah~ Now I remember! This is an [em1]Incubator[/em1]!
I've seen it in Mom's workshop.
Oh yeah, you broke that one and Aria kicked you out of her workshop.
What a shame I don't know what it's for.
All that I know is its name, since Mom told Dad that "Ellie destroyed the Incubator!"
This is probably the one Lisa used?
I can finally solve the problem that's been troubling me for days!
Just turn this handle... Eyyy!
Eyyy! <shake>Huh?</shake> Why's it not moving?!
It turns out that your second Incubator has followed the footsteps of the first.
It hasn't! It must have been broken from the beginning!
But I know a method that fixes everything.
<shake>Eyyy!</shake> Taste this!
My, my, are you going to smash it into pieces?
Please solve problems like a civilized graduate of the School for Witches.
Uhh... I've seen the principal fixing tools like this, though.
Okay. Like a civilized person...? Hmm...
Since it's a witch tool, maybe I should just go ask [em1]Diane[/em1]?
That's right. Solve it peacefully. No violence.
Now, try to decorate your workshop and make it fancy.
The workshop is for processing and crafting, so you must consider work efficiency.
Such as your route across the workshop and space utilization.
That's beyond me. I just need it to look good.
But it seems to be too cramped...
Can't I increase the workshop size?
I don't think you can dig all the way down.
Okay, after I've cleaned this place, I'll go ask Diane.
And I didn't find that lizard I saw on the second floor in the basement.
What do I do then? This place is way too small.
Maybe Witches' Catalogue offers that sort of service.
After all, you can't dig tunnels in the ground just because your workshop is too small.
You need a witch-ish solution.
Ah, before that, pick up [em1]the item dropped down there[/em1].
<shake>WAHAHAHA! </shake>You're so slow, way too slow! You're kept me waiting for centuries!
Rex... Told you to stop running around like that.
Can't you stay put for a bit longer? You lost your patience and rushed over in no time.
I can't wait to show off my talents, but you are being so late!
I've been itchy to play the flute in front of everyone at the welcome party.
I'm a bit nervous... but I hope you enjoy my performance.
Next up is [em1]Vinch[/em1]!
After he heard about the parade... Rex's been on the edge of his seat.
I'm not particularly good... but I can play some simple tunes, so I've tagged along.
Okay, parade restarted!
Okay, I've got a rough idea about the villagers.
Now it's time to go to Enite and decide who to contact first.
Alright, now it's time to decide who's next to return.
Let's go talk to Enite!
Now that we've decided the next one to return.
Hurry up and talk to Enite.
Now that the Witch's House is repaired, I should repair the village bridge.
I need to ask Kyla about this too.
Talk to [em1]Diane[/em1] first.
Virgil!
Hold on, let me guess.
Huh? Guess what?
Did a goddess dressed in white come to tell you how you were the chosen warrior?
Uh, kinda...
So original...
But Virgil, this is different.
Different as in, the main character is a bit lacking in some aspects?
This is my story.
It’s not about some chosen warrior from your typical fairy tale.
And so you’ve decided to be the heroine of this tale as old as time?
It’s so I can make everyone happy.
"O Witch, help those in your reach," is how it goes, right?
After all, the heroine always goes on fun adventures.
Besides, it's so that I can graduate from school and become a true witch.
Also, White Cat God said something... about the village.
This is why heroes must make choices carefully.
I heard it in my dream!
The road above the village is open now.
Let's go there.
Well...
Hmm...
Why are you idling with collected items in your hands?
I'm wondering whether to juice them or dry them.
Didn't you learn it at school?
You know what I'm worst at, Virgil.
Staying quiet and still?
Besides that!
How can I possibly remember how to process all those bugs, herbs, fur and toe nails.
And it's not like there's any pattern!
So, what is it?
Hmmm... I can't recall. It should be either [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Manufacture_Extractor"))] or [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Manufacture_Roaster"))].
Ah, I remember now. It's [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Manufacture_Kneader"))][/em1]!
Ah, the thing that clunks as loudly as hell.
[em1]Diane[/em1] sells work tools. I'll go ask her.
But I didn't see any in the workshop...
[lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "MoonFlower_Collect_Name"))] can only be collected at night.
Wait until night and use [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "SunlightPotion_Name"))][/em1]?
Use [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "SunlightPotion_Name"))][/em1] right now?
[em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "SunlightPotion_Name"))][/em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Choice", "NotHaveItem"))]
It smells really good...
Wipe your drool.
It's been a long time since I last had this.
I missed this smell.
Sweet things make my mouth feel gross, but this is delicious. Hahaha.
Maybe Enite just has the magic touch?
A giant pie! A giant pie!
Thank you, Enite!
Did everyone get a slice?
Have lots, everyone. Eat well, be well!
It's time to wrap up today so we're ready for tomorrow.
I would like to thank everyone again.
Especially Ellie. It's been happy times only since you came.
You're the lucky charm of this village.
I really like Ellie, too!
If it wasn’t for Ellie, I wouldn’t have returned.
Thank you for helping me return.
Great work, Ellie.
Hmm.
Let's all keep doing our best!
By the way, have you forgotten something?
What? I should look for the prickly vine core, right? I haven't forgotten.
I may not look attentive, but I know what I'm doing~
I am creating a path to the prickly vine.
I mean, the thing for removing the core.
[lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "MoonTear_Name"))].
You really forgot?
I, <wave>I didn't~</wave> I was about to mention that.
Um, let's see. Finding [lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "MoonFlower_Collect_Name"))]s is easy. Then I just need to buy the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "SunlightPotion_Name"))] recipe.
The problem is the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "SacredWater_Water_Name"))][/em1]...
There's some in the temple.
Oh, right! I'll just get it from the temple!
I'll ask the Cat Gods just in case!
Speaking of which, can you just fetch water from the temple as you wish?
Then it wouldn't have been sold at 1500 Luna Coins.
Maybe you'll have to offer something super precious in exchange.
No way... The Cat Gods can't be that mean.
Oh, these are the one!
These are the flowers Enite talked about. Pick some and take them to [em1]Enite[/em1].
Huh? It's a notebook?
Well, I know I shouldn't read someone's notebook without permission... but I can't know who the owner is if I don't, right?
Save the first sentence if you really think so.
Hehe, let's have a look.
Meh, I thought I finally discovered something interesting.
There seems to be something between the next pages.
Hm? Oh! It's an envelope. And it's been processed to endure wear.
I can feel something inside. I'll tear the top apart...
Oh no... What a pity. The letters are blurry.
It's a letter! Let's read it!
Dear Tice,
Tice, my dear younger brother, this place is no longer what it used to be.
The liveliness when the witch swelled the mushroom for me the first time has gone.
The villagers left one after another. Only a few people are still around.
Recently, I noticed that I just can't help [em1]coughing[/em1].
It's probably time to go home.
I hope we can soon reunite at home. I'll write again.
Oh...
So the mushroom was really swelled by a witch. I was right.
A witch that can change the size of plants. Do you know anyone like that?
Well... According to the letter, the locals were probably quite happy when the mushroom became large?
Why did they all leave then?
Whatever the cause was, it couldn't be anything good.
Hmm... This is strange.
Let's keep looking for tea.
Got the tea. Let's get it to Enite first.
Woohoo! The [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "SunlightPotion_Name"))][/em1] is ready!
Wait until night and go to the summit?
When you're ready take the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "SunlightPotion_Name"))][/em1] to the [em1]top of the hill in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_GreenForest"))][/em1].
Should we go up the mountain now?
Why do the flowers feel smaller?
One single tree doesn't produce so many [lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "MoonFlower_Collect_Name"))]s in the first place.
And you collected once not a long time ago.
Sigh, I wanted one more this time.
I'll just pick the ones dropped earlier.
Alright, let's go to the dispensary now.
I should make [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "MoonTear_Name"))][/em1].
Now all I have to do is remove the nucleus.
Now I must find the nucleus.
We can use this to attach the doll's arm.
Collect the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "FallenCotton_Name"))] and give it to the strange creature that won't stop crying.
Take the collected [lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "FallenCotton_Name"))] and give it to the strange creature that won't stop crying.
Aha, problem solved.
<wave>Sticky~ Sticky~ Potion on my hand~ Grab the slippery with ease~</wave>
What in the world is that song?
It's my song of celebration.
Aw, AWWWW! You saw that, Virgil? I was flying!
It was a high jump, so it felt like flying.
I haven't been so excited since I rode on the witch's broom.
I feel dizzy. Calm down and don't do it too much.
Wow, this is amazing.
This is troublesome.
How come? Sniff, there's even a faint aroma of flowers. It's nice.
It's hard to find [em1]traces of prickly vines[/em1] if there's water everywhere.
Oops.
Well... but we can find them if we are careful.
Yeah, since they must be around.
Good, we'll be careful then! We'll check every nook and cranny! Target: [em1]traces of prickly vines[/em1]!
You're simple excited about getting a chance to wander around.
<wave>Woahhh</wave> this is exciting!
I almost flew off!
I hate mountain winds!
C'mon, it's just a little scratch on the leather. Don't make a fuss.
The weird smoke has disappeared. We can go now.
Alright, let's go!
What do we need to do?
Just like [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_GreenForest"))].
First, track the prickly vines to find the prickly vine core, and destroy it.
Then, tell Kyla. After she finishes building the house, we can get the villager back.
Sounds pretty easy on paper.
Okay, let's go! Off to [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))]!
The [em1]prickly vine seems to be going upwards[/em1].
Can I climb this wall? I can't see anywhere to hold on to...
There is a hole on the side though.
Hole?
Hmm... It looks about the same size as the [em1]board[/em1] in the mushroom from before.
But the board is missing and even the [em1]spring[/em1] has fallen off.
Have the parts fallen off due to wear and tear?
I think they are still in the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Map", "RainbowForest_Basin"))][/em1], unless they have feet.
Can you fix it?
I just need to insert the parts. It's easy.
I'll find the [em1]board[/em1] and [em1]spring[/em1].
I once found a [em1]spring[/em1] here.
I'll insert the [em1]spring[/em1] here and go find the [em1]board[/em1].
Good, the spring is attached.
Now, I just need to place the board over it.
Done! Let me try standing on it.
There seems to be something on that bridge!
A [em1]piece of wood[/em1]... Is it the [em1]wood plaque[/em1] in the letter of Honey Bear's companion?
I'll check it out.
Oh! We're here!
And we can get down now!
I'll swim to my heart's content.
Alright, let's go on looking for the [em1]prickly vine core[/em1]!
Woah... Is that a cloud? Or smoke? It's vast.
It's so foggy. I can't see the other side.
The prickly vine trace is still going [em1]up[/em1].
Hmm, then I guess I can only go from there.
Nothing seems to be in the way...
A bit of smoke is nothing, and it's not a restricted zone.
Let's go!
Ah... It looks upset.
It keeps crying.
It probably won't cheer up unless we find the [em1]doll[/em1].
It will only stop crying if we [em1]repair the doll[/em1]?
I think so.
Sad things always linger on for a long time.
I need [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "MoonTear_Name"))][/em1] to remove it.
Use [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "MoonTear_Name"))][/em1]?
Here...
It looks like a campsite.
It... doesn't look like it's been visited.
It has apparently been abandoned for some time.
Would Lisa have been here before?
We can't say this is Lisa's camp just yet.
Okay, let's look around first.
The books are scattered around.
Special Means To Tend to a Witch Garden, Good Soil and Bad Soil, On Witch Gardens...
They are all books about witch gardens.
And Lisa happens to be from the Whitegarden family.
Nice theory.
And... wait! This note...
"The first dew of spring, a red Bluemoon Butterfly, the fourth dawn of summer..."
I think I've read about this somewhere...
Must have seen it.
Wait, I've read this. Is this from a book on the bookshelf at Witch's House?!
The method of splicing plants?
It is! This note is cited from that book.
Why is this book here?
So, the owner of this camp is also interested in plant splicing.
Just like Lisa? Really?
Don't jump to conclusion. It will limit your imagination.
Keep looking and you'll find out.
Right... Well, let's look elsewhere!
Wait, there seems to be something under the book.
I've looked around this place.
This portable witch's pot is cute.
Virgil! This is made by the [lua(GetLocalizedString("InteriorPropTheme", "BasementBasic"))]!
Just like the one at the Witch's House.
Right!
But that doesn't mean anything. The Blue Lightning Workshop is popular.
That's true but...
It still has a bit of trace on it.
Hmm... is this the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "CoughCandy_Name"))]?
Was she not feeling well?
Maybe a villager asked her to bring it.
Let's go look somewhere else.
Oh, wait a minute. There's something under the pot.
Indeed. That might be the case.
But... Wait a minute.
Is this a small garden?
Why does she have to come to the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))] to grow plants?
Some plants can only grow in special environments.
Was she trying to grow collected items of the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))]?
Maybe.
Er... Well, let's look elsewhere.
Hold on. There's something glowing there.
Wow, are these mushrooms?
They are giants of mushrooms.
I've never seen mushrooms [em1]this big[/em1] even in the incubation room of School for Witches.
The incubation room itself wasn't that spacious after all.
I wonder if any magical creature lives in it.
Or maybe there's a path in it, leading to another forest...
Stop it, stop it. Do you think we're in a romantic fairy tale?
It's okay. I will enjoy it even if it is a horror story!
Okay, let's keep following the [em1]prickly vines[/em1], and explore the surroundings.
I found something interesting!
Who made them?
They are old, but they are systematic.
With such a big scale, it can probably hold a large crowd...
The weird thing is, I don't see anyone.
Maybe they're just away for now.
No. The instruments haven't been maintained for a while.
So, either this place is uninhabited... or it has only a few residents.
Besides, the villagers never mentioned it.
It's weird. Why do you feel so smart today.
You didn't eat any poisonous mushroom when I wasn't watching, did you?
I've been to nowhere and eaten nothing, okay?!
Okay then...
There must be something here. My instinct keeps sounding the alarm!
It can be... a forgotten ancient civilization, or...
A village that disappeared all of a sudden due to triggering a forbidden spell...
I was mistaken. You're just your usual foolish self. Get going.
Uncover the hidden truth!
Don't forget that we are after the [em1]prickly vine core[/em1].
Oh, there's something written here.
Let's see... [em1]Earthgem Shroom Gathering Ground[/em1].
Huh? Earthgem Shroom? Is it the Earthgem Shroom I know?
Really? Has the sign been replaced?
Are Earthgem Shrooms this big? No way!
Sometimes, impossible things can happen.
Maybe it's just a sudden mutation, though...
Or a modified breed...
Come to think of it, Sally did something similar at school.
She wanted to grow a giant apple on the apple tree to eat.
But it became so huge that the branch snapped before the fruit was ripe...
So, a witch could have caused this.
Maybe Lisa is the very witch.
What? No way. What is the point of cultivating mushrooms?
Since this mushroom is so expensive, she could have been trying to rake in a fortune with it.
We'd better find the other things first.
After all, Lisa was studying plants too.
Why don't you say that she was dreaming about building a mushroom garden?
Lisa studied vines. It has nothing to do with mushrooms.
Wait, what about this? She tried to combine the traits of mushrooms and vines, but failed!
Actually, I've been having this strange feeling.
You're hungry?
No, it's not about myself!
I mean the inside of the mushroom. Isn't it too tidy?
Although most of the tools are old, they aren't badly damaged.
It feels more like they abandoned this place on purpose, instead of having to do so, right?
Well, it really is not messy.
At first, I thought the people here were forced to leave because of monsters or something.
Just like the prickly vines in the village.
But... after looking around, I thought it wasn't the case.
Let's forget about those people for now.
Remove the prickly vine core first.
It's not like the place itself will disappear. We can investigate it later.
Uh... You're right. Restoring the village is our top priority.
There are many entrances here too. Have a close look first.
What's that?
Looks like a clump of cotton.
There are more scattered around.
Seems like we've got a scatterbrain here too.
The road from the village is blocked...
So, does it belong to people who live here?
Be careful. We don't know what kind of person they might be.
If we follow this trail, we should find out, right?
You really didn't listen, did you?
Ugh... My hands are getting dirty.
And what's that smell? It's disgusting, I'm gonna puke.
Holding it will make your hands smell like a sewer for three days straight.
That's horrifying...
You might end up throwing up every time you eat bread.
If only there was [em1]a magic potion that can clean it without getting myself dirty[/em1].
On closer inspection, this doll is actually quite cute.
It looks a lot like that strange cub, doesn't it?
I don't know. They both having two eyes indeed.
Ugh, you're so blunt.
Let's hurry and give it back to the cub.
See that, Virgil? Water instantly cleaned this doll.
Water is indeed the most effective way against dirt.
Alright, now let's take the doll and go find that [em1]strange creature[/em1].
Oh~ It's clean now~
Do stop throwing potions around without thinking.
But it was too dirty and stinky.
Ah, the doll's arm has been torn off.
It has the same color as the one beside the weird guy.
So this is probably its doll.
Yeah, but whose doll is this?
It's missing an arm. Maybe it's abandoned?
Hmm... Let's take it with us. Its owner may be looking for it.
Hey, what is this?
Ah! <shake>I got it!</shake> That invisible wall that prevented us from entering [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Map", "RainbowForest_Plateau"))][/em1]!
Are they related?
Come to think of it, it was probably a witch barrier.
Well, I once blew up the device on the no-entering door at the principal's office.
No one would repair this place for you if you destroy it.
Can't we just destroy it?
It will end your adventure, Ellie.
Alright, I understand. I must solve it in a witch's way, right?
I'll have a closer look at it. I'm a witch of words.
Ah! There's a similar decoration on the [em1]witch barrier[/em1].
In that case, this may be a [em1]witch barrier generator[/em1].
I sensed similar magic flow nearby.
I need to observe surrounding devices carefully, and try to [em1]touch[/em1] them.
A device? It looks complicated...
I sense magic here.
Right? And it's a large amount of it.
A device should affect a [em1]huge[/em1] area if it uses so much magic...
Emm... I feel a bit confused...
There're [em1]patterns[/em1] carved in the shards. Let's look into them.
A [em1]witch barrier[/em1], huh...
Light from the [em1]witch barrier connection device[/em1] is shining this way!
It's the [em1]same device[/em1] as in the red mushroom.
It should be activated in the same way. Let's have a close look.
<shake>Eek~</shake> The bird cage is so slippery.
Told you to exercise more.
That's not the point! It has some slippery stuff on it.
My hands keep slipping no matter how hard I try.
What about using a [lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "GlueCandy_Name"))]?
No witch would stick their hands on a bird cage. That would be ridiculous.
I need to come up with a way to [em1]hold on to[/em1] a slippery bird cage.
Too slippery.
Wash it with water?
It doesn't help.
Is this how it's supposed to be?
You have no clue?
Well~ I got here, but I'm not confident.
Let me see if there are other [em1]similar devices[/em1].
And start devices in [em1]other mushrooms[/em1] too.
Phew, this is just a walk in the park.
Go to the road previously blocked?
Sure! Let's find that weird kid!
Because it has got [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Key_BlueTag_Name"))][/em1].
Hm, the [em1]weird kid[/em1] may be that way.
I need to find it.
Shoot, I still can't get to the other side.
There's a mark.
Mark? Hmm...
Can you read it?
I can't! I lack clues!
What were you pondering on then.
I was just trying to figure it out, but I failed.
I'll simply go to wherever I can reach for now.
Oops, why can't I raise it?
It looks hard when you only use one.
Yeah, but there's only one hole.
There are two kinds of fighting.
Say, just charge and strike?
Rely on the variety of techniques... or rely on [em1]size[/em1].
I don't understand a word.
Think it over.
<wave>Great~</wave> It worked!
Now, I can climb up.
I also need to check the [em1]box[/em1] up there.
Ah, what's going on!
Have you been eating too much?
Of course not!
Well, this is the only way to get up there.
The bridge above has also collapsed.
I got all the parts and installed them. What other problem can there be?
I wish I [em1]can jump higher[/em1] by stepping on it.
If you can't fix the board, try fixing the [em1]person on it[/em1].
<shake>Oh man!</shake> I can't get high enough no matter how many times I try.
If brutal force can't solve it, use some brains.
Yeah, the board has defeated me...
I must [em1]change my state[/em1]...?
Hm? This looks just like the place in the Green Forest!
A suspiciously unusual sight, for the second time.
A water tank and a pipe... Is this a hand-held scale? And a water-powered trip-hammer.
If you see a puzzle, you should solve it. It's manner.
Is it for the villagers?
Sure!
What should you do if you see a puzzle, again?
Hey, that doesn't matter.
They are all connected.
If you were so passionate about your schoolwork, you could have graduated summa cum laude.
Did it work? Did something happen?
I’m not sure.
Hmm, since it's related to such a puzzle, it can't be something small, right?
There really was a [em1]giant device[/em1].
Right! Near the [em1]weird smoke on the other side of the lake[/em1]!
Maybe something has changed. Let's check it out.
I got so much cotton.
Are you going to make clothes or something?
I'll keep it. It may become handy.
Your backpack is full of cotton.
Well, it should be enough to fix the doll!
Hasn't the doll lost one arm? It needs cotton to fix.
I've got a whole bag of cotton. It should suffice.
Wow! It's completely different from the Green Forest!
Look, the [em1]prickly vines[/em1] extends there...
There seems to be a path on the other side.
What surprises lie in wait? What interesting creatures call this place home?
Don't forget why we're here in the first place.
We are here in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))] to look for [em1]Lisa[/em1] and the [em1]prickly vine core[/em1], aren't we?
Don't worry. I haven't forgotten my mission.
Okay, forward!
Oh, so this is also the inside of a mushroom.
It doesn't look much different.
Oh, that voice is...
The weird kid.
It's also playing here.
I've been seeing it so often that I've developed affection for it.
Shall I approach it?
You want your face covered with honey again?
No, I'm just curious! About what it's doing.
And I've been concerned about the [em1]key[/em1] it's holding since the first time I saw it.
Hi! What are you doing here!
At least we now know that it's outgoing.
Is it showing off its doll?
My taking the trouble to mend it wasn't for nothing...
<shake>Ah!</shake>
Now you know how much it hurts when you stab me with a needle?
That's not the point! Look, there's a [em1]prickly vine trace[/em1] going towards that door.
And there's a [em1]keyhole[/em1] beside the door lock device!
Did you get so worked up just for the key?
No, no! The weird kid had the key it played with the doll!
And the key had a [em1]blue tag[/em1] on it!
Oh, Ellie II, you're awesome.
Don't give me strange aliases!
Well... To open the door, we must drive that [em1]weird kid[/em1] away.
Beside the doll, it was playing with a [em1]key[/em1], right?
It was holding it already when we first met it.
Shall we just ask it for the key?
We fixed its doll. Maybe it's willing to give us the key.
Let's [em1]talk to[/em1] the weird kid.
The key [em1]tag has the same color[/em1] as the [em1]keyhole in the mushroom[/em1].
It worked?
It worked.
Okay, now I'll turn the device and get out!
Oh! So that's how the inside of the mushroom looks like.
I never thought I would one day enter a mushroom. You'll get to experience everything if you live long enough.
As if you're anywhere near "living long."
But where's the thing in the mushroom that looks like a mesh bag?
It looks old, but it's still usable.
Signs of humans living here too.
I wonder where is everyone...
Could it be... that a mushroom monster showed up?
Please be realistic.
Since there's a huge mushroom, why can't there be mushroom monsters?
By the way, I've been hearing strange noises...
It's that weird guy.
Did you hear any strange noise?
Do you think I'll quit just because you say that?
No, listen carefully. There seems to be someone crying.
Imagine it... what can be in an isolated forest?
<shake>Ee... eep!</shake> You think you can scare me like that? Stop making creepy jokes!
Why are you trembling if you're not scared?
I'm not trembling! It's [lua(GetLocalizedString("Encyclopedia", "Gaga_Name"))] I suppose!
I think this one's scarier.
Looks like it is the one crying.
Seems a bit harsh to comment on someone's appearance like that...
What's the big deal? Right now, the problem is it's crying here and blocking our path.
Virgil, try to be empathetic...
That's really hurtful. Spare me the lecturing.
The [em1]prickly vine marks[/em1] seem to lead in this direction...
Hmm... It's crying so sadly, I don't really want to ask it to move.
Why are you crying? Scattered cotton balls...
Looks like there's something next to it.
Oh... Let's see... An arm? It's an arm from a cotton doll.
Emm, it went on wandering about without noticing this. Did it drop the [em1]doll[/em1] on the way?
Reminds me of when you were little.
You used to carry the doll Aiden made for you everywhere.
Even during baths and meals.
Eventually, the doll became all ragged, and you cried all day.
Was that me? Are you making this up?
Ask Aria if you don't believe me.
Aiden and Aria couldn't get anything done because they were trying to cheer you up all day.
Your crying was so loud and it felt like the house was going to collapse.
Don't exaggerate.
But this story of yours does remind me about...
My dad frequently made dolls for me.
Hmm... To track the [em1]prickly vine marks[/em1], we must follow that path.
The cub needs to move for us to pass.
Let's help it find its lost doll.
By the way, have we seen the doll before?
Oh, stop it! I don't even remember!
Look, the arm's been torn off, and the [em1]cotton[/em1] might have fallen out [em1]elsewhere[/em1].
Let's search for [em1]the cotton[/em1] again.
The cotton we just found seems to have fallen out of the doll.
Better collect it and take it with us.
By the way, have I seen that [em1]fallen doll[/em1] before?
It looks weird.
There's something on the side.
Emm... Is it a [em1]key[/em1]? After losing the doll, it fiddled with the key instead?
Speaking of dolls, didn't we find one earlier?
And the arm is missing.
[em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "HoneyBearDoll_Name"))][/em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Choice", "LetsBringItem"))]
Can't we just get around this crying guy and proceed?
Alright, we can't, I see.
It probably was damaged when carried around, unless its owner enjoys collecting arms.
Hello? Could you show me that thing you've got?
I need that key.
Ah, it's angry.
Because you had nothing for it.
But I mended its doll.
It's not a mouse rescued by Cinderella.
Why would it play with a key?
Wait a minute... Will it give me the key if I get it another toy?
But I don't know it, less what it likes.
There's a pile of random items behind it.
Yeah, this looks like its secret hideout.
You may get a better idea of the weird kid if you investigate the pile.
Hi there~ Here's your companion's doll!
Ah, why is it crying?
It must miss the doll badly.
It reminded it of its companion...?
Now I also miss Jenny and Sally.
I hope their apprenticeships are going well.
It has stopped crying.
Even though it's not the companion, it's a doll left by the companion.
I hope Honey Bear can also feel happiness.
It dropped the key.
Good, I'll get the key!
Analyze info obtained from items around Honey Bear and find [em1]the doll left by Honey Bear[/em1].
I-I won't take it. Don't be angry.
Let's check out the place with the [em1]ladder[/em1] down there.
Investigate the abandoned campsite.
No need to backtrack.
A gate?
[em1]Garden gate[/em1]...?
There's a smell.
Isn't it similar to the one we saw at the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_GreenForest"))]?
They seem to have a lot of secrets.
Hmm, there's a [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "WitchSign"))][/em1] right ahead. I'd better remember this place.
Haha... It did make me a little nervous. How did it sound?
I haven't heard it in so long. The sound's as bright as I remember it.
Wow, that was really nice. Though it's still some way from my flute, not bad.
What a lovely sound.
Vinch's bells are awesome!
It's a lyre, really, Rubrum.
Looks like you're pretty good at performing on instruments.
Not as good as you say, it's just a hobby... Thank you for your kind compliment.
I didn't think it would be such a hit.
Thank you, everyone.
Welcome back.
A young person who dabbles in the arts is hard to find, yes.
Haha, welcome back! If you need anything, just let me know!
Glad to... make your acquaintance...
We're about the same age. I'm sure we'll get along fine.
Welcome back, Vinch. I'm so happy to see you again.
Welcome, Vinch! Let's play together again!
Welcome back to the village!
Haha, thanks. I'll be seeing you around.
Hehe, how interesting.
Hm, though it's a bit small, it's pretty good!
Alright then, time for my marvelous flute performance...
That's enough... Rex. It's too early in the morning. Everyone's... probably still reeling from all this.
What? I thought we were just getting started?
You'll be living in the village from now on. There'll be plenty of chances.
I have to go and prepare to open my shop.
I'll make sure to treat all of you to a recital with my marvelous flute next time.
Haha, I can't believe we've got someone more boisterous than me now.
Though the library here is small, there are plenty of books you can't find or buy elsewhere.
I may have to trouble you frequently in the future.
What are all the noises? What time do you think it is? This is exhausting.
Hahaha... Anyway, welcome, Arin... and Rex of course!
Play nice, everyone.
An explorer! A librarian! That's so cool!
Thank you for letting us stay!
This is repetitive but... thank you for letting us stay.
What do you think? Although this one's not for sale, I have quite a few similar items that are.
I wanted to give a violin performance, but the violin broke on my way here.
I can't believe it. You were just advertising your own wares! I was almost fooled.
If you have lots of antiques... I may be a bit... curious.
Oh, if you have anything that might be helpful for adventuring, I'd like a look.
It's been very well preserved. Looks like something from very long ago... But the exterior's very clean and it sounds good.
Did you make these yourself, Alvin?
I made this myself. But the ones for sale were sourced from reliable merchants or craftsmen.
Why? That music box looks really dainty too.
Well… probably because making and selling it isn’t price-competitive.
I'm getting on in years, so I do look for things to while the time away.
I also thought knitting was a boring hobby when I was a lass, but I enjoy it greatly now.
Yes, just like that. This is just a hobby.
Can I just browse around?
Yes, my sundries store is open to everyone.
Oh and, this is a little gift to mark our reunion.
Hehe, apple flavor! Yummy.
I haven't had this in so long. The peach flavor really shines through.
Oh! Isn't this the candy Grandpa always brought back for me?
Reminds me of the past when I ate so many in one go that the roof of my mouth was skinned! Mine's lemon. It's great!
Oh, those are the candies painted on the tin can holding the sewing kit...
I thought it was filled with candies, and fell for it many times...
It was really famous during my time. Good thing the children these days like it too.
There, I'm really grateful everyone came to welcome me back, but your time is important.
Don't spend more of your time on an old man like me. Hurry along and take care of your own business.
Welcome back, Alvin. It was nice meeting you.
I'm really happy to see you again. Let me know if you ever need help.
Welcome!
I'll hold you to that then.
Okay, the prickly vine core in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))] is finally removed.
Now we can go on with village restoration.
Unfortunately, Lisa is still nowhere to be found.
Come to think of it, it's true.
Hmm, I suppose White Cat God won't lie...
Should we go back to the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))]?
Maybe. Gods don't always tell the truth.
Look, Virgil! A path appeared after the prickly vines over there were gone!
I heard Lisa was there?
Maybe she got caught in growing prickly vines when wandering in the woods?
Let's take a look.
Hmm, chalk...
This is...
It's the witch's chalk! Why is it here?
It's not here.
Not here either.
Found it! The witch's chalk!
Let's look inside the tent.
Should it be used at the tent?
Alright, let's take a look.
Great... It's open.
What, why don't you get in?
What if Lisa's in there?
Just tell her that you're an apprentice witch.
Y-you've got a point. I didn't do anything wrong.
Except for intruding a Witch's House, using the furniture and ingredients there,
being an apprentice witch without a master witch, and making up a master witch.
I suppose I'll be fine. Let's check it out.
Are you serious?
Emergency food... common medicines, tools and a makeshift bed...
Though small, it has everything one needs.
The only problem is that Lisa is not here.
These are enough supplies for us to stay here for a few days.
In a forest? What for?
Well, I didn't see anything worth noting.. Hey wait.
A diary!
Do you think I can skim through it?
That's nothing compared to what you did before.
Good thing it doesn't have a lock or something.
"Spliced Plant Observation Journal－[lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))]"
"Lisa Whitegarden"!
It's written by Lisa Whitegarden!
So, Lisa did make camp here!
Virgil, now you won't deny it anymore, will you?
Alright. This was Lisa's camp.
Go on reading.
She seems to write every day.
Although a method of splicing plants has been discovered, there are many inconveniences.
First, the traits to be inherited can't be predicted. Second, the splicing results in seeds. To check the outcome, one must grow them into plants.
Therefore, I decided to camp in a place suitable for various plants to observe plant growth.
Day 1. The seeds were planted. The soil was mixed according to the family's special recipe. I believe it would germinate soon.
Day 2. The seeds have rotten. For spliced plants, I should be extra careful about the soil type ratio. This time, it's 5:3:3:2.
Well, this part is about seed rotting and soil type ratios. Skip.
Day 5. It finally sprouted. The ratio of soil types is 3:2:5:3.
Well, the rest is about plant observations. Nothing special.
Ah, this is it.
Day 10. The plants were finally mature enough for traits to manifest, but it was a failure. White Prickly Vine just grows pricks.
I need a plant that can grow on buildings, and won't die or change no matter what.
Lisa did produce the prickly vines in the village!!
So it seems.
But... why?
Does the diary say anything else?
No, only observations and failed experiments.
...another failure. Next time, I'm going to try plants from other locations.
This is the last page.
Apparently Lisa didn't create the village prickly vines here.
Because the village prickly vines were spliced with Little Honey Pumpkin.
So, Lisa was once here, but then went to somewhere else?
Probably.
If there's another camp like this somewhere else, she may be there.
The camp is well-equipped and good for long staying...
It also goes some way to explaining why Lisa hasn't appeared in the Witch's House in a long time.
It was 5 years ago when prickly vines appeared in the village and Lisa disappeared.
5 years is a long time!!
She couldn't have stayed at the camp all that time...
Let's go back.
Hm... alright.
We also need to restore the village. I'll talk to White Cat God again.
And we need to tell Enite about removing the prickly vines.
It looks roomy. I'll walk around and see if there's [em1]another entrance[/em1] besides the one we entered from.
Look around for the witch chalk.
Found the witch chalk. I'll just use this.
Draw the witch sigil again to activate it.
Huh? What's this?
It seems that someone blocked the path with a tent to keep people out.
It's much like the huge garden door in the forest.
Yeah, that witch sigil also needs to be activated, right?
Let's find the witch chalk first.
Maybe it's not here.
Aren't keys usually hidden under flower pots or something?
And we need to search this place anyway.
I'll look for it too.
Oh, it's a doll!
Hmm... But it's so dirty!
The owner of the doll will always love it no matter what, right?
No. If one loves his doll, he will definitely keep it clean.
That's easy to say. Your doll was...
This has nothing to do with my doll!
It's so dirty that I can't even recognize it. We can't just leave it like this.
We need to [em1]find a way to clean it[/em1].
Who's doll is this?
Was it thrown away? It's dirty and missing an arm.
Yeah. I think I don't need to touch it, but...
The [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "FallenCotton_Name"))][/em1] near the doll looks worn yet clean.
It seems to be from the doll... Maybe the [em1]doll's owner[/em1] is someone else?
We may find them if we follow the [em1]Fallen Cotton[/em1].
<wave>Woahhhh</wave>
That was fun. Let's ride it again!
I thought your purpose was to get up here?
Yeah, but it was so fun.
That's mean to the prickly vine trace.
Finish your work before you play.
Sigh, you're annoying.
See? The [em1]prickly vine trace[/em1] is going [em1]upwards[/em1].
Yup, and there seems to be a water body ahead.
There seems to be something on the other side.
Okay, let's check it out!
Ugh... <shake>A-choo!</shake> What's going on?
Is your nose itchy?
Not very, but I can't breathe.
Hold your breath and run through.
<shake>I can't.</shake> My eyes are burning too!
In that case, just hold your breath and close your eyes.
Virgil, do I look like a hat to you?!
[em1]Prickly vine traces[/em1] have reached here...
I can't get through directly.
I need to get rid of the [em1]weird cloud of smoke[/em1] first.
<shake>A-choo!</shake>
<shake>A-CHOOO!</shake>
Search the surroundings for anything that can [em1]blow off the cloud of smoke[/em1].
What is this? It's so big.
Can I turn it on? Hmm, let's see, <shake>oomph!</shake>
How dare you touch it when you don't even know what it is!
I can enable it if I touch it!
It's tied by a chain in the first place.
Speaking of chains... I feel like I've seen them somewhere.
It feels familiar... Ah!
The huge garden gate at [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_GreenForest"))]! There was something similar on it!
So, there should be a device nearby for lifting this...
Is this also related to [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "WitchSign"))][/em1]?
Didn't you just pick up a piece of [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "WitchChalk_Blue_Name"))][/em1]?
[em1]Blue[/em1]...
Do you remember where you saw it now?
Sure
It was... there! On the hill of [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))] and [em1]beside the box with the doll left by Honey Bear's companion[/em1]!
Exactly! There was a [em1]blue [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "WitchSign"))][/em1]!
Okay, I'll take the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "WitchChalk_Blue_Name"))][/em1] and go to the place with the [em1]blue [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "WitchSign"))][/em1]!
I can't remember...
Think carefully. It's somewhere you've been to.
You've seen something that resembles a [em1]blue mark[/em1].
Um...
I got it
No idea...
Some hint please.
[em1]Doll of Honey Bear's companion[/em1].
Eh? Huh?
Ah! <shake>Now I remember!</shake>
You also need [em1]something related to [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "WitchSign"))][/em1].
I'd better take a look around here.
Take the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "WitchChalk_Blue_Name"))][/em1] and go to the [em1]box with the doll left by Honey Bear's companion[/em1] on the hill of [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))].
To turn the device, we need to insert Honey Bear's key into the [em1]keyhole[/em1].
Try the key.
Oh, it's a [lua(GetLocalizedString("Map", "RainbowForest_Plateau"))] again.
And the voice...!
There it is!
My goodness, how did it get pass?
You didn't notice it after so many trips to the forest?
It doesn't work on forest creatures.
The barrier only works on humans? Crap!
We have to [em1]lift this[/em1] after all or we can't enter.
Um... how should I greet it? "Hello, is this your doll?"
I guess it should be fine, since we don't know what it's saying anyway.
But it doesn't intend to move at all.
Maybe it's because the doll is still missing an arm.
Um... should I sew it back?
Are you being serious?
It doesn't seem too difficult, I think I can do it.
Do you not remember what happened last time you handled a needle and thread? You made me look like a beggar's hat.
What? Stop being unreasonable.
My accusation is perfectly justified!
I was just a kid! Now that I've learned it at school, I believe I can do some basic sewing.
You can go to [em1]someone good at needlework[/em1] to learn it again if other solutions fail.
I don't need to learn again. I didn't forget!
I don't have enough cotton to fill the doll.
We need to gather the missing cotton first.
Let me see what to do...
Do you have sewing tools?
As long as I have a needle-like stuff and some sort of thread, no?
But to sew with the tools I have, I need abundant [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "FallenCotton_Name"))][/em1].
So that I can redo it if I get it wrong.
Now, behold my marvelous skills!
I'm very, very worried.
Then, fix the doll with the cotton.
You may end up with a [em1]creepy doll[/em1] if you sew it with no preparation.
There will be [em1]risks[/em1] no matter how I do it, so I'll do it the way I like.
Beats me why you always choose thorny paths over smooth roads.
Alright, let's get this over with.
How to sew it?
Rely on intuition
Emm... let's see... will this needle and... this thread work?
Eh... is the thread too short? If I only use the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "SewingBox_Name"))] for this part...
Emm... oops, the needle hit the wrong place... I'll redo it...
Now, find the same color thread, thread the needle, and then put it here...
Patiently, one stitch at a time...
There! See? I told you I could do it.
Uh-huh. Feels like you just crossed a point of no return.
Hmph. That kid will definitely be pleased!
Here you go! Your doll!
It seems quite happy. That's great.
Huh? It's reaching out to me? What's it doing?
What a sweet smile!
<shake>Ugh, I'm all sticky!</shake>
<shake>This creature!</shake> I repaired its doll, and it's playing a prank on me!
Maybe that's its way of expressing gratitude.
If it wanted to give me honey, it should have put the honey in a jar! How am I supposed to eat it when it's smeared all over my face?
Oh? It actually gave it to me?
Maybe it wanted to feed you honey.
Thank you! I'll savor it!
Oh, it finally left.
We can go down this path now.
Will we encounter more strange creatures ahead?
I certainly hope not.
See? It likes it.
Strange in appearance, and even stranger in sense of beauty.
You're being too harsh, Virgil.
Use tools and do as taught
[em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "SewingBox_Name"))][/em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Choice", "NotHaveItem"))]
[lua(GetLocalizedString("Choice", "Cancel"))]
You need [em1]3[/em1] [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "FallenCotton_Name"))][/em1] to mend the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "HoneyBearDoll_Name"))].
First, I need [em1]8x [/em1][em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "FallenCotton_Name"))][/em1] to mend [lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "HoneyBearDoll_Name"))].
Huh? Not this one? A-again...
Really? You won't regret?
I'll think again
I won't regret
Everything is ready. There's nothing more to prepare.
Rubrum, let's go.
<wave>Okay~~~!</wave>
Look! Isn't my trumpet super cool! I'm going to play it today!
So, this is what you've been learning from Vinch. It really suits you well, Rubrum.
Hehe, I had some serious practice.
I can't wait to hear you play! Shall we go now?
Phew, it's no big deal. Why am I kind of nervous.
Shall we start the parade now?
Before that, Ellie, I'd like to give you something.
Aurea helped me get this cloth.
It glows in moonlight, perfect for a leader's banner.
They say that you will lead the parade, so I tried to make one. Take it with you.
Whoa... That's so kind of you. Thank you, Enite!
Then, how about we go pick up [em1]Kyla[/em1] first?
Okay, this time we're really setting out!
<wave>Let's go!</wave>
Virgil! There's a [em1]cat[/em1]!
Is it here to see me?
I don't think so. It just happens to be standing in front of the house.
Are you sure? Look again. This is nothing but the expression of "Let's play!"
How are you doing, kitty?!
It doesn't give a damn about you.
No way! It didn't hear me. That's all.
I hope it's not ignoring me on purpose.
Let's have a closer look.
I asked around, but none of the villagers keeps a cat.
Someone feeds the cats occasionally, but nothing else.
That cat didn't look close to the villagers in the first place.
Doesn't that make becoming friends with it an even more remarkable feat?
Anyway, at least we found out that someone had been taking care of these cats until recently.
The [em1]person[/em1] Rubrum mentioned? A mid-aged man he doesn't know?
Right, Rubrum said that he saw the man at the temple entrance north of the village.
So, you want to check it out?
Waiting for him there doesn't sound like a good idea to me. He may never show up.
But we don't have any other lead.
Did you see that? Those books and apples scattered on the ground.
Go to the place mentioned by Rubrum.
It's weird that these stuff are left all over the ground.
Is it? But Rubrum said that the man looked busy.
If he was busy, he might not have had time to put things in order.
You have a point.
Anyway, let's see what these stuff are.
Virgil, look at this book. Isn't it cute?
The title is adorable too. [em1]Cat Befriending Operation[/em1]. "Operation," it says, heh.
This messy handwriting looks like a child's doing.
But Rubrum said he saw an adult. Maybe it was just an adult with not-so-great handwriting.
Look at this. His drawing... is even worse than mine. It's a disaster.
Is this really a cat? He must be a devoted abstract artist.
This guy... He must be really eager to make friends with the cats.
He's recorded various cats, just like me filling up my encyclopedia.
But most of the pages are blank.
Maybe he didn't have the time, or they didn't like him.
I guess I can fill the blank pages for him!
It's decided. I'm going to make a cat encyclopedia.
Where is this idea coming from?
From our shared passion for cats. We both want to get closer to cats.
Well, honestly speaking, this idea isn't that bad.
And look at this. This [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Cranapple_Name"))][/em1] has cat bite marks.
A little bit of it is eaten. Perhaps a cat tried to eat it, but gave up halfway.
So, cats here also eat [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Cranapple_Name"))][/em1]s.
I've never thought about it. What do cats eat?
Find the answer and write it in the encyclopedia.
Alright. Let's tell Rubrum about our discovery first.
He must be sitting on the edge of his chair now.
He can't be that curious.
Rubrum, is this the place where you saw that stranger?
Yup.
But I don't usually come here, so I know little about this place.
You explore beyond the village whenever you get the chance, yet you know little about a location within the village?
Well... I prefer to stay away from the temple.
Why is that?
Anyway, I believe this is the place where the stranger took care of the cats.
To attract cats, you just need to put some [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Cranapple_Name"))][/em1]s here.
Unless no cats live around here... which is impossible.
Ellie, why would you know?
It's the intuition of a witch.
Some intuition you've got there. You deducted it from the half-eaten [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Cranapple_Name"))][/em1].
Humph, can't you stop raining on my parade?
I'll first try leaving [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Cranapple_Name"))][/em1]s at the place from before.
It ran away.
As soon as it saw the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Cranapple_Name"))][/em1]s.
It's the same as when I tried to feed it...
Jeez... We're here to befriend it, but we ended up driving it away.
Maybe... we should stay away from the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Cranapple_Name"))][/em1]s?
Why?
Just step into its shoes. Wouldn't it feel cringe to have someone stare at you when you're eating?
So, let's drop the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Cranapple_Name"))][/em1]s and observe from a distance.
Like this?
Yeah, I'll join you.
Rubrum, did you see that?
The cat ate the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "Cranapple_Name"))][/em1]s.
Right, I think it likes them, since it gobbled them down.
Now I know what to do.
Cats can't relax and eat if we don't stay away.
I've been chasing them around with food in hand... So, it doesn't work out that way.
Cats have different personalities... but I guess you would scare every single cat, haha.
Oh no...
Ah, what's that noise? I think the cat's leaving.
<shake>Bye, kitty. Looking forward to meeting you again.</shake>
<shake>Byeeee!</shake>
It's gone. I can't see it anymore from here.
And it didn't even look back.
That doesn't worry me at all.
Why? Do you have a plan?
Brace yourself. I would call it "the power of observation."
Look, Rubrum. This is the cat encyclopedia left by that mid-aged man.
My goodness... He draws even worse than I do.
Hahaha... Don't worry about the pictures. Look at the information recorded here.
See? Many different cats are described here.
You'll get close to the cats sooner or later, as long as you keep recording!
Ellie, you're sounding like a researcher.
Exactly! I'm gonna be an expert in cats!
Cool!
Right? That's just a piece of cake for someone graduating magna cum laude from the School for Witches.
Your using your learnings to study cats would give the principal a heart attack.
Anyway, we've found out how to make friends with cats.
Now, we just need to apply our finding to practice.
Cats don't usually lower their guard around humans, though. It takes time.
No problem. A bit of challenge will add fun to it. Don't you think so, Rubrum?
I prefer it to stay simple.
A-alright...
Still, it's been a smooth start for our [em1]Cat Befriending Operation[/em1].
I look forward to more progress.
I'm gonna be a friend to all the cats! There we go!
This cat is kind of shy.
I think it's just avoiding humans habitually.
So I see.
It must be because we don't know each other well yet.
It will soon get used to me and drop by.
That stubbornness of yours is impressive, Ellie.
Humph. But I've got a cat at my door!
Ellie, you've never kept a cat. You don't know them.
Cats are attracted to magic power.
It's just here to have a look, after finding the long vacant Witch's House occupied by a new witch.
But I'm also a witch. I've got magic power. Shouldn't it be attracted to me too?
Or, is the magic power of a witch apprentice too weak?
No idea. I've never dealt with cats.
Me not knowing cats is also justified, since witch apprentices don't get animal companions.
You could have had one if your guardians allowed... but Aiden gave an absolute no.
It can't be helped. Dad is terribly allergic to fur.
But I can finally take initiative, now that a cat is at my door.
I'll give it another go... <shake>Kitty!</shake>
It's gone...
That's aloof, as expected from cats.
It was here to see me, but it wouldn't let me stroke it.
Isn't that too much?
It wasn't necessarily here to see you.
And no cat would willingly be stroked by a stranger, as long as it is a cat.
There are exceptions, such as the cats kept by the school faculty. And the owls too.
They are used to students. As you said yourself, exceptions.
Can't argue with that.
Sigh, I finally got a cat coming to me, but I don't know what to do. That's a shame.
Isn't that a perfect opportunity for forming a bond?
It wasn't quite the ideal interaction, but at least you've met.
Right. That they show up at the Witch's House means they are interested in this place.
But since this house doesn't hold any cat supply...
No cat would bother to come, except those that live nearby or in the village.
Right. Afterall, cats can thrive anywhere.
I can ask the villagers.
Some may be familiar with those cats.
I also want to become friends with them soon.
To mother? From "Dosca"?
This letter isn't for me.
Of course not, since you're no mother to any Dosca.
And I don't even know any Dosca. Who is it?
How could you have forgotten?
According to official records, there's [em1]another witch[/em1] in this area.
You mean Lisa? Oh! The letter does mention [em1]Lisa[/em1] too!
Is it the Lisa we know?
Who else could it be if not [em1]the Lisa[/em1]? The letter has been sent to her Witch's House.
Wait! That means... [em1]Lisa's daughter[/em1] has given birth to a [em1]daughter[/em1]!
That's usually called her [em1]granddaughter[/em1].
My goodness... This should make <shake>headlines</shake>!
And Dosca said that she wanted to name the child after [em1]Lisa[/em1].
We should tell Lisa about it at once!
There's a common saying that "A witch leaves her [em1]brooch and name[/em1] upon death"!
That's how much a witch's name matters.
But where is Lisa? We didn't find her at the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))] either.
Although the [em1]White Cat God[/em1] said she was there...
You should ask the White Cat God directly.
Right, and I can inform her of the village restoration too.
Time to build the bridges!
Let's see... Roy and Vinch, try to gather all the materials we need.
Kyla has told me the numbers needed. I'll go with you and double-check.
It's chiefly rocks and timber, I believe? It's been a while since I transported supplies.
Well... I wonder if Roy and I should be grouped just because we're peers...
Don't push yourself too hard. I'll have your back.
Mister Alvin and Arin, please search the surroundings for any suitable stones.
Stones that suit the task? Understood.
I'm not familiar with stones... but I'll try.
As for the others...
<shake>Me and Rubrub will go on an adventure!</shake>
Ordinary stones are not enough for the village bridge!
Rubrub! Let's go!
It's Rubrum...
These two dudes are overly excited. Just let them be.
Are they going by themselves? That worries me a bit. Can anyone follow along?
Arden! Join us!
What? Why should I ask for the trouble?
It's not like you've got anything else to do.
Humph.
Haha! Rubrub, you were right on the mark!
Alright, Arden will come with us!
Seriously, give me a break...
We'll go get the materials then.
Eek... That's gonna be a month's worth of physical work in one day.
Everyone, stay alert and be careful.
Ahem! Guys! What do you feel about being selected as the elite squad?
Captain! You haven't assigned me a mission!
Oh yeah, Ellie, as my right-hand girl, you should stay here and help me.
I've left a pile of rocks over there, meant for the base.
Lay the base well, and the bridge will be enduring, making it the most crucial step in bridge construction.
I'll tell you the [em1]order in which they are needed[/em1]. [em1]Throw them to me in order[/em1].
Give me the stones one by one, smaller ones first.
Just throw them as hard as you can. They won't break, hahaha!
<wave>Help! We've got a problem!</wave>
<shake>(puffing)</shake> Rubrum, wait for me...
I can't! I need to tell everyone!
Rubrum, what's going on? What happened to Vinch?
Arden is dead!
And Rex is dying!
WHAT—?!
Come quickly!
What on earth?
There was... <shake>(panting)</shake> There was an accident... You'd better... all have a look...
Looks like we've got an issue. Everyone, put your task aside and check it out.
Jeez... What's going on?
*sobbing* Hang in there, Arden!
<shake>Don't forget me, Rubrub!!</shake>
<shake>Boohoo</shake>, Arden!
What's this all about?
Rex said that you'd only get ordinary rocks if you searched ordinary places...
That you must look somewhere weird, suspicious and unusual.
So we came here and mined with pickaxes...
Then, suddenly, the cliff made a loud cracking sound, and Rex was stuck.
A giant falling rock missed me narrowly, which scared the wits out of me...
Arden covered me from the rock... and he — he died! <shake>Boohoo!</shake>
It's okay, Rubrum. Arden is a dragon. Dragons don't die. He's just sleeping.
<shake>I can't breeeeeathe!!!</shake>
<shake>Heeeelp!!</shake>
Hahaha, shouting is a waste of the little air you have.
And you're deafening us. Let's move all the rocks first.
Arden is simply unconscious. He will be fine.
Oh, and Arin, fetch some cool water to wake Arden, hahaha!
Phew! I thought I was going to suffocate!
Ouch... my head...
I'm never ever going anywhere with this redheaded brat.
Told you to be careful. You could have injured Rubrum as well.
But ordinary stones are boring!
Treasure hunting is inherantly risky! And you can't let minor failures discourage you. Rubrub, don't you agree?
Er... well...
You were simply causing trouble in the name of looking for fancy stones...
Now you've finally stepped into my shoes.
I don't put my friends in harm's way. You're the only one I may drag down with me.
At least I'm stepping in Arden's shoes.
Anyway! You must be more cautious. You gave everyone a scare.
But I haven't found THE wonderful stone of mine!
I want a beautiful stone too.
<shake>(puffing)</shake> I... I may be able to help you with that.
Vinch! You're finally here!
I... I don't usually run...
But I've heard every word.
How exactly are you going to help?
Could you come over here? Yelling all the time will leave me out of breath... <shake>haha.</shake>
(panting) L-let me catch my breath.
Well, I make my own [em1]paint[/em1], you know. I may be able to grant Rex and Rubrum's wish with paint.
You've got a point!
I'm the one who suggested a stepping stone bridge... I should contribute to it.
All the more reason now that Rubrum was nearly injured.
Rex should take most of the blame, for being carried away...
But using paint is a nice idea.
Since we're painting rocks that will become the piers, normal paint will easily be washed away.
And to realize the rich effects they want, the materials at hand may not suffice.
Could you help me with that?
We need more materials?
It's not about the materials. We'd better get paint [em1]of varied colors[/em1].
I know how to keep the paint on stones, since waterproof paint is common in oil painting.
So, what we need is [em1]as many colors as possible[/em1]?
Right, I want to do this for Rex and Rubrum.
Well... to make colorful paint...
<rainb>[lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "ColourfulPotion_Name"))]!</rainb>
I think Ellie has come up with something.
I'll make as much paint as possible. Come to me when you're ready.
Hi, what are you doing over there?
This place may collapse again. Let's return to the village quickly.
Ellie, wait a minute.
There's no need to follow me around. Feel free to [em1]work on what you and Vinch have decided[/em1].
I caught you two plotting something in secret, so I listened in, haha!
Rubrum has been a well-behaved child. He's never caused any trouble except for doodling on his quilt when he was little...
It'd have broken my heart if he had injured himself following Rex around.
Roy promised to help me later, saying that the material gathering was progressing faster than expected.
So, Ms. Witch, you can focus on other tasks.
Alright. I've got a brilliant idea. Leave it to me.
Hahaha, no one's more reliable than our Ms. Witch!
I'll leave it in your capable hands!
I haven't made any [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "ColourfulPotion_Name"))][/em1] in a while, but here we go.
It's the first potion recipe I learned from Mom.
You would play with it in your seat, instead of messing around.
Everyone will fall in love with it! It [em1]produces a different color[/em1] each time you use it. It's so fun!
And the [em1]color changes[/em1] whenever you stir it or add more drops. It never gets repetitive.
But when I was a bit older, I developed other hobbies, and rarely played with it anymore.
Fair, since the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "ColourfulPotion_Name"))] can neither pick locks for you,
or show you the way to the secret library.
Ahem, as for the [em1]recipe[/em1], I can ask [em1]Diane[/em1] like always.
Woah! Is this all paint?
Some colors are brighter than those crayons Vinch gave me!
Holy cow! I've never seen so much paint ever since I left my father's study!
If we decorate stones with this, it will save you the risky exploration.
We have all the paint you'll need. Use as much as you want.
Jeez, we're making our special stones instead of looking for them?
Artists are experts when it comes to thinking outside the box! This is awesome!
You're too kind... I'm glad you like it.
Come at me, Rubrum! See if your stone can beat mine in appearance!
I won't lose!
Rex is as much a kid as Rubrum...
So, this is what Rubrum rushed out of the home for.
Granny, look at this! It's so fun!
We've got loads of paint! All that we can use!
So you have, and the colors are brilliant! Paint some beautiful stones with it.
Heh! I will!
Are you decorating the stones? It's gonna be a unique bridge.
I'm sorry for all the trouble Rex's causing you...
Don't be mad at Rex! Rex has shown me a lot of fun and magical stuff.
Aww, Rubrub...! You're such a loyal dude!
He never says my name right, though.
Ellie?
Ellie, what elements do you like?
What, me?
Yup! Vinch told me that you helped make the paint.
So I'm gonna draw something you like, heh.
Things I like
Just draw your favorite things, Rubrum.
Okay! Leave it to me!
Just draw your face, Rubrum. It's the classic choice in such occasions.
Draw that tea tree on the hill. It's gorgeous when it flowers.
No wonder the village's so quiet. Everyone's gathering here.
Kyla! Come and draw with us!
Hahaha, I'll pass. I like stones as they are.
But polished ores and smelted steel are charming in their own ways too...
Oops, that's not what I'm here for.
Hi, Ellie, your solution has apparently been a success.
Aha, you can always have faith in me, captain.
Haha! Of course, I always do.
Thanks to you, the preparation is going smoothly. I believe the construction can soon begin.
Great! I can't wait to see it finished!
It will probably take [em1]one day[/em1], starting from [em1]tomorrow morning[/em1].
Look forward to it, hahaha!
Ellie~! The bridges are ready! Come take a look!
Rubrum's so excited.
Let's go see the bridges.
It's the new bridges! This is amazing!
We've got two new bridges in one go!
The bridges look both beautiful and enduring.
Ellie, would you like to say something on behalf of the villagers?
Eh? Me?
Go ahead and speak as the deputy captain.
Ahem, well... thank you all for making time to help build the bridges.
Together, you've made these incredible bridges possible. My gratitude also goes to Kyla, the biggest contributor.
Haha, you're too nice to me.
Now, I suggest that we walk this bridge together.
Look! Here are the stones I painted!
Hahaha! Do appreciate my stones whenever you pass this bridge. You'll be mesmerized by their sense, creativity and beauty!
I can't believe that Wisteria now has a bridge you can't find elsewhere!
I've never witnessed a bridge being constructed... It was so fun.
Hm, it's not bad at all.
Don't ever get me involved in such things again.
Hurry, let's go!
There used to be a [em1]bridge leading to the southern part of the village[/em1] over here.
What happened to it?
As you can see, most of it is gone.
I've talked to Enite about it.
This bridge is beyond repair. The only option is to [em1]build a new one[/em1].
That's not gonna be a small task.
I suppose it will cost a lot of materials.
What if we get more builders?
The more the better!
If so, how about we call on the villagers to [em1]build it together[/em1]?
We'd better listen to everyone's opinions if we're getting a new bridge.
Nice idea. You're a genius, Ellie.
I'll ask Rubrum to gather all the villagers.
But it's too late today. Let's come here tomorrow [em1]during the day[/em1].
It's too dark at night. Crowding can cause injuries.
Ellie, please don't stay up too late. Being an early riser is the secret to good health.
Granny! Everyone's here!
Can't you leave me alone? I want nothing to do with such activities.
How can we leave any villager out when it comes to village affairs!
Heh, thank you all for coming.
I've summoned you today to discuss a plan on rebuilding the [em1]bridge[/em1] leading to the [em1]southern part of the village[/em1].
I'd like to have as many helpers as I can get when building it, haha!
You can see that it's gonna take forever if I'm to build it all by myself.
And, I've been thinking...
How about we seize this opportunity to build two bridges at once, the other one located [em1]south to the steps over there[/em1]?
It will save the long detour every time someone wants to get to the other side.
As long as we get everyone's consent.
Right, more hands will boost the efficiency in tasks like this.
I want it! There can never be too many roads!
You guys can make the decision.
Well... I don't often travel to the southern part...
But it will benefit anyone who does, so I agree with Kyla.
So do I... It will make it easier for the elders to navigate the village.
No objection.
Let's do it!
Haha, alright. Everyone's so supportive!
...Hmm.
What is it, Ellie?
Instead of building just any bridge, why don't we build a bridge [em1]unique to Wisteria[/em1]?
An ordinary bridge would be boring.
But what exactly is a bridge unique to Wisteria?
What about a glass bridge? There's a glass bridge at the School for Witches, on which you can see the scenery beneath you.
It sounds cool, but I don't think we can afford the material.
What about an arch bridge? It may be common, but I find it nice-looking.
If we can't build a bridge that's unique in itself, we may decorate it with flowers when it's finished.
We can grow mushrooms along the bridge and bounce on them!
I want it to have an unprecedented shape that will surprise any visitor!
Oh my, it's difficult to cater to all tastes.
We're building a bridge, not crafting a sculpture.
What about a [em1]stepping stone bridge[/em1]?
It may not sound notable... but the impression varies dramatically depending on the stones used and the layout.
A stepping stone bridge! I like it!
A stepping stone bridge can be dangerous for kids, such as the younger child of the [em1]bakery[/em1] owners, if they move back.
Well, I wonder if that can be said for yourself too, ma'am...
That can be addressed.
The bridge will be safer as long as we lay the stones tightly.
It will be too much work if you want both bridges to be creative though.
How about one ordinary bridge and one stepping stone bridge?
That would be perfect!
Aha, glad to hear that.
Let's divide the work then. Everyone will be responsible for part of the construction.
I'll collect the tools and be ready to work. Let me know when you want the construction to begin, Ellie.
It's dangerous to work in the dark. Let's do it [em1]during the day[/em1].
Alright! See you when the construction begins!
Miss Arin, by the look of the list, we'd better sort the stones over here first.
But wouldn't it be easier to do the smaller pile first?
Miss Kyla must have a reason for arranging the steps in this order.
It's like reading a conductor's score. You need to follow their intentions.
But just like how books are shelved... stones should also be sorted if you want to find them quickly.
Hello, Ms. Witch. What do you think?
Ellie, you've been to the library several times... I believe you get my point?
W-well, hahaha... I'm here on a mission assigned by Kyla.
We should follow the list. Kyla must have her reason.
Stones will be easier to find if we sort them like we sort books.
I'd better stay out of this...
Good idea.
I'll first go somewhere that the villagers gather.
Okay, the party has come to its end.
Enite has made a custom-ordered dish for today!
Ta-da! <wave>Whaah...</wave>
Here comes the custom-ordered cake! Enite, wanna give a little speech?
I thought about baking a giant pie like the last time,
but we've got much more guests this time, and there's Ellie, who has contributed so much to the village,
so I decided to prepare something more special.
But I can't take all the credit for it. Everyone helped make it.
I helped Granny a lot while practicing my trumpet!
Indeed. Arin helped me process the ingredients, and Roy got the ingredients for me.
I... I just followed Enite's instructions.
I'm glad to be of help.
Vinch helped me make the cream, and Arden baked the bread with me.
Whipping the cream is the hardest part.
Hmph, what do you mention these for.
And there is another crucial person,
which is Ellie. She helped us reunite here. Without her, none of this would have been possible.
Please allow me to thank you on behalf of the village, Ellie.
Hehe, I've been having a great time myself since I met you guys.
Now, let's share this cake!
I want to have this every day...
It's good... so very good.
Wow, what a great cake Enite has made! I can finish the whole of it by myself.
Enite's always been an amazing baker.
It's sweet and delicious... I suppose this is the sweetness that brings happiness.
Hmm, this is a high-end taste. It's pretty good.
Ah... It literally melts in my mouth.
I'm so glad to see everyone enjoying the cake.
It's an awesome finale, Enite.
Ahem, let's call it a day then.
Thank you all for attending today's party, villagers of Wisteria.
I'm Ellie Blueriver, your emcee tonight.
<wave>Waaaah!</wave> Ellie is the best!
Haha, I look forward to seeing the rest of the village restored.
Let’s all keep doing our best!
<shake>Hi there!!!</shake>
Hey, Ellie!
Hi, Rubrum! And... who's your friend?
Hello, Miss Witch! I'm Dana.
I love carrots and donuts, hate green peppers, and I'm really good at addition!
I'm also the delivery girl for the brand-new Munchy Bakery.
My sister makes amazing donuts, so please stop by sometime!
Nice to meet you, Dana. I'm Ellie Blueriver. Just call me Ellie.
And you can relax. There's no need to be so formal.
Really? <shake>Okay, sister Ellie!</shake>
That was fast...
So... your sister's coming too? Where is she?
She's been busy at the bakery since dawn, so she couldn't make it.
I even woke up an hour early today to help her!
Once everything was ready, she told me to go invite people,
and I ran into Rubrum, who was heading out of the village. So, we came together!
On the way here, Rubrum told me all about you, sister Ellie!
I had to see for myself!
Right, Rubrum?
I see. Well then, let's go check out this new bakery!
Hurry! Donuts taste best when they're still warm!
Welcome. Long time no see, everyone.
And... we have someone new here, too.
I'm Clala, and this is my little sister, Dana. Nice to meet you.
Hi! I'm Dana! I love carrots and donuts, but hate green peppers!
Ah, so you're the new witch in town.
I've heard about you. Thank you for everything you've done.
Thanks to you, I could open this bakery.
Hehe, you're welcome. Welcome back to the village, Clala and Dana!
Clala, you've grown into such a fine young lady... And Dana... I almost didn't recognize you.
Wow, Granny Enite!
She's my grandma.
It's a shame Paul and Linda couldn't come.
Ah... our parents decided to keep running their bakery in the city.
I've improved a lot, so I don't think anyone will be disappointed.
Oh, right! Didn't we say we'd set off fireworks when we all met again?
I bought some on the way here. Wanna play with fireworks together?
And welcome to Munchy Bakery!
Welcome to Munchy Bakery!
Hmm!
<wave>Ah!</wave>
R–Rubrum... who's this?
You're the witch who cleared the prickly vines in the village, right?
Oh, yes. I cleared the pricky vine in Wisteria...
<shake>Thank you!</shake>
Name's Bjorn.
Uncle Bjorn... you're really loud.
Ahem... guess I'll try talking softer then, Rubrum.
Ah... well, speaking up means I can hear you clearly, so that's nice too.
I–I'm glad to meet you. I'm Ellie Blueriver, from the Witch's House.
<shake>Oh-ho!</shake> Ellie! Now that's a fine name.
Ahaha... no one's ever said that before, but thank you anyway.
Well then, Miss Ellie. The welcome party's all set. Let's head into the village.
Just call me Ellie... No "Miss" needed.
Got it, Ellie!
So... he's new in town?
Yep. Uncle Bjorn.
Sorry. I worked in noisy places for years, so I'm used to speaking up...
Thanks to you, I can call this village home again. So, I wanted to say hello.
I've been away for thirty years! And now I'm finally back.
I would've returned sooner, but... those strange prickly vines kept me away.
I'm just glad you made it back, Bjorn.
I missed you too, Enite.
Aside from you and Arden, most folks here are new faces.
Arden didn't seem to remember me, so it's like meeting everyone for the first time. Ha!
Can't blame him. You were just a scrawny boy when you left.
Hah! Years of hard work will do this to a man!
You've built quite the muscles... are you a blacksmith as well?
Nope! Spent most of my life driving trains.
Decided to retire early and settle down.
Hahaha, well, welcome home, Bjorn.
Thanks, Ellie.
And most of all, thank you, everyone, for preparing such a warm welcome.
Thanks to you, I got the rare experience of seeing someone other than a tipsy Kyla at four in the morning.
Knocking on doors at dawn... gave me quite a scare.
Haha! I was too excited, so I was wandering around early.
Now, let's celebrate with some firecrackers!
When I first saw him at the gate, I thought he was a giant monster.
Uncle Bjorn, when are we setting off the big one you brought?
Perfect timing, Rubrum.
So, you're the witch who cleared the prickly vines and saved Wisteria, right?
And you are...?
Mm, this is a new neighbor. When I said I was coming to find you, he wanted to tag along.
Well, since I had the chance to meet the famous witch in person, I came straight over.
I'm Theo. Nice to meet you!
Hello, Theo. No need to be so formal.
By the way, the amazing witch who cleared the prickly vines is none other than me, Ellie Blueriver!
That makes it sound like you did it all by yourself.
<wave>Whoa...</wave> And a talking hat, too. You really are a witch.
Yup. This friend on my head is Virgil.
Think of him as my assistant... with a sharp tongue.
Nice to meet you, Virgil!
Right, I might've forgotten to mention he actually helped a lot. We'll just skip that part.
Do you have any special abilities too?
I am the special ability, being a talking hat.
Ellie and Virgil seem to get along really well.
Virgil talks to the old lady who made him the same way. You'll get used to it.
Anyway, let's save the chit-chat. Everyone's waiting. Time for your welcome party.
Alright! Enite's pie is ready, let's go.
I've only ever met one talking hat, and that's Virgil.
Hey, Rubrum. He moved here too, right?
Is that so? Alright then, Ellie.
Talking in front of everyone feels kinda fun.
My name's Theo. Pleased to meet you.
Theo is living alone because of some things that happened with his family.
I check in on him often... but I hope everyone else will visit him too.
Hahaha, if anything breaks in your house, just let me know.
If you need help with anything, don't hesitate to ask.
But, Theo, why are you living alone?
Ah, my parents are archaeologists. They've gone off to look for mysterious relics and ruins.
Both your parents are archaeologists?
If you ever need survival training, I'm your guy!
Normally, I'd travel with them, but this time they went somewhere too dangerous, so I had to stay behind.
They used to investigate ancient relics together. Then, they got married.
Guess you had no choice but to split up this time.
Still... isn't Wisteria safe now?
All thanks to the great witch and problem-solver, Ellie!
Hearing it put that way is kinda embarrassing...
Finding a village where I could live on my own was really hard...
But thanks to Enite and Ellie, I made it here.
If it's okay, I'd like to give you my [em1]Hero's Firecracker[/em1], Ellie. What do you say?
[em1]Hero's Firecracker[/em1]?
Yep. It's a special firecracker made for celebrations. The principal gave it to me before I came here.
That's such a meaningful gift! Thank you!
Then let's set it off! To celebrate everything that brought me here!
Since I can't follow my parents, I have to live on my own.
Did you mention something about special training?
Look! Rubrum sent me a letter!
The handwriting's a bit messy... but I can still make it out!
Reminds me of when you first started writing. You annotated all of Aiden's books.
Oh yeah, I was at that age where I wanted to use everything I'd learned.
But... he didn't mention exactly what kind of toy it is.
Probably like when you found the cat encyclopedia and apples last time.
Really? Guess we'll find out soon enough.
This is what [em1]Rubrum[/em1] was talking about in his letter, right?
It doesn't look in great shape, does it?
You're right. It's like something heavy was put on it, and it just broke under the weight.
Rubrum says it's a cat toy...
Anyway, it'd be odd if a cat managed to put Rubrum on it and break it, wouldn't it?
<wave>Hmm~</wave> The air's so fresh today.
And the village restoration is progressing smoothly. What a delight.
My apprenticeship is quite fruitful, isn't it?
At this rate, I may even achieve a full restoration, hohoho.
We haven't found Lisa though... That is frustrating, but I'll find her one day!
You're getting dizzy with success, Lady Witch.
I think you've got a letter. Check the [em1]letterbox[/em1] first.
Come on, it's just a new letter, not an emergency.
If you don't read your letters in a timely manner, you may end up in an emergency.
Your staying here was discovered and you had Kent cover it up for you only recently. Have you forgotten that already?
What do you mean by "cover it up"? He wrote a letter for me. That's all!
Come on, you're such a spoilsport.
I'm saying it for your sake.
Fine, fine, I'll read the letter. Stop nagging at me like a geezer.
Let’s get closer to the villagers.
What's this? I got it from some tiny guy that resembled an acorn.
I suppose that was a [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Ritoring"))][/em1].
[em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Ritoring"))][/em1]?
Right, a [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Ritoring"))][/em1]. They are a rare sight.
Little about them is known, not even to witches.
Now I remember... There was this kid — Ralph, was it — who was always wearing a couple of clover-shaped brooches.
Those were apparently not usual clovers... They were made of [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "RitoringPouch_Name"))][/em1]s.
I didn't expect you to be so observant.
After all, Ralph was unique. He always carried a lot of collections with him.
He even boasted about it, saying that those items would bring him good luck.
Maybe they would. Some believe that [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "RitoringPouch_Name"))][/em1]s bring good luck.
Really? Those people must want to collect them then?
Sure. For them, [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "RitoringPouch_Name"))][/em1]s are collectibles.
Okay! I'll loof for more.
As I expected, this place is also overrun by prickly vines.
This [em1]wisteria tree[/em1] has withered.
It was a huge tree in my memory, but look at it now...
Jeez, even the trees were ruined before I noticed?
What a sorrowful end for a tree that has witnessed history.
This is probably also the prickly vines' doing.
Trees... can also suffocate.
Ellie, go that way if you're looking for the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
Be careful, will you?
Okay, I will.
Rex, you heard that? It's the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))]!
Yup! I like the ring of the name. I'll visit it someday.
Hey! Didn't you hear all the talk about how dangerous it is?
I want to say the same line to YOU.
I've read about the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))] in books...
It's an ancient cave with many different names,
such as the Evening Dome, the NightSea Cave, the Whispering Mines, and the Star's Grave...
It's also described in detail.
"A star has fallen in this pitch-black cave, filling it with starlight. That starlight, as profound as the night sky, is—"
Please stop.
Why! I want to hear more!
Humph, those are just lies.
Arden, you're the first among us to settle down at Wisteria. Do you know about the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))]?
Don't go there. That's all I have to say.
It's where a star has fallen.
So what?
That means it's no longer an underground place, but the night sky itself.
Creatures on the ground must keep away from the night sky.
I can't understand a word.
I'm saying it's dangerous. If you have to get inside...
Do it at your own risk.
I've seen paintings about the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
Every one of them was obscure.
However, they all depicted some sort of giant shadows.
I know you're going for the village's sake, but do be cautious.
Alright, I'll be careful.
Prickly vines on the ground are extending towards the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
What we should do is quite clear.
Yeah, it's just like before.
We shall [em1]locate and remove the prickly vine core[/em1], and search for [em1]Lisa[/em1] as we go along.
By the way, Ellie,
during the bridge construction, I removed all the stuff in the way,
including the pile up here.
And I've organized the stuff on the other bank.
The path should be clear now.
Wow, thank you, Kyla!
As always, let's do a great job.
Alright, off to the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))]!
Let's goooo!
Not you two!
Heehee, this is so fun!
Since you came all this way, you're not leaving empty-handed.
Here, try a donut. One each.
We made them this morning! Go ahead, try one!
Wow... so good! Just like Granny's pie!
This donut is delicious. The dough is chewy, and the jam is so fragrant.
Mmm... sweet.
Such pretty colors. They're beautiful.
And some are shaped like flowers... They're too cute to eat.
Haha! One bite and I'm wide awake!
Kids will love these!
This feels more like a snack than a meal.
Eat enough of them and it is a meal!
That's right! I could eat a hundred donuts!
I'm glad everyone likes them.
Ellie, why don't you pick one from the bucket up front?
Oh? What's this?
It's our grand-opening raffle.
I wouldn't even be doing this if it weren't for you.
So, I wanted you to have the first draw.
<wave>Tada~!</wave> Time to pick a prize!
Hmm... which one should I pick?
Red
Okay, I've decided! This one.
Well... Let's see... This color is...
Congratulations, you won!
Yes! I won!
Win on your first try, no wonder people call you the lucky witch.
Bring this [em1]tasting coupon[/em1] on your next visit and I'll give you a free [em1]donut[/em1] for it.
Alright, everyone else, it's your turn to try the raffle! Today only!
I'll try... Wow! <shake>I won!</shake>
I've never won anything like this...
Oh! <shake>Ohhh!</shake> I won too!
Looks like I won as well.
Yay! Free donuts!
Wow, everyone's lucky today!
Hmph. Things can't be that easy.
So, everyone's got their tasting coupon?
Seeing everyone again and meeting someone new makes this a wonderful day.
A wonderful day! It's a wonderful day!
Please visit again, and keep supporting our bakery.
Delicious donuts! Come try them anytime!
Welcome, and thank you.
I'm glad to see more lively kids around. Come by anytime.
Blue
Yellow
You won all of them. Great start!
That's one loud, flashy firecracker.
Feels too big for a little village festival.
This kind only sells in the capital.
Thought it might come in handy, so I brought some. Judging by your faces, I made the right call.
Could use it to scare off wild animals too.
Oh, I brought more than just firecrackers.
If you saw what's in the rest of those boxes, you'd be shocked.
Judging by the pile of crates, it's not just "something small."
Yep! Uncle Bjorn said he got us all expensive presents.
What?! Rubrum! <shake>Don't tell them!</shake>
Now the surprise game I planned is ruined...
Haha, were you planning to hand them all out?
Your decorations are nice, but the audience doesn't seem ready for this level of show.
It's really no trouble, but compared to what I imagined...
I didn't want to burden anyone, so after talking with Enite, I only brought useful things.
For the painter, a paint set of 180 colors. For our librarian, ten sets of silver bookmarks!
I... make my own paints, actually.
And I... wouldn't dare use bookmarks that expensive.
What?! If I can't give these away, my "ice-breaking" plan...
Haha. It's just nice to have you back, Bjorn.
Leave the gifts in the storage. People can take what they like.
Yes! Exactly!
Then how about everyone leaves here with something from Bjorn?
Carrying gifts home always feels nice. It's just like birthdays.
Can I pick some snacks?
Take all you want, Rubrum.
And if anyone needs anything else, just tell me! Being part of such an exciting welcome party is a gift to me.
Gifts are great, but I'm looking forward to the days we'll share from now on.
Haha. Next time, skip the presents and share a drink with us instead.
...And bring more beef bread.
Agreed. From now on, we're all neighbors.
Thank you! Let's <shake>be friends with each other!</shake>
Uncle Bjorn, you're even louder than a Gaga Bird.
I also brought hats for every season for the little lady!
Ooh~ Dana wants a cute one!
You're not planning to play all day, are you? We've got plenty to do.
Yeah. That loud voice must be quite useful! Hehe.
...That is a lot of gifts.
What's this?
Pfft!
Haha! Ellie and Virgil's faces look just like the principal's!
The white powder just went poof everywhere.
Let me just... get the powder out of my mouth first...
Hahaha, so that's what it is!
It only takes one little gadget to pull off a twist like that. What a funny guy.
Ellie! You okay?
If you're fine, I'm using that next time.
How is that "heroic"?!
Even the talking hat got spooked by the flour firecracker. Perfect! Hehe.
You two really do seem close.
Dana, don't play with food.
Ellie, you alright?
Yeah, yeah, I know. My sisters tell me that all the time.
I was wondering where all my flour went while I was baking pies this morning... now I know.
Terrifyingly sweet.
Theo... you didn't mess with the pies too, did you?
Nope. I just asked Enite to make them sweeter than usual.
Come on, sweeter's always better, right?
I like it. It's sweet and delicious.
I'll never say no to Enite's pies, but still...
It's delicious, but I think I'm going to put on a few pounds.
Theo... you've been busy since this morning, right?
Hehe, a party's only good if everyone's having fun.
If it makes people smile, then I'm happy.
Alright... I don't know when, but you'd better be ready next time.
When it comes to pranks, I'm no slouch.
Now I'm really looking forward to it!
Alright, let's wrap up the welcome party. We'll start cleaning from Theo's place. There's still plenty to do today.
Thanks for the warm welcome! If anyone needs a firecracker, just say the word!
Theo seems like a pretty fun guy too.
Great... now I've got flour all over my face.
Speaking of which, everyone should have some pie before it gets cold.
Yes, please! I feel really hungry from all that laughing.
Ellie, use this handkerchief. Give Virgil a good shake, too.
Thanks, Enite and Vinch. You're lifesavers.
The village feels a little livelier already.
Let's follow the thorny vines first.
A lizard?
This isn't a magic lizard or anything like that, is it?
It's possible a former witch created it or raised it.
Possible? Mental jaws! Mysterious firs!
Are you talking?
Talk? Incredible lakes! Noble elms!
Are you laughing?
Laugh? A bumpy picture! A unique pine!
What kind of conversation is this?
Whatever you make it out to be.
I don't get it, but it sure is fascinating.
Fascinating! Secretive food! Lovely apple trees!
Oh, I've got an idea! Virgil, did you get it?
This lizard's acting like a home spirit.
Home spirit?
As I said before, houses built by witch craftsmen are sentient.
This house must have been built by a witch craftsman powerful enough for its mind to manifest into a concrete object.
So the lizard is the manifestation of this Witch's House.
It's the spirits.
But why has it suddenly shown up?
I suppose it's because the house was so worn down.
So what about the materials I thought of?
Just bring the materials. I think it can now fix itself.
Fix it! A full study, gloomy weeping willows!
It's saying so.
How do you know?
Know! Relocation on a whim! Suspicious lime tree!
Seriously, how do you know it?
I think I'm getting along well with the house.
I don't know about that.
But I do know how we can expand the house now.
Okay, how about we check out the underground workshop again?
I wonder what it will become!
This lizard reminds me of the one at the village fountain.
A spirit?
Yes. Spirits may dwell in houses built by witches or craftsmen.
Great! It's registered in the Encyclopedia!
Seems like you can't catch it right now. Do you know why?
How would I know!?
You might not know, but the [em1]Encyclopedia[/em1] does.
Take a closer look at the [em1]Encyclopedia[/em1].
Let's see here...
Now, do you see why you can't catch any?
Time
Take another look.
Location
Habit
Tool
Hmm... So, you can collect them using a [em1]bug net[/em1].
I don't have one right now, though.
Not much you can do then.
But, I want to do it right now!
Getting to the Witch's House in Highlion is more important.
Hmph...
Let's go back down now. There's gotta be something else that's fun.
But, you should finish cleaning up before you leave.
Oh, sure...
It seems like something's dropped on the floor.
Do I need to sweep the floor too?
Now I need to craft [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "MoonOil_Name"))][/em1].
Let’s use the [em1]Witch's Pot[/em1] to make potions first.
Got it.
I'll lend a hand too.
Isn't there anything I can help with?
Ellie, why don't you take a break this time?
You're always the one working the hardest. For once, just enjoy the festival.
Mm... alright, if you say so.
Don't worry! We'll put together the most amazing celebration you've ever seen!
Okay, I'll sit this one out, then.
Speaking of which, didn't Enite say she was stepping out for some fresh air? Where is she?
I think I saw her heading toward the [em1]large tree[/em1] earlier... let's go take a look.
What's everyone doing out here?
This wisteria tree... It's been on everyone's mind lately.
We're trying to figure out how to save it.
It's going to be tough.
It's still alive... but just barely.
It's been with us for so many years. It's practically one of the villagers itself.
So this is what Enite was so worried about earlier.
Yes. The people have all returned, but the tree... It's not what it used to be.
It's like someone never came back at all.
Let me take a closer look.
You will?
I don't know if it'll work... but I'll try.
Just... don't push yourself too hard.
Nothing lasts forever. When it's time to let go... we let go.
Alright, we've been away long enough. Let's head back.
The food will be prepared by me, Clala, and Arden.
Music will be Alvin and Kyla's department.
Then what should I be in charge of?
Ellie, you've worked so hard lately. This time, just enjoy the celebration.
Good.
It's nice to rest, but... feels a little too quiet for me.
Then think about how to save the [em1]wisteria tree[/em1].
It's ancient. None of the potions you know will be enough.
...Let's take another look and see if we can come up with something.
What's wrong, Enite?
It's nothing. Just... it seems like all the villagers are finally back.
It does look that way.
<shake>A festival!</shake>
A... festival?
<wave>A festival?</wave>
Everyone's returned! Let's throw a celebration to mark the occasion!
Hahaha! Now that's a good idea!
...Rex.
Huh? What?
No, he's right.
We've welcomed newcomers, and the old villagers are back together again. A festival would be perfect.
Yay! A festival!
I bet there'll be tons of delicious food, right?
Let's move somewhere else and talk details.
So, that means all the villagers have come back now, right?
So, how should we go about it?
Lots of tasty food! That's the most important part!
I can take care of that.
I'd love to have another concert.
Last time's performance didn't quite hit the mark.
Ooh! A concert! Dana's gonna sing!
Alright, alright. We'll take our time planning.
This is where the prickly vine core lies.
Now, let's gather everyone and plant the seed together!
[em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "BartenderLetter_Name"))][/em1], [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "SeedOfWisteria_Name"))][/em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Choice", "LetsBringItem"))]
Thank you all for coming together today.
I didn't know the Green Forest had a place like this.
It's a good spot. Smells nice, too.
This is where the prickly vine core once lay.
And the most vibrant, life-filled place in the forest.
The trees here almost seem to be breathing.
And the flowers... they look so cheerful.
Our purpose today is simple, to save the wisteria tree in the village.
The White Cat God has shown me the way.
First, we plant the seed and the letter gifted by the White Cat God.
And then use the trowel to plant the seed and flag in the ground.
...So... what do we do now?
I'm... not entirely sure.
You haven't changed a bit.
That's called staying true to my heart.
Haha! That's a good thing!
Honestly, you feel exactly the same as the day we met.
Back on that train, I just thought you seemed... different.
Someone with a warm heart.
That warmth hasn't faded—then or now.
Ah... you're making me blush.
I think your kindness hasn't changed, but I've also noticed something new.
You think more about others now, and you're not afraid to lean on them.
Maybe that's the kind of growth that comes from meeting so many people.
Is that true?
Of course! I'm still growing, after all.
Oh, wait—look! The seed... It's reacting.
It's moving! Something's happening!
Yes! Let's keep it up.
Ellie, you're the most beautiful woman in the world.
That's... not quite what I meant.
And Ellie loves to eat anything.
...I'll take that as a compliment. Thank you.
But instead of praising me, why don't we share our stories?
You saved me when I was tangled in a spider's web!
That's right. That's how we first met.
You healed my leg, brought me back to the village...
Things have been so much more fun since you arrived!
I agree.
The prickly vines are gone, the villagers have returned...
But more than that, Ellie, you've brought something good into the hearts of the people here.
I used to feel bored in Wisteria.
It's the countryside after all.
But when I left this time, it didn't feel right.
Like I'd left home. I kept wanting to come back.
So, thank you, Ellie, for being the first to write to me.
I feel the same.
I didn't appreciate the tranquility until I left.
And now, it's tranquil and full of life at the same time.
...Do I have to say something too?
Please, Arden.
I never planned to leave the village.
And if the houses collapsed, if everyone left?
Dragons live in caves by nature.
That's not the same...
That's... more like camping outside.
It's the same to me.
But...
But?
I like it the way it is now.
...What's that supposed to mean?
Ah! It sprouted!
Whoa! Amazing!
It's already grown, right after planting...
That must mean our bond is strong.
That's wonderful.
I'd better get back to preparing the festival, then.
Don't make a fuss.
No, thank you.
Yes. Ellie always worries about the village.
We should head back to the village now.
Ellie, will you join us?
If we want to plant the seed correctly, we'll have to dig deep enough.
Heave-ho! There, that should do it.
[em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "LittleConstellationRock_Name"))][/em1], [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Item", "SeedOfWisteria_Name"))][/em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Choice", "LetsBringItem"))]
Wow, thank you all for coming together!
It's more tiring than I thought.
Yeah! This is definitely a place worth exploring!
It's so beautiful here.
It really is.
Alright, let's plant the seed.
Now, why don't we all share some memories? Stories from the parade should be good.
That sounds fun!
It was the first time that I had so much fun performing.
I usually play alone, but performing together felt great.
Playing with several people at once was a real pleasure.
I didn't play any instrument, but marching in the parade was a lot of fun.
Watching others perform was enjoyable too.
I wasn't entirely satisfied with that concert.
The balance between instruments and different performers wasn't great, and the venue choice was poor.
Not to mention the stage props and setup.
It was the worst show I've ever been part of.
<shake>Alvin!</shake>
Well... despite all that...
It was fun.
Absolutely, I had a great time too.
Me too.
I was happy. And moved.
I'm not sure I've ever enjoyed playing the violin that much before.
It felt like a long-lost joy... Playing with that much happiness.
And Ellie, that night your flag was especially beautiful.
That's why I got interested in the flag. I keep thinking about how it looked back then.
But after inspecting it carefully, it turned out to be just a regular flag.
That night, the flag with red and gold glow was stunning. I borrowed one too.
But on closer look, the colors weren't anything special.
When Ellie held it, the patterns felt mysterious, but really, it was just an ordinary flag.
Even when I ran around holding it, it didn't feel like that night.
The flag itself isn't special.
It's what we did that night. The parade and concert we all shared made the flag extraordinary.
Even if the event wasn't perfect...
We can feel the special memories it left behind.
I felt the same way. I want to experience it all again.
It's sprouted.
Looks like the bonds we share are strong indeed.
That might be a bit much, don't you think?
Our village is the best!
Whew...
I hope we can hold another concert someday.
Let's do it again!
Yeah, anytime! Let's do it again!
Next time, we'll be even more prepared.
That's when it gets really fun.
It's not about preparation.
It's about sharing it together.
Yes.
Ellie, you've worked so hard for the village, both then and now.
Oh, come on now.
No, really. We're here thanks to you.
Exactly. Without you, Ellie, we wouldn't even be together like we are now.
And no parade or concert either!
That's true.
Coming here from the village, I can see how much you've been through.
Yeah, it's been really tough.
I was pretty lost before.
You've worked so hard on your own. Thank you.
Thanks for all your hard work.
Thank you, really.
I'm not one for sappy words.
It's okay. I'm just happy everyone came together like this.
Looks like it's over now. Shall we head back to the village?
Thanks for coming all this way.
This place might still be dangerous. Stay alert.
This... this place is amazing.
I hope to have adventures here someday.
I... I want to go on adventures too!
No way, Dana, didn't you hear Ellie? It's dangerous!
Hehe, looks like Dana's out of luck.
And you too.
Hey, why me?
Haha! Theo's out too.
Bjorn, you too.
<shake>Wha... What does that have to do with me?</shake>
Kids might try to follow you.
And it's dangerous, even for adults.
Kids learn from adults. We have to set the example.
Then let's enjoy this beautiful view while we still can.
Haha! The view keeps getting more spectacular!
Stars are falling and sparkling on the ground!
It's really jaw-dropping, right?
Of course! This really is where stars fall.
It gives me some inspiration for a new donut.
I probably won't get to come here often, so I'd better write it down right now.
Yep.
If you want to come again, just let me know. I'll take you here.
Alright, let's get started.
Now, tell me your wishes.
I want to be friends with everyone quickly!
I want to spend lots of time with everyone!
Sing, dance and eat donuts!
Haha! Dana's full of energy!
And I want to sing with Bjorn too!
Ahem... Okay, okay, I got it.
Not now!
I see. Maybe next time.
I'm not good at expressing myself.
No matter what I do, people say I'm scary.
You do look scary, hehe.
So I want to express myself without being misunderstood.
With gifts.
Gifts don't have scary faces or expressions. They only mean goodwill.
No room for misunderstandings. That's perfect.
I want to get close to villagers quickly and be a part of the family.
Family's exhausting.
But there are so many interesting things around here.
The more people to adventure with, the better.
Adventure! That sounds fun!
Count me in.
Really? Really?
You can play together, but not if it's too dangerous.
Alright, alright~
I want to be friends with everyone too.
Just to sell lots of donuts?
Of course, that's part of it.
I want people to be happy after eating my donuts.
But there's another reason.
My parents used to tell me stories about their time in Wisteria.
Mine too.
So did mine.
I often find myself missing the village when I'm away.
I think it's because of the villagers.
That's why I want to get along with everyone and understand what that feeling is like.
Maybe it'll be an inspiration for a new donut?
I hadn't come up with a design yet.
It'll be a great donut, and even be the signature donut that represents this village.
You're such a donut fanatic.
Is that a compliment? Thanks!
I love donuts.
Haha! Me too!
It's sprouted. Great job, everyone.
It's working!
The seed we just planted is sprouting...
It really is alive.
Looks like my singing helped!
Maybe my gifts worked.
Haha! Maybe it really likes the gifts we all prepared together!
Ellie put so much effort into this.
No, we all put our hearts into it.
We're just like one big family.
Yeah!
We've all grown closer without even realizing it.
I'm glad our feelings have been recognized.
So, should we head back now?
Yeah, it's time to go back.
Can't we spend a little more time with it?
I want to enjoy this beautiful view a little more.
I want to write down the inspiration I had.
I want to watch the sparkling stars a bit longer!
Alright, let's stay here a bit longer then.
I brought plenty of gifts for the villagers.
Well... about that...
Use the trowel to plant the seed and the flag in the ground.
We took a long time wandering around before coming back.
Phew, the seed is finally planted.
That was a bit tiring.
How about a break now?
No, I still have to think about potions for the festival.
I thought they wanted you to have a rest this time.
I can't help it.
I've already used all the potions I can.
Now, let's figure out what to do next.
Haven't you forgotten something?
Forgot what?
Ah, right! Did we forget to deliver candy yesterday?
Not that. Lisa said we should visit her after planting the seed.
Oh, that's right.
Let's go find Lisa then.
Looks like everyone we wanted to invite is here now.
I suppose it's time to start preparing for the festival?
Summoning shooting stars.
It's gonna be fun.
Ah! Just imagine. If the villagers all do it, it'll be wonderful.
Like when we set off firecrackers at the welcome party.
Do you think it might be dangerous?
If I do it right, it should be fine.
A little more diluted than what Lisa suggested.
Theo... give it a good shake before handing it to him.
Revenge time!
He will have black soot all over his face.
Just like when our faces got covered in flour.
Alright, let's mix the [lua(GetItemName("FirecrackerPotion"))] with the [lua(GetItemName("SpotlightPotion"))]...
Then we just need to find the ingredients for the [lua(GetItemName("FirecrackerPotion"))] in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
Once that's done, head over to Enite.
It really hasn't been easy for everyone to gather like this.
Before the festival begins, there's something I want to say.
Well.
I've come to realize that nothing lasts forever.
Everything must come to an end someday.
Before Ellie arrived, Rubrum and I sat in Arden's restaurant and thought about this.
I thought it was time to let go of this village, Wisteria.
I thought, 'It was fun until now...'
But then Ellie came, and everything came back to life.
First, Kyla and Roy returned.
Next, Vinch and Alvin arrived, and in the library, Rex and Arin joined as well.
Then Bjorn, all grown up, and Clala and Dana from the bakery, and Theo, the son of the teacher couple.
I still believe that nothing is forever.
That night... the night even Rubrum didn't come back.
I was scared of tomorrow coming. Because I saw the end.
But I didn't want to admit it. Because I love this village.
That night, when Ellie returned with Rubrum, I told Ellie to leave.
I was afraid of the future of this village. The future Ellie was trying so hard to save.
But Ellie, you didn't leave.
You just like the sun stubbornly rising each morning.
How could I have known that the future you were fighting for would be so beautiful?
Ellie, thank you for staying.
Because of you, I now look forward to tomorrow.
I look forward to the happy days here with all of you.
I want to express my gratitude to everyone who has returned.
I hope all the villagers who have gathered here, and those who helped us, enjoy today.
Now, since Ellie has something to say, I'll step aside for a moment.
I was also so happy to come to this village and meet everyone.
But not all the villagers are here yet.
What do you mean, Ellie? Aren't all the villagers here, except for those who moved away?
Just a moment, you can come out now.
You can come out now.
Hello, it's been a long time... everyone.
And some new faces here as well. Hello, I'm Lisa Whitegarden.
Lisa...? Is that really you?
It's me, Enite. There's so much I want to talk about, but first...
Before anything else, there's something I want to say to all of you, the residents of Wisteria.
I am truly sorry.
The prickly vines covering the village are, without a doubt, my fault.
It's my fault that everyone's village was destroyed and everyone had to leave. Once again, I am sorry.
You don't need to be sorry.
Arden, I...
I owe you a great debt.
So do all the villagers.
Of course, this was your mistake, but...
You've given us so much more in return.
I feel the same way.
You've been helping us all the time.
I'm not sure if I should say this...
But fixing the village is all that matters now.
Heehee! That's right! Ellie can take care of the troublesome prickly vines.
I'll fix the broken buildings.
And we'll repair the broken bridge together.
I'm more worried about you, Lisa.
You've been in this village longer than anyone.
This village means a lot to you.
I can't imagine how much you must have suffered...
But I'm still...
It's because everyone trusts you.
The kindness you showed us remains.
You must have had a reason.
Exactly! You don't look like a bad witch!
We've received a lot of help from Lisa.
Haha! Of course! Lisa could never be a villain!
Let me explain what happened.
The tree...?
It's healed!
Wow! It's so beautiful!
Haha! The tree is back to how I remember it as a kid!
Just like that...
It must be our strong bonds!
It's everyone's... connection.
As Arin said, this is something all of us have achieved together.
Because Ellie, this village, and everyone share a strong bond.
Lisa too, right?
Yes... yes. Me too, of course.
I'm part of this village too.
So, Enite, shall we continue?
Ah, yes. I never thought such a happy day would come.
Let's begin the festival.
Is everyone here?
The concert was wonderful. Everyone's skills are getting better.
Today truly feels like a special day.
We prepared a gift for Ellie, who made a day like this possible.
For me?
It felt like we never gave you a proper gift.
Please, accept this.
What's this...? A wisteria tree?
That's right.
It's a wisteria tree that started shrinking after the village was taken over by prickly vines.
This little sprout has become a symbol of hope for me.
Just like you, Ellie.
That's why I want you to have it.
Wow, thank you so much!
I'll take good care of it.
I also prepared something for today.
Here, please accept this.
Now, when I give the signal, please shake the potion.
You just need to shake it exactly four and a half times.
Be careful, as it might explode.
One... two...
Three!
Wow!
Wow! A shooting star!
Wow, never seen anything like it...
It's so pretty...
We created this together.
This beautiful shooting star, and this village too.
Lisa...?
Huh? The Cat Gods?
What brings the Black Cat God here?
I... I thought everything had failed.
I thought I could never build my own garden again.
But I was wrong.
Ellie told me that everyone built it together.
This place... all of you... It's my precious garden.
My time has come to an end.
The night has fallen.
The day has passed.
Darkness cloaks the sky.
Light has gone far away.
When stars fall from the night sky.
When stars return once more.
May the deep darkness bless them.
May the radiant light bless them.
Lisa...
The Cat Gods? Why are you reciting the old farewell words...?
I'm sorry I couldn't tell you.
Lisa...? But...
But you said you would come back.
I didn't want to ruin such a beautiful day.
That's why I kept it to myself.
But if you leave too, then what would I do now...?
Enite...
I entrust my garden to you.
If it's you, I know it will be well cared for.
...Ok.
You will be a great witch.
Of course.
Follow the path you want to take. I couldn't, but you will be able to do more.
Lisa, you did it too, in the end.
...Yes, I did. Hehe, you're right, I did it too.
Ellie. Please tell Dosca.
I'm happy to give her my name.
Tell her that I will bless my granddaughter, Lisa.
Yes! I will.
Thank you all. Today is the happiest day of my life.
Don't be sad—smile instead. On such a beautiful day...
Goodbye, Lisa.
Thank you for everything. The garden... the village... I'll take good care of it.
Stars fall to the earth.
Stars return to the sky.
In deep darkness.
In radiant light.
Night goes.
Day comes.
And as always, tomorrow comes.
May the skies tonight be indigo.
May it be a dazzling morning.
It's a happy ending.
Yes, it is.
I had fun, too.
Why are you so quiet?
Time keeps flowing.
Children grow up.
Aria would be happy to see this.
Couldn't do this without you.
Even though you're a little cocky.
But you're still a good guide.
...This is a little more cringe-inducing than I thought.
Yes, you're right. But it's still a happy ending.
The festival is over now.
But there's no need to feel sad.
Because tomorrow will come?
Exactly. Because all the villagers are finally here.
The future of Wisteria is just beginning.
Here we are, in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))]!
It's so spacious!
I think I sense danger.
You always do.
By the way, did the star land somewhere around here?
Where's the fallen star?
It must have gained much momentum from the long fall.
I suppose it's [em1]at the bottom of the cave[/em1].
Alright, let's go find it!
Something probably has slipped your mind...
Of course I will follow the [em1]prickly vine traces[/em1].
If Lisa is here, she should also be somewhere near the fallen star.
Bear that in mind.
Look over there!
There's a weird door-like structure.
But it has a witch sigil on it as well.
Why's there a barrier between me and every place I want to be in?
That means those are places you shouldn't be in.
I'll come back when I've got a [em1]Witch's Blue Chalk[/em1].
Look! There seems to be a board over there that leads downward.
I wonder if it still functions.
I believe so, since all the doors and switches are still functioning.
Hm? Did you hear that?
There's something on the ground. What is it?
Is this... a sculpture?
It isn't finished...
Looks like a bird cage, but why would anyone make a bird cage out of a rock?
Maybe it was meant for ornamentation only.
Well... I guess you're right...
Wait, come to think of it, I've found [em1]a bird cage beside every prickly vine core[/em1]...
And I feel like the same white marble has been used in [em1]Lisa's sculptures[/em1].
After all, white marble sculptures are typical in the Whitegarden style.
Are you saying that this belongs to Lisa?
That I cannot say for sure.
Right... Wait, there's a memo.
This cave is more dangerous than I expected, especially for inexperienced witches.
I should seal it off.
But you've already gotten inside.
Calling a place dangerous only makes me more eager to explore it.
Is the big guy just now the source of danger?
But who wrote this memo?
Could it be Lisa?
That's a groundless guess.
Wait, it has words on the back too.
V Gather star shards.
V Buy lunch.
V Remove the sculpture of Tanis.
V Seal the second entrance.
Clean the camp.
Look! It really was Lisa!
Now it's a proven guess.
And judging from the condition of her items, she must have been here until recently.
Like I suspected, Lisa must have descended in search of the star.
Let's go down as well. If we find the star, we find Lisa.
But didn't she call the place dangerous?
Every place can be dangerous.
Both the prickly vine and that big guy go this way. We must do the same.
Let's descend!
This place is also strewn with step boards.
All the used weights are gone.
So they are.
And I don't think there are enough weights left...
You need to summon all the Ellies.
There's only one Ellie!
Try to [em1]do the work of two Ellies[/em1] then.
Well... I'll see if there's a potion I can use.
Alright, the door's open.
You really can do the work of two Ellies.
That's what that potion does!
Let's go to the step board we saw before.
Keep an eye out for that big guy.
Hmm... I think I'm supposed to descend, but a barrier is in my way.
And its switch is turned off.
There's no starry flash on this side.
I think I can probably get it across if I throw really hard.
It's a long distance. Are you sure?
Then I need to somehow power my throw further.
Build the muscles of your right arm?
That will take forever. At least two years if I want to throw twice as far.
I'm a witch! Witches use potions!
Awesome!
Can't stop me with such a tiny gap~
Can't stop the potion, you mean.
Potions don't work on their own.
Let's get outside.
Phew, the deepest part's finally behind us.
We're still in the cave though.
There are more barriers.
I don't think they are of the same shape as the previous ones, though.
You're right!
There seems to be some sort of [em1]bell[/em1], although I can't see it clearly.
I guess you need to ring the bell for the door to open.
The prickly vine seems to go downward.
Anyway, I'll look around for a way to lift the barrier.
Like before, there's something on the ground.
Does this also belong to Lisa?
It is... a memo pad? And a trowel.
Why is Lisa so disorganized?
It isn't that surprising if you recall the state the Witch's House was in when we first saw it.
It's a weird diary, but it's readable.
The ecosystem here is cursed.
Most of the sunlight is blocked out. Only starlight manages to seep through layer after layer of darkness.
The land is dry and cracked, the soil as barren as death itself.
However, the place is home to stunning fauna and flora.
Like a forest under the night sky, or a temple where the moon and the stars are worshipped.
But it only indicates a curse more dangerous and deep-rooted.
Tanis's witch brooch remains missing.
Does that mean she
The writing ends abruptly.
That sounds ominous.
After all, it's a curse she's talking about.
And the name "Tanis" sounds familiar...
Why was Lisa looking for Tanis's witch brooch?
Probably to confirm Tanis's [em1]death[/em1].
Right, since witches always carry their witch brooches with them...
But why is that? And there's that curse thing...
You should think about what the White Cat God said.
Hm? What did they say?
"Whatever you see, just ignore it."
Are you telling me not to overinterpret things?
The White Cat God should be more familiar with this place.
And when it comes to exploration, one thing is for sure:
Lies, deception and misunderstanding cause more failures than physical hazards.
"A reasonable degree of neglect is an explorer's virtue."
Is it Mom you're quoting? I remember that line.
Right, although Aria tends to forget about virtues once she gets excited.
Of course, unknown fauna, flora and treacherous landscapes are dangerous in their own ways.
I don't sense a curse though.
And we know little about this Tanis.
My point is...
That we should be cautious, right? I understand.
Okay, let's keep going. Be cautious and reasonably neglectful.
Good, it's finally open.
Let's see... the prickly vine seems to be reaching down this cliff.
But how do I get down there?
From the tunnel we entered just now?
We've wandered every corner of that tunnel.
And there was no path leading deeper.
What if that giant hole was a passage created by the fallen star?
A passage created by the fallen star?!
Right, if the star fell through the rocks when it landed...
Then the star should be at the bottom?!
Right, and witches who studied the star are also...
In that case, there must be a device that leads down!!
Right...
Is that it?
I can't quite see it from here. It's too far.
Judging from the location, it should be the one.
But to get to it...
I need to lift the step board down there.
Let's check on that board.
Now I can get past.
How on earth did people navigate this place before?
Maybe time has rendered the bridge unfunctional.
Let's go down and check it out now.
Is this the hole created by the star?
It goes so deep. I can't see the bottom.
After all, it fell all the way from the sky.
That means I'm traveling the same path as the star did.
It traveled much faster than you do, though.
I know. But at this rate, Rubrum will have grown up when I'm back on the surface.
If you dive at a star's speed, you will become Ellie Red-river.
Hey, stop shaking me. Virgil, I'm not that scared.
I'm a hat. All that I can shake is your brains.
You—huh? Wait, do I see something glowing down there?
Woah, look, Virgil! It's the star!
The star has really fallen through that hole!
And so has Ellie.
Right, and I've survived the fall just like the star.
But what exactly is that guy?
Thanks to that whale-like thing, I almost fell to my death!
It's a flying whale.
I know. It's amazing indeed.
A giant flying whale!
And it can go through obstacles.
It certainly is amazing...
But it <shake>almost killed me</shake>!
And I don't get what it is thinking!
How would we possibly know what such a creature is thinking?
We can't even understand an ordinary whale.
But it has obviously caused us danger.
Maybe we shouldn't blame all of that on it.
As you said, before it came, the bubble was already quaking.
Well... that's true...
But it almost shook my life out of me!
Maybe it was trying to save you from the fall.
That... could be the case...
Alright, I'll just find it and ask it directly.
You are going to "ask" a giant flying whale?
Why can't I ask a whale questions when I've been chatting with a hat all the time?
You just hurt my pride badly.
I'll look around this place.
And examine the star on my way!
We need to locate quite a few things.
Right, such as the [em1]prickly vine core[/em1] and [em1]Lisa[/em1].
We should be quite close now.
Another barrier?
Witches here do remember to lock their doors behind them.
That may suggest there's something valuable in there.
Right.
Time for the bell hunting. There are 2 this time.
Is this... a backpack?
And there are bits of memo everywhere.
What in the world was Lisa doing...
Honestly, this has become a bit unnerving.
I don't think a person in their right mind would litter things like this.
I'll tell Lisa you said so when I meet her.
Lisa deserves the criticism.
What do the memos say?
There are messages about a myriad of things.
I may need to redefine the meaning of <lunaphobic>. The "luna" here should mean more than the moon itself.
Turn the fire down... Add a pinch of [lua(GetItemName("PumpkinTerrier_Powder"))] and a spoonful of [lua(GetItemName("BubbleLizard_Water"))]. Stir anticlockwise. Add one [lua(GetItemName("OneEyeFrog_Powder"))]...
I haven't found [em1]the key to Tanis's workshop[/em1], but hardly any witch manages to come here anyway.
With its giant form, the [em1]Starwhale[/em1] soars through the sky as if swimming. Both the creature itself and the way it blends into the environment are absolutely stunning.
However, the moment I think of what's inside it, I find it ominous — a cursed creature.
Starwhale? Could it be...
The thing that took us for a ride.
So, it's called a Starwhale!
By the sound of it, the creature's quite dangerous?
But you said that it could be trying to save us.
I don't know.
One thing is for sure. Lisa isn't a big fan of the Starwhale.
That's one more thing to talk to Lisa about when I meet her!
I'll follow traces of the prickly vine for now.
The traces stretch quite a distance that way.
The witch sigil here hasn't been erased. It saves the trouble.
Look carefully. There's a [em1]starry flash[/em1] on the side.
Oops, indeed.
Hmm... The [em1]witch sigil can't be used[/em1] when there's a starry flash around. What now?
And you can't blow the starry flash out when it's cased.
I need to work out a way.
Maybe a [em1]potion[/em1] as well.
If I can't move it, I shall cover it up.
Now, back to follow the prickly vine.
Oh my... This is spectacular...
It's stunning in all ways.
You can say that again. A shame the prickly vines ruined such a beautiful view.
Nothing looks more out of place than these prickly vines.
Can I remove these like I always do...?
Your guess is as good as mine. Give it a shot.
Alright, it can't be helped.
Firstly, I'll go to the White Cat God and get the [lua(GetItemName("SacredWater_Water#Important"))].
But you need to remove the bird cage too. How do you plan to get to the cage?
I don't know. We do have a lot to figure out.
I'll explore the cave more. There's got to be a way.
Look over there.
You may spot an old friend of ours.
Huh? Where?
Over there, beyond the prickly vines.
Where...
Oh, indeed! It's the Starwhale!
Let me have a closer look.
Hm? The flower seems to have shrunken.
That Sunlight Potion must be subpar.
I suppose selling it will soon become illegal.
Off to the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
Wait, is that...
The campsite?
This must be Lisa's base of operation when studying the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
But we haven't proved that this is Lisa's campsite.
By the look of it, it can hardly be anything else.
Okay, you've got a point.
I don't see Lisa around. Could she be in the tent?
Could be.
Alright... I'll look around first.
Or you can go straightly into the tent.
Many books are lying open.
Let's see... Lunaphobic Plants, Hiddes: A World Under the Night Sky, Fallen Stars...
They are all about plants and the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
Looks like Lisa is studying stars and plants at the same time.
I suppose so.
There are more...
The Meaning of Life, Forest of Witches, On Stellar Magic...
The topics are varied.
Lisa has started to think about the meaning of life.
I've read Forest of Witches. It was on the required reading list back at school.
Do you remember the content?
It was about how witches live and die. I remember it clearly, since it was profound.
"Years of practicing magic, a power originating from nature, close the gap between the body of a witch and nature itself."
"As a result, an older witch turns into wind and becomes one with nature upon her death, leaving not a trace behind her."
"However, a witch will leave a body if she dies prematurely."
"A witch who dies young will be buried at the foot of a tree."
"There's a site for such burials near Luminaria Edis, known as the Forest of Witches."
That counts as a book about plants as well.
It's a book about death and the circle of life.
But dying prematurely or not, a witch always becomes part of nature.
For you, books are just collections of head-scratching theories, though.
Because they always try to figure out things.
That's why we got all the demanding tests.
Lisa was probably using this book to study the nature of magic.
Does every witch have one of such portable pots?
It's too heavy to be called "portable."
Maybe it should be renamed as a "camping pot"?
It's certainly not for witches that run about all the time, such as yourself.
Right, it can be useful for witches like Lisa, who are stationed at a place for research.
This may become handy.
It's broken. What a shame.
I suppose nobody's maintaining it.
Wait, there's something on the ground...
There's one more.
[lua(GetItemName("BubbleLizard_Water"))] and [lua(GetItemName("PumpkinTerrier_Powder"))]?
Was Lisa crafting something?
Crafting is what you do with pots.
A potion or candy made from [lua(GetItemName("BubbleLizard_Water"))] and [lua(GetItemName("PumpkinTerrier_Powder"))]. Sounds fun. I want to see it.
There's another garden.
It's not surprising. She's here to study plants.
But she could have planted them anywhere in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
Soil may not be consistent even if it's in the same cave.
Isn't soil basically the same everywhere?
You need to take your gardening course again.
Everything I grew for that course thrived, and all that I did was water them.
Can't argue with that. Even your teacher was amazed by your peculiar talent.
Wait, are these prickly vines in this garden?
Why are they so limp?
Because no one's tending to them?
S-shall we knock on the door?
You could simply shout.
They can probably hear you.
H-hello...
May I see Miss Lisa Whitegarden?
You're being very polite.
After all, it's our first meeting.
I don't think anyone's in.
Forgive me for pushing in then...
Umm... well... this place is also empty.
Where on earth has Lisa gone to?
We've searched everywhere possible...
Could she have gone to another world?
Don't you curse her, Virgil!
Isn't rummaging through her tent worse than cursing her?
I'm only doing it to find Lisa.
Wait, look at this.
It's a piece of [lua(GetItemName("WitchChalk_Blue"))].
And there are some sort of notes.
... In addition, lunaphobic plants cannot even grow properly in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
They can't sprout when near a starry flash or a star.
That leads to one assumption: "Lunaphobic" plants are not afraid of the moon, but [em1]afraid of night[/em1].
(Perhaps the so-called power of the moon is just one of many powers of the night...)
However, such powers will no longer impact the plant once it has matured.
It takes [em1]a strong presence of night[/em1] to remove such plants, such as the light of a full moon.
After all, stars are not immortal lives.
Lisa has apparently been studying prickly vines too during her stay here.
But she said that "lunaphobic" plants didn't grow well in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))]...
How did that prickly vine core manage to thrive?
Well, the prickly vine is a plant engineered by Lisa.
It could have received a buff from all the different characteristics combined in it?
Hmm... could be the case.
It's just my assumption.
Anyway, let's make some Moon Tears first.
I wonder if there are more than her diary...
Don't rummage through someone else's dwelling like that.
But this may be the last location unsearched.
If she's not in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))], I can't think of another place to look into... hm?
Whatever your reason, it's rude to ransack someone else's bed.
Virgil, could this be...?
It's a witch brooch.
<shake>A witch brooch!!</shake>
If her witch brooch is in her bed, it means...
Usually, it means she passed away in her sleep.
<shake>Just what I was thinking!</shake>
No day... Is Lisa... [em1]dead already[/em1]?
This can't be. But... the White Cat God...
Could she have left without the brooch?
As you know, a witch does not take off her brooch as long as she lives.
It's because witches vanish upon death.
The witch brooch is proof that they were here.
I know that...
<shake>But... if that's the case...</shake> Why?
Are you chewing the White Cat God's words?
Why did they lie to me?
Remember what the White Cat God said?
That Lisa was at [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))]?
Not that. They said something else about the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
This should be the thing they were referring to.
How could anyone ignore this!
Lisa died here ages ago?!
The White Cat God may not be aware of it either, although the situation suggests otherwise.
They said "ignore it," which indicates that they had known it this whole time.
But why would they deceive me?
And they've been doing it from the very beginning?
To get you to remove the prickly vine cores?
I would have done it anyway! They didn't have to lie!
I don't get it. Why? <shake>Why did they...?</shake>
Let's remove the prickly vine core first.
Virgil, you sound like the White Cat God.
The prickly vine core's existence is objective.
And it's plaguing both the village and the Starwhale.
As for the other things, you can ask the White Cat God when we're back.
Alright... I guess you're right.
Although their action totally baffles me.
Anyway, I'll take this brooch with me.
And I'll definitely pry an explanation out of the White Cat God.
But what do I do now?
Do what you should do.
You mean removing the prickly vine core.
Haven't you got the [lua(GetItemName("WitchChalk_Blue"))]?
Right, there was that large door up there.
I'll remove the prickly vine core.
For the Starwhale and the villagers.
I-I guess I should look somewhere else first.
Delaying it won't do you any good.
<shake>I'll delay it regardless.</shake>
There’s nothing more to see here.
Alright... I think I'm starting to get it.
So you're really gonna fix the village first?
The White Cat God is obviously hiding something.
Hiding what, exactly?
No idea.
But it definitely [em1]has something to do with Lisa[/em1].
Lisa's dead. What could there possibly be to hide?
That's exactly it!
What if [em1]Lisa's still alive[/em1]?
But you're the one who found her brooch.
A witch's brooch doesn't prove she's dead.
She could be in hiding, leaving the brooch behind to make it look like she's gone.
Using the usual assumptions about witches as a trick, huh?
Right. Most witches, if they see a brooch lying around without its owner, assume that the witch is dead.
So you just drop the brooch somewhere, and everyone thinks you're done for.
And the White Cat God helps her pull it off?
Then I stumble across the brooch...
...making you the witness to her "death."
And while they're at it, they'd also have me clear out that prickly vine core.
That does line up a little too neatly.
Which would explain why the White Cat God acted so strangely.
They'd need time to pass the letter to her while she's in hiding.
If that's true, though, why would Lisa hide in the first place?
No clue. That's what I want to ask her.
It's not impossible, but you've got zero [em1]evidence[/em1].
Then we look for her. If it doesn't work out, so be it.
We can finish fixing up the village afterwards.
But how do you plan to find her? We've searched everywhere already.
That's because the White Cat God's been lying to us.
Now... hmm...
Maybe I should ask [em1]Diane[/em1] about a tracking potion.
Always Diane, isn't it?
What's wrong with a witch using the Witches' Catalogue?
The simplest solution is usually the best one.
Let's go see Diane.
Feels like it's been ages since I last came here.
Let's see if we can find the [em1]bartender's letter[/em1].
...I could've sworn it was around here somewhere.
Maybe someone took it?
Hm. Let's ask Enite.
Can't imagine anyone here would have a reason to steal it.
Huh? What's with this feather?
If a villager found it, they might've picked it up to return it to its owner.
True... they could've taken it to deliver it back.
Oh, hey. What's going on?
Ellie's wondering if you've seen a letter out by the forest railroad.
If you mean a black envelope, yeah. I saw it once.
Uh-huh. Last time I was there, it was still lying around.
It's gone now... so someone must've taken it since then.
Could've been the [em1]Gaga Bird[/em1].
The Gaga Bird?
Yeah, that bird snatches up anything it fancies.
Now that you mention it... There was a feather where the letter used to be.
Ah! That's definitely the Gaga Bird.
<shake>That bird again?</shake>
Hey, at least it's a good courier in its own way.
Then maybe it's time we buried that bird... right next to a seed.
Don't. That's another genre.
Rubrum, do you know where the Gaga Bird takes the stuff it steals?
Took one of my toys, too.
Great... we've found the culprit, but not the loot.
Oh, that reminds me. Last time the Gaga Bird took something, another villager helped get it back.
Wait, last time?
The letter?
Yeah. Black envelope.
So... where do we even start looking?
Really? Who helped?
Hold on, I'll go find them.
What's all the commotion?
Heard Ellie's looking for something for the good of the village.
Can we make this quick? I've got a restaurant to run.
The Gaga Bird stole something important. Any idea where it might stash its loot?
Ha! That busy little thief is at it again? Never stops working.
Don't ask me.
When I was gathering ingredients in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_GreenForest"))], I'd see it all the time...
Usually wandering between the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Map", "GreenForest_Waterfall"))] and the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Map", "GreenForest_Deep"))][/em1].
Right, I think I saw it there too when I was clearing out that prickly vine core.
I haven't seen the Gaga Bird often, but... I do know what [em1]flower it likes[/em1].
Really? Which one?
[em1]Asrahi[/em1]. A glowing purple flower that mostly blooms in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_GreenForest"))].
Last time it took Rubrum's toy, we found it in a [em1]spot thick with Asrahi[/em1].
And it's taken another one of my toys.
Thanks, Roy.
I'll find it this time.
Yeah. Now that we know the spot, it should be easy.
Just check between the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Map", "GreenForest_Waterfall"))] and the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Map", "GreenForest_Deep"))][/em1], [em1]where the Asrahi's in full bloom[/em1].
Here. Take this.
A [em1]bird-chasing bell[/em1]. I use it at the restaurant to keep that thing away. Figured you might need it.
Alright, I'm off.
Take care, now.
So this place does exist...
Hm. Guess the Gaga Bird's not here right now.
Better search while I've got the chance.
My bag is full.
If I'm going to take the letter back, I'll need to clear some room first.
Let's make at least [em1]2 slots free[/em1].
So this is the bird's nest, huh?
Even shaped it to look just like itself.
Careful with that tone.
Please, after all the trouble it's caused, I'm allowed to be a little harsh.
Hm... nothing visible on the outside...
Whoa! Why is this thing so <shake>solid!</shake>
No way I'm getting through with my hands.
Guess it's a skilled nest-builder.
More like it just crammed in a bunch of junk...
A sturdy nest is a good nest.
Hmph. You think I'm gonna lose to a pile of twigs?
Let's see how it likes my shovel.
Wow... it really stuffed in everything.
Looks like your school locker.
Then you know I'm an expert at digging through one of these.
Huh... is this the toy Rubrum mentioned?
So the Gaga Bird did take it.
Let's dig a bit more.
Ugh! There you are, finally.
Sorry for wrecking your nest, but maybe don't steal everything.
Pretty sure it has no idea what you're saying.
Yeah, probably.
Anyway, I still need to find the bartender's letter.
Time to try out that bell Arden gave me.
Looks like it's working.
...And it's flying off!
Perfect! Let's grab the letter while we can.
Got it. Finally.
Time to get out of here.
Whew, made it out.
Letter for the bartender, toy for Rubrum—two birds, one stone.
More like one bird, a lot of rocks.
First things first. Let's get Rubrum his toy back.
Then we'll gather everyone and head to the prickly vine core in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_GreenForest"))].
Alright, I think I've got the hang of this. Not so hard after all.
So next is... the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))]?
Wonder what I'll find in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))].
That weird guy?
Huh? The Honey Bear? No, he's not a villager.
If it's something involving the villagers...
Oh! The [em1]parade[/em1]!
That was when more people had moved in. Everyone joined in for the parade, the concert, and the party. It was so much fun.
Not that it was perfectly done.
We were all beginners back then.
Still fun, though.
Oh! Then I can use the [em1]flag[/em1] from back then.
If we all march around it. It should create a strong enough bond!
Do you even know who has it now?
Hmm... I think I gave it to someone...
Ah—pretty sure it was [em1]Arin[/em1]. Let's go ask.
Okay, let's piece this together...
Arin gave it to Vinch...
Vinch gave it to Alvin...
And Alvin gave it to Rex, right?
Then Rex gave it back to Arin.
And so the next lap begins.
<shake>Ahhhh!</shake>
Now that's what I call a "bond."
Everyone's definitely connected now.
This is ridiculous!
So... [em1]who has the flag right now[/em1]?
Think calmly.
Nobody's mentioned giving it to anyone outside this group.
Which means [em1]one of these four people[/em1] still has it.
Highly likely.
But do you know which one?
Not a clue.
Guess I'll have to call them all in and get more details.
You're really going to summon the suspects like that?
Suspects?
The [em1]flag thief[/em1], obviously.
A thief hunt? Sounds fun!
But honestly, I doubt anyone stole it.
Probably just set it down somewhere, forgot, or got mixed up.
So there's no harm in calling everyone together.
Once we've got them all in one place, we'll figure something out.
<shake>Everyone, gather up!!</shake>
What's going on?
I heard it's about the village wisteria and the parade flag.
Ah, it's the thing you asked about earlier. Still haven't found it?
Yes, that's right. That's why I called everyone here.
Let me explain.
To fix the town's wisteria tree, we need the flag that was used in the parade.
But when I asked around, no one seemed to know where it was. That's why I gathered everyone here.
Arin, could you start by describing the flag [em1]in detail[/em1]?
I borrowed it from [em1]Rex[/em1].
I wanted to study the pattern on the flag, so I asked him to lend it to me.
While I was examining it, I noticed the [em1]colors of the pattern had faded a little.[/em1]
Once I finished my research, I passed it on to [em1]Vinch[/em1].
Vinch, can you continue from there?
I saw the flag on a desk in the library and asked [em1]Arin[/em1] if I could borrow it.
I really wanted to [em1]draw it[/em1] exactly as it appeared during the parade.
So I drew it [em1]as faithfully as I could[/em1].
While I was painting it, Alvin asked to borrow the flag.
I finished the painting and then lent the flag to [em1]Alvin[/em1].
And Alvin?
I kept thinking about the texture of the flag from the parade. I wanted to study it a bit.
When I saw [em1]Vinch[/em1] carrying it, I asked if I could borrow it, and he agreed.
I asked Enite about checking the material, and even [em1]cut off a small piece[/em1] to examine it.
While researching, I left it briefly at the sundries store, and [em1]Rex[/em1] asked to borrow it.
My research wasn't finished, but it wasn't urgent, so I let him take it.
Okay, Rex?
So, I stopped by the [em1]sundries store[/em1] and saw something amazing—the parade flag.
It seemed perfect timing, so I asked [em1]Alvin[/em1] about it.
He said I could take it from the [em1]sundries store[/em1], so I borrowed it.
I wanted to carry it around myself, just like you did...
After a while, [em1]Arin[/em1] asked to borrow it, so I passed it on.
That's it?
<shake>Y-Yeah! I'm not carrying it now!</shake>
Ugh... alright.
The truth is, I broke the [em1]flagpole[/em1] while carrying it.
<shake>What!?</shake>
Here's the flagpole.
Figures you'd break something.
<shake>H-Hey,</shake> but I'm not carrying the flag now, that's true!
That's right. I clearly remember only receiving the flag...
So... it doesn't really matter, then.
Does anyone else remember anything important?
I made a mistake while studying the pattern, and [em1]the moon part[/em1] of the design turned [em1]silver[/em1].
Here is the [em1]painting of the flag[/em1]. It might be useful.
Here is the [em1]piece of flag[/em1] that I cut out for my research.
Are we in a detective novel? It's going to be challenging!
What? Detective novel? Sounds cool!
So, are we the suspects?
Looking for a flag thief? Interesting.
Probably it's just that someone accidentally forgot about it.
I'll find out who.
It does have a nice sense of [em1]bonding[/em1].
We just need to find it now.
There must have been someone who got the flag in the first place, and someone who has the flag now.
Hmm... Let's think about it.
Listen to others again? Review the information? Or... point at someone?
Hear the stories again
Whose story should I hear again?
Listen to others again? Point at someone? Or... Ask Virgil for a hint?
Ask Virgil for a hint
Virgil, any hints?
The flag didn't just appear out of nowhere among these four.
[em1]The one who received it first[/em1] must've obtained the flag from someone outside this group.
It might look like a confusing tangle, but really [em1]it's just a straight line[/em1].
Who got it [em1]first[/em1]? Who has it [em1]now[/em1]?
Everyone obtained the flag [em1]from someone[/em1], then passed the flag to the [em1]next person[/em1].
So someone must have received it [em1]twice[/em1].
If only one person received it twice, they're likely the [em1]first recipient[/em1].
And since they didn't pass it on after that, they must still have it.
Go back to the start—[em1]who got it first[/em1]?
Want a clearer hint?
Some of the evidence from people's statements is [em1]impossible[/em1].
The results, however, are real.
That means the [em1]original assumption[/em1] must be wrong.
Try forming a new theory that makes the "impossible" evidence possible.
How would the events need to unfold for this evidence to make sense?
No, I'll think it through myself.
Want me to share my deduction?
I'll tell you who's the culprit.
Yes, please. I have no idea.
The culprit is [em1]Vinch[/em1].
Vinch?
Look at Vinch's drawing.
The pole is intact, the pattern's color is different, and there's no sign of cutting.
The flag passed from Alvin to Rex, Arin and finally Vinch...
Alvin cut the flag, Rex broke the pole, and Arin changed the pattern color.
If Vinch drew the flag from Arin, how should it look?
The flag would be cut, missing the pole... and the pattern color would be changed.
Yet Vinch's drawing shows the pole intact, pattern color altered, and no corner missing.
What does it mean?
I cannot know for sure what happened.
I just know Vinch's drawing couldn't have been made from the [em1]flag he received from Arin[/em1].
So there must be a theory that explains it.
If you want to know, ask Vinch yourself.
Alright, let's talk to [em1]Vinch[/em1].
Review information
The color of the pattern.
When I got it, I think the pattern was already [em1]silver[/em1].
Hmm... I didn't look too closely at the color, so I can't remember.
I don't remember either.
Flag fragment
I [em1]cut off a small piece[/em1], with Enite's permission, to study the material.
I don't recall anything that small...
When I got it, it was [em1]already cut[/em1].
When I drew the painting, the flag [em1]looked intact[/em1].
Vinch's painting
This is the flag I drew.
(The pole is intact. The pattern color is silver. The corner is still attached.)
Hmm... nothing too unusual.
Broken flagpole
I broke it while carrying it...
When I received it, the pole was [em1]broken[/em1]. I only got the flag.
Same here, I only got the [em1]flag[/em1] from Arin.
Hmm... I got it with the [em1]pole intact[/em1].
Point at someone
Who's carrying the parade flag and forgot about it?
The culprit is... [lua(GetLocalizedString("InteractableObject", "People_Arin"))]!
Me? But I passed it on to Vinch.
That's right. I got it from Arin.
Uh... maybe not...?
Think carefully.
The culprit is... [lua(GetLocalizedString("InteractableObject", "People_Vinch"))]!
Me? But I left it at the sundries store, I swear.
But look at this.
This is the drawing Vinch made of the flag.
Vinch said he drew it [em1]exactly as he saw it[/em1], right?
The culprit is... [lua(GetLocalizedString("InteractableObject", "People_Alvin"))]!
Me?
When Vinch passed the flag to Alvin, he left it at the [em1]sundries store[/em1].
Yeah, that's right.
Did you meet Alvin [em1]directly[/em1] at that time?
Uh... no. I don't think we met in person.
Rex, when you borrowed it from Alvin, did you meet him directly?
Huh? Uh... yeah, I asked him in person.
Did you get the flag handed to you [em1]directly[/em1]?
No, I took it from the [em1]sundries store[/em1].
So when Alvin passed the flag, no one actually [em1]met in person[/em1].
True... but why does that matter?
It's easy to misremember something you didn't see directly.
So it's basically my mistake.
Right. I don't think anyone would lie just to keep the flag.
Did you receive it from someone else the same way Vinch did?
Like Enite leaving it at the sundries store...
Hmm... ah, yes, that makes sense.
Does that jog your memory?
Yes, now I remember.
After the parade, I suddenly thought about the flag Ellie was carrying.
I asked Enite about it. Enite said Rubrum had it.
I couldn't go to Rubrum at the time, so Enite said she'd pass the message.
Later, when I met Rubrum, he said he left it at the [em1]sundries store[/em1].
I think I saw it there briefly.
And... no way...
Right after, I met Rex.
After that, I forgot about the flag for a while.
When I saw it with Vinch later, I asked for it without thinking.
I guess I mistakenly thought I lent it to Rex.
So is it still at the sundries store?
Seems like it... If what I saw was left by Rubrum, then I probably didn't see where Vinch placed the flag.
Vinch, where did you put it in the store?
Oh, I put it [em1]in the box next to the counter[/em1]. I didn't want it to get damaged.
I never thought about that.
Sorry, I forgot to mention it.
Still, it's my fault for not checking properly.
As Ellie said, not passing it directly caused the confusion. My apologies.
It's okay. Mistakes happen.
Sorry to everyone else too. I caused unnecessary suspicion.
It's fine! It was fun!
Yeah, like a detective novel!
My fault too. Sorry everyone.
Alright, case closed!
Sorry it ended anticlimactically.
If I'm the "villain," I should've played it cooler.
That's reality. A bit anticlimactic, but understandable.
Yeah. Learned something new.
Alvin, can we get the flag now?
Hmm... sorry, can you wait a bit?
Huh? Why?
From what I hear, we won't see the flag in the future.
Right. We need to plant it with the seeds.
Then give me a day. I haven't finished studying the material.
Okay. I'll come back tomorrow.
It was an enjoyable little novel, Ellie.
The culprit is... [lua(GetLocalizedString("InteractableObject", "People_Rex"))]!
Huh? Me!? <shake> I'm not!</shake>
I'm innocent!
That's literally a "villain confession"!
But Rex isn't the culprit. I definitely got it from him.
Y-Yeah! That's right... I gave it to Arin...
Ugh... still not sure...
Virgil, do you have any idea?
There are a few things that stand out.
Ugh, don't tell me. I'll figure it out myself.
Go for it.
Only the flag though.
Rex did break the pole...
Yeah. I just wanted to draw it as it looked.
But if Vinch drew it using the flag Arin received, the pole shouldn't be there.
Rex already broke it, so Arin only had the flag.
That's right. I only handed over the flag to Vinch.
Definitely only got the flag from Arin.
Yet Vinch's drawing shows the pole, and the flag is perfectly intact.
But the pattern is faded, as Arin said.
Exactly. Here's my theory:
Vinch received the flag first from someone.
He drew the flag while the pole was intact.
Before [em1]finishing the painting[/em1], he lent the flag to Alvin.
Ah!
Later, he got it back from Arin and completed the painting.
That's why the drawing shows a mix of different states of the flag.
Right! Now I remember.
I asked Enite for the flag for the painting.
While painting, Alvin asked to borrow it.
I left it there to finish coloring later, then forgot about it!
Me? Twice?
Yes... I only remembered that I needed to give the flag to Alvin after finishing the painting.
So I left it at the store after coloring.
Alvin? You saw it at the store?
Hmm... not recently.
By the counter...
Actually, at the back of the store.
I didn't want paint fumes to damage it if left inside.
Didn't think of that.
Sorry, I tend to forget other things when painting.
It's okay. Glad we found it in the end.
Sorry to everyone else.
It's fine. Mistakes happen when focused elsewhere.
Yep, and it was fun for me too.
And quite an interesting case!
Mistakes happen! No worries.
Hey... I actually helped find it, didn't I?
What do you mean?
By breaking the pole, it was obvious where it came from.
Rex.
Even if you catch a mouse by stepping back, applause doesn't follow.
Alright...
But I definitely got it from the store.
I'm pretty sure I gave it too.
If no one left it there secretly... then probably not me.
So Vinch, who got the flag from Arin, naturally only had the flag without the pole.
Right. I only made a draft and left it at the store.
And later saw it at the library.
Yeah. I remembered I hadn't finished coloring, so I borrowed it again.
I borrowed it from Arin to color and finish the painting...
...then put it back in the store.
What!?
Alright! Then there's just one left.
The last one's going to be a bit tricky, though.
It's the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))], remember?
So?
Compared to the others, not much has taken place yet.
Don't you think it's... lacking a "bond"?
Well... yeah, that's true.
The people there haven't really done anything together yet.
Yeah... you're right. They haven't... yet.
But [em1]they will[/em1]! A lot!
We just have to bury what [em1]will become[/em1] the source of the bond!
Wait, what? You can do that?
We've always been burying things from the past.
Who says we can't bury things from the future?
Easier said than done.
How would you even do that?
...I don't know.
Oh! Let's ask Lisa.
She said she'd help anytime.
Don't you think you're asking for her help a little too often?
Lisa's the master witch here, remember?
An apprentice witch is supposed to learn from her master.
I guess that's true...
Then let's go see Lisa.
If I could see you every day at home, mornings would be so much happier. How about you?
(The cat lets out a soft purr.)
Are you sure? Living with another being means taking on responsibility.
Confidence...?
I've got it!
...Maybe not yet.
I've been waiting for this day for so long. You're excited too, right?
(The cat's tail stands straight up.)
Then... I've prepared a gift. Will you accept it?
Like you said, Virgil, it's something I should think about carefully.
So... can you wait until I'm ready?
(The cat's tail sways gently.)
I have something I want to ask. Will you stay with me a little longer?
(The cat walks up beside Ellie.)
If it's okay with you, would you like to live at my house?
I just think it'd be nice for us to be close.
I'd love to live together, but... there's still a lot I need to prepare.
Would you like to use the [em1]Token of Friendship[/em1] on the cat?
Here. This is the [em1]Token of Friendship[/em1] I prepared for you.
Wearing this will let everyone know you're a friend who lives with me.
(The cat sniffs the tag, then purrs contentedly.)
I've enjoyed spending time with you. You'll be living in the village now, right?
It's not like you'll be leaving Ellie forever. Be happy.
I know, Virgil. I'm just... remembering the friendship we've built.
Then... take care!
(The cat meows while looking at Ellie.)
Alright, it's done.
Could you tell our friends the news today?
I should tidy up the house before you come over.
So starting tomorrow... <wave>Let's be good friends.</wave>
Virgil, I can feel the cat trusts me. It's such a strange, wonderful feeling.
Really? Then you're not forgetting the responsibility that comes with it, right?
Of course not! I'll take great care of it.
(The cat looks back at Ellie affectionately.)
Thanks to the token, I can sense what the cat's feeling.
Hm? Do you have something you want to say?
(The cat's tail sways slowly from side to side.)
Judging by your expression... you've got something on your mind, haven't you?
If the cat wants to return to the village, what would you do?
I...
I'll let go.
It makes me sad, but...
I know I haven't always done my best for you.
So if you want to leave, I'd at least like to see you off. That's alright, isn't it?
I'll persuade it to stay.
Oh? So you're confident?
I'll do my best. Trust me.
(The cat starts to purr.)
Alright! I'll be counting on you again.
The cat's expression really is different from usual.
Maybe it's because of the [em1]Token of Friendship[/em1]...
Do you... Really want to go back to the village?
(The cat looks silently at Ellie.)
Keeping it against its will may not be a good idea.
You want to return to where you lived, don't you?
It makes me sad, but I want to respect its wish.
Are you heading to the village right away? Let me walk you there.
Maybe it's the necklace... I somehow know it wants to return to the village.
What do you do?
If only I had taken better care of you.
(The cat stares at Ellie indifferently.)
Do you have anything to say?
Of course I should ask. Would you trust me one more time?
(The cat rubs its face against Ellie.)
I can feel your trust. That's a yes!
I'll do my best—you're trusting me again, after all.
Great! Let's be friends with each other!
Would you trust me one more time?
I can feel your trust.
...But I can also feel you're still thinking about returning to the village.
This is... the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))]?!
Is it just me or...
It's not as fancy as I expected.
Perhaps this is no ordinary cave.
You think so?
It's connected to the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
There's a prickly vine. I shall follow the prickly vine for now.
Wait...
Did you hear that?
I won't know what it was, but that was loud.
Was it... something giant?
Look around.
Doors, elevators, and writings on walls.
Apparently, someone was here.
But what about that?
If we can find these where the star landed,
there can be a couple of giant guardians too.
Let's move faster...
<shake>Woahhhhhh!!</shake>
<shake>What's that!!</shake>
Wh-what's going on?
Why have we halted? What's this place?
Was it because of stellar magic?
Phew, anyway, we survived.
<shake>I honestly thought I was going to die.</shake>
Woah, this is breathtaking. What is it?
Some sort of seal? Used to contain overflowing stellar magic and prevent it from rising?
It's too ancient to be familiar even for me.
Uh-oh... It's descending.
I can't see it anymore.
You can always visit it in the village.
And our friendship will never fade.
I know, Virgil.
I think this can carry us down the hole created by the star...
I'm gonna use it.
Maybe later.
Look, Virgil! It's the Starwhale.
It does look like a whale.
That translucent body looks as if made of tiny stars. It's incredible.
But this one looks sluggish.
This one? Is it a different individual?
Yeah, the size is different. The appearance is also slightly different.
They look the same to me.
This one doesn't look strong...
Is it because of the prickly vines?
Is the prickly vine core absorbing the power of the star?
That's why the core keeps growing while the Starwhales are weakened.
Why do you keep saying "maybe"?
Because we know nothing about that star.
Your assumption may sound reasonable, but it's still just an assumption.
Okay, it's just like you said.
If only we could find written materials left by witches who used to study this place.
If such materials really existed, that is.
Okay, let's first do what we can.
Craft Moon Tears, you mean?
Right, as long as we remove the prickly vine core with Moon Tears...
The Starwhale will be well again in no time.
It's the Starwhale from before!
It seems to be showing us the way.
Let's follow it then.
Follow what?
Our guide!
It dropped something.
This was on the Starwhale...
A glove...?
It's a gardening glove.
Then it should be Lisa's.
Wait, does this mean that all those belongs scattered on the ground had fallen off the Starwhale?
That explains why they were so disorganized.
But where in this world is Lisa?!
And why's the Starwhale dropping Lisa's stuff all over the place?
To draw us over?
Draw us over? What for? And where to?
Does it want us to cure it?
I can't read its mind.
Well... fine. I'll follow it for now.
I think it has gone down from here...
Oh, there it is!
I'll check out Lisa's campsite first.
I need to remove this bird cage first.
The witch chalk may do the trick.
Now, I just need to craft some Moon Tears.
On my way then.
I need to bring the Moon Tears over.
I need to find a way to remove the prickly vines.
It's really a backpack!
It's been stuck in the prickly vine bush this whole time.
Well... It's full of trash I don't even recognize.
Not surprising for a long-abandoned bag.
Can there be something useful...?
a dice?
Looks like a traditional witch dice.
There's a memo too.
Potion ingredients: 6 dice
It means you can craft a potion if you find 5 more dice.
Kids nowadays no longer know "Olivia's Pot"?
Olivia's Pot?
Is that the dice game mid-aged men play at bars?
Don't mix up games with reality, Virgil.
Ancient witch dice should be quite valuable.
Are they? I'll take this one then.
What else? ... Basically just trash...
Virgil, look at this.
It's a key!
Must be the key to that locked lab!
How would you know?
Because that's how things go in all stories!
And look at this.
It's the same sigil as on the door.
It's worn, but it does look similar.
Right~?
Okay, back to the lab!
A locked room must house some good stuff!
Oh my...
Where am I...?
Looks like a room used by people who investigated this place.
Like a lab? Is it a lab?!
It can be just a room for having coffee.
It really is a lab used by previous researchers!
Anyway, it must be at least a hundred years old.
I can't believe I'm seeing stuff used by people centuries ago.
We can only pray that those people had done their work carefully.
We can only learn about the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))] if they'd done a thorough investigation of the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
Let's see what they discovered then.
These books are in better condition than those in the bookcases outside.
After all, they had a door to shelter them.
But I can't understand them either.
And I think they'll be crumbled by even the gentlest touch.
Still, you should search the place thoroughly.
You may find clues about the "curse" Lisa mentioned.
Our priority is to remove the prickly vines. The curse can wait.
I'll read the books when the situation requires it.
Just say that you hate reading.
I hate reading! So what!
It will come in handy.
Then I'll read when it comes handy.
I'll look elsewhere for now.
Star Potion
A potion that tracks down any living thing, be it a human, an animal, or a plant.
It captures and reveals the target's soul or true form.
Note: Only effective when the user knows the target well.
The user is qualified if the potion glows.
Here's another witch's pot.
Apparently, Tanis has also crafted potions here.
Potions can be needed in sculpting as well.
Witch's pots haven't changed much in the past century.
And it still seems usable...
No, wait, it's in a terrible state.
It's all ruined by green tarnish.
After all, it's been more than a century.
Wait, there's something in it...
Isn't this another witch dice?
Four to go then.
Nothing can be crafted from a bunch of dice.
You seem to share Tanis's sense of humor.
Do you have something against my sense of humor?
I'll take this one with me too.
And... add the dice.
Can I really craft a potion like this...?
The memo in that backpack with the key said so.
It did.
If anything, I want a potion that removes the prickly vine core.
Pray that Lady Luck smiles on you then.
May Lady Luck smile on me, whatever that means!
Let's follow the glowing string!
Nothing in particular for now.
Alright, I'll use the key from that backpack...
That may not be the right key.
It is. Look, it fits.
Huh? Wait...
I-it won't turn...
Easy on it. The key's ancient. You may break it.
Don't put pressure on me when I'm already nervous.
Maybe the key has worn down too much to fit well.
Don't push it too hard. Pull it out a bit and turn again.
Alright, pull it out a bit...
And turn...!
I said easy on it.
It's fine. It's budge... Got to turn harder...
You'll break it!
Just a second. A bit of stirring... and turn!
Done! See? It's open.
I think you've just destroyed the lock.
That may not have been the right key in the first place. It didn't fit well.
As long as the door's open.
You ended up forcing your way through.
Let's have a look inside.
You forced your way through when you had the key.
Stop complaining, Virgil. Time for an investigation.
What's behind this door?
A hidden chamber?!
It isn't hidden at all.
I was creating an atmosphere for adventure, okay?
Wait, there's an inscription.
"Tanis Rustystone's Sculpture Workshop"
Tanis?
That name was mentioned repeatedly in Lisa's memos...
Never in a positive way.
She was probably an artist who made sculptures for the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))]...
I'm gonna open this door.
Be easy on it.
I will. Easy on it...
That's still quite rough. Be easier.
Okay... huh? What the...?
Hah! Ummmm...!
If that's what you call easier, you should go easiest the next time.
It's locked?
We need a key.
Whoever locked it should have taken the key away.
Where to?
Home.
When?
A century ago.
Can I not smash it open?
You shouldn't be that violent even if you refuse to be easy on it.
Alright, I'll look for the key.
The door smashing can wait.
I'll come back when I've got the key.
There's a glowing string!
Since when have you got two lives?
I suppose the potion kept away by Tanis should be safe?
It could have been dangerous.
I rolled a good number then.
You can complain after I've caught up with that string!
How can I get to the other side?
Not from here, I'm afraid.
Alright, I'll look somewhere else.
It feels chilly here...
There's ice over there.
Woah, you're right.
What will we discover this time? My heart's racing with excitement.
Woah, it worked!
Has anything changed...?
I didn't feel anything.
Hmm... I don't get it. Anyway, I'll go back to the prickly vine core.
Huh? That's it?
It's not working at all!!
Things were going too smoothly before.
I'm not joking, Virgil!
What do we do now?
Maybe you need more Moon Tears?
Where can I possibly find all the Moonflowers and Sacred Water...
And the Moon Oil you used at the beginning.
What about the Phoenix Feather? And it could be Phoenix "Feathers" that we need...
Is there no other way...
Speaking of another way, Lisa mentioned something in her notes.
Did she? I don't recall anything notable.
She said that it was not the moon's power that those plants feared. It was [em1]the power of night[/em1]...
Oh... Wait a second. Come to think of it, if the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))] contains the power of night...
there should be [em1]something in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))][/em1] that we can use.
Unfortunately, we hardly know anything about the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
You're right.
We've found the lab, but there's nothing decisive in it.
There's a locked door.
You mean the door that says [em1]Tanis's Sculpture Workshop[/em1] or whatever?
Alright, let's search every corner of the lab.
If it doesn't work out, I'll make a bucket of Moon Tears...
Where?
Moon Oil has removed some prickly vines, revealing something resembling a [em1]backpack[/em1].
A backpack?!
I'll have a look at it.
<wave>Wow! The crafting was successful?!</wave>
But why?! All that I added was dice!
Maybe there had been other ingredients at the bottom of the pot?
It should be a device with a mechanism of that sort.
Has Tanis made this device as well?
Tanis is amazing!
So, what potion have we got here?
It's glowing.
The bottle says... [em1][lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion"))][/em1].
I've never seen such a potion!
Wait, I didn't get that one right.
<shake>I've never seen such a potion!</shake>
Congrats. You've crafted a potion from 100 years ago.
What exactly is this potion?!
Does it remove the prickly vine core?!
You need to identify it first.
<shake>How can I possibly identify a potion from 100 years ago!!</shake>
By looking it up in a book from 100 years ago, of course.
Uh-oh...
Time to read books, Ellie.
No... I'm not giving up.
There's another way to find out.
What? What are you doing!
Light from the potion is directed at the prickly vine core.
My goodness! Look at this!
I can hardly recognize this place.
The device has sent water flowing down from above.
It looks better now!
And there's more over there.
Locations that were dry are now filled with water.
You can now swim to the prickly vine core.
Right. What are we waiting for?
This doesn't make any sense!!
There must be more to it!
Besides Lisa's death?
P-probably...
Firstly, I need to get the [lua(GetItemName("SacredWater_Water#Important"))] from the Black Cat God.
Let's talk to the Black Cat God tomorrow during the day.
Am I really doing it correctly?
The east is the cradle whence both day and night are born.
Why are you also talking like the Black Cat God?!
If you want to know whether it's the right path, you need to reach its end.
What would Mom do?
Aria?
What would Mom do if she wonders whether she's on the right path?
Aria would run along the path at full speed.
Run?
Each picks their own path.
If the answer lies at the end of the path,
you can never find out unless you keep going.
And Aria always runs instead of walking.
That's very typical for Mom.
There were several times when it almost cost her life, though.
Haha, I see.
As a Blueriver myself,
I should also try running along my path.
Because there's so much I need to find out.
What's the right thing to do? Am I doing the right thing?
Is it a good idea to hand over the brooch? Should I leave Lisa alone?
It's a mountain of books.
Many are already worn... Others feel like they will crumble the moment I touch them.
A lot of them are written in languages I don't recognize.
Turns out that only a few of them can actually be read.
These books are in decent shape if you consider their age.
There's nothing to read at the moment.
This is a plain room.
This is normal for a witch's workshop.
Think about Lisa.
Right, this is at least way more tidy than Lisa's place.
Will I find any clue here?
To remove the prickly vine core, I must learn about the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))][/em1]...
But isn't this a "sculpture workshop"? I doubt that a sculptor would possess anything relevant.
But Lisa kept mentioning Tanis.
I have a feeling that there's something here.
<shake>There's got to be something.</shake>
Honestly, we'll be in trouble if there's nothing.
If there's nothing, I won't be able to make a bucketful of Moon Tears!
Be careful when you investigate.
Like you mentioned, Lisa didn't say anything positive about Tanis.
Relax. I'm always careful.
Seriously?
What's this? A bell?
Why would there be a bell?
Usually, you ring a bell to send a signal.
Could it have something to do with that barrier from before?
It's possible. That barrier had a bell pattern on it.
I'll ring the bell to find out.
Oh my, it makes a lovely sound.
That can travel very far.
Yeah, it's not loud, but it's penetrating.
I think it can be heard throughout the area.
Let's see what has become of that barrier with the bell pattern.
Great! The barrier's finally lifted.
So, I can actually lift the barriers by ringing bells for the required times.
The first barrier had 4 marks on it, which means...
To descend further, I'll have to find and ring 2 more bells.
The owner must be hard of hearing if they only open the door after the bells ring 4 times.
By the way, where's that big guy we saw just now?
Flying around somewhere in the cave, I guess.
I'll just follow the prickly vine down.
Hasn't that always been the priority?
Woah, it's a table.
Woah, it's a shelf.
Woah, it's a desk.
Do you get it?
Certainly not.
The Starwhale guided us here with Lisa's belongings.
If so, the Starwhale's also...
The prickly vine core's removed! We did it!
It actually worked.
I knew the Starwhale would listen to me.
It seems that Starwhales can communicate with humans to some extent.
Or it could have been a coincidence.
I mean the dice.
The Starwhale took the starry flash!
Look! It understood me!
Could it be that the Starwhale...
Starwhales, how gorgeous and fascinating...
That's a dangerous idea to have.
It's just an idea. I'm not doing anything.
But now that I look back on the whole incident, I didn't contribute much this time.
That's not the case.
The Starwhale is the one that removed the prickly vines.
Dice won't roll on their own.
You rolled them and brought this outcome.
Tanis helped me too.
Anyway, as long as everyone's safe.
It's finally all settled.
Now that the last prickly vine core is removed, the village can be fully restored.
The village just needs a little more repairing, and we're done.
Are we really done?
Why not? All the prickly vines are removed, and the village is restored.
What about Lisa?
Isn't the village our top priority once we've handled the core?
You can restore the village first and think about anything else later.
It doesn't feel quite right though...
With hindsight, the White Cat God is really suspicious.
They said "Ignore Lisa and restore the village."
I don't know what they're hiding, but I don't think I shall obey them.
What's your plan then? I doubt that those cat gods will be honest with you.
You'll never know if you never try.
Firstly, I need to talk to the White Cat God once more.
Starwhale! Could you please help me?
I need your power to remove this prickly vine core! Both your and my friends depend on it!
Please <shake>burn</shake> these prickly vines with starry flashes!!
<shake>Now what do we do?</shake>
Big talk about handling it yourself, and now this.
Well, I can't make things harder for Diane.
Even if she offered to help, it'd still be risky.
So... what now?
Should I just start pounding the pavement and searching?
If the White Cat God is hiding her, I doubt that'd do much good.
True.
We need to... think outside the box.
Maybe there's a potion I can brew that could help...
You mean like the one you used to find the Starwhale?
Exactly. The one that can track living beings, right?
If I had that, I could find Lisa for sure!
And how do you plan on making it?
Last time, you gathered dice to make it.
Oh, right! Now that I think about it... <shake>I don't even know the exact ingredients!</shake>
Let's go to the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))][/em1].
Hmm... maybe I already brewed something similar before?
Think hard. You've made plenty of things.
Something useful...?
The [em1][lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion"))][/em1] maybe?
You have done a lot of brewing.
How about [lua(GetItemName("IntUpPotion"))]?
[lua(GetItemName("IntUpPotion"))] won't make you suddenly know something you don't.
[lua(GetItemName("ManaDetectingCandy"))]?
That candy isn't anywhere near that powerful.
What about [lua(GetItemName("LuckUpCandy"))]?
You don't even know where Lisa is.
Best you'd do is find a couple of coins.
<shake>So nothing's actually useful?!</shake>
[lua(GetItemName("BoomPotion"))]?
Absolutely not.
Ah! Come to think of it...
I did use something like that in the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))][/em1]!
Wait... maybe there was info in the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))]'s lab[/em1].
You sure? That potion was first made over a hundred years ago.
Still, I made it not too long ago!
Using dice, remember?
<shake>Either way, let's just go!</shake>
You don't even know the recipe.
Feels like it's been a while since I've been here.
Alright, let's check the [em1]bookshelf[/em1] for anything on the [em1][lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion"))][/em1].
And we should check the [em1]pot[/em1] too.
Right, let's examine [em1]every place we can[/em1].
Hm... looks like a normal pot from the outside...
The mechanism must be inside.
If they had brewed with the mechanism active, they would've hidden it well.
Then let's take a peek inside...
Ugh, the smell...
Ewww...
Whew... iI's awful down there.
See anything?
Looked like part of the lower wall could open up.
That's probably where ingredients were added.
Impressive craftsmanship.
Shame it's single-use, though.
Anything else?
Not much—just some [em1]blue powder[/em1] stuck around the opening...
Nothing else.
And... some [em1]black residue[/em1] on the floor.
That stuff's what smelled so foul.
Doesn't sound like we've got much to work with.
At least we know [em1]blue powder was one of the ingredients[/em1].
And whatever's left behind smells terrible.
Yeah, I didn't need to know that.
Let's check the other spots.
A potion that can find people or creatures... just what we needed.
Does it have the recipe?
Ah, right. Hold on...
"Control the fire..." but the rest is smudged out.
Hmm... oh, these must be the ingredients.
[em1][lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_0#Important"))][/em1]... [em1][lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_1#Important"))][/em1]... [em1][lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_2#Important"))][/em1]...?
At least I can read these.
But there's one I can't quite make out...
Looks like it says [em1]something powder[/em1].
Well, it's kind of like finding a recipe, at least.
Yeah. Let's check the rest of this place too.
Okay, I think that's everything. Let's review.
The book listed [em1]four ingredients[/em1].
[lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_0#Important"))], [lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_1#Important"))], [lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_2#Important"))] and something powder.
And the fire-control and ladle instructions were too damaged to read.
We'll worry about that later. Doesn't seem too complicated.
I'm pretty sure I know where to get [em1][lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_2#Important"))][/em1].
Because we've seen it before.
Exactly. There might be one lying around [em1]where the giant Starwhale was resting[/em1].
Where the prickly vine core was.
Yep. We should check there.
Next... the "something powder."
What powder?
I think it's actually [em1]star powder[/em1].
There were jars of different colored star powder on the [em1]shelf[/em1].
And thinking about the [em1]blue residue[/em1] in the pot...
We probably need [em1][lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_3#Important"))][/em1].
It was on that [em1]shelf[/em1]. Let's grab it.
That leaves the other two ingredients.
I might have a lead on [em1][lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_1#Important"))][/em1].
How so?
Actually... I don't really know what it is.
...So what do you mean?
Remember the [em1]gunk[/em1] at the bottom of the pot earlier?
I think it might be that.
Sounds like a guess.
It's all we've got.
But [em1][lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_0#Important"))][/em1]... I have no idea what that's supposed to be.
Maybe it's a metaphor?
Potion recipes don't usually use metaphors.
Just weird names.
If it's not a metaphor...
The [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))] is often described as "night."
So maybe there's a spot in the cave where [em1]sunlight comes through[/em1]?
Sunlight in the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))], with sea spray in the air... that would be perfect.
Can't say I remember a place like that.
It'd need an opening overhead.
Like... [em1]a well[/em1]?
Possible.
I think I saw a [em1]well[/em1] in the [em1]Green Forest Plains[/em1].
Let's check there.
Hmm... no luck.
Maybe there's a sunlit spot in the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))] Tunnel[/em1] instead.
Let's have a look at the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))] Tunnel[/em1].
Wow... I didn't know such a place existed.
Sunlight really is reaching all the way into [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
A well that draws up the water of night.
The person who built it probably didn't even think about that.
Good, now we have the [lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_0#Important"))].
Let's collect the rest of the ingredients.
Ugh, the smell here is intense.
What does it smell like?
Hard to explain...
Like wet leaves mixed with clay, burned into some sticky mess.
Doesn't sound bad.
I didn't say bad. It's just strong and weird.
Let's move before my nose gives out.
Oh, good, there's one lying here.
It's beautiful! So shiny!
I hope the Starwhales are doing well.
Nature does its own thing.
We should come back and visit sometime.
Star powder comes in more colors than I thought.
Do you remember which one we need?
Blue, obviously.
You'll need more than "blue."
There were like three or four shades of it.
Still remember?
Like the color of the sky before dawn. Not dark, but deep.
Alright, that should be it.
Okay, that's all the ingredients.
Let's head home and brew the [lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion"))].
Brewing's more than just throwing in ingredients.
Fire and ladle, right.
You still have to heat and stir.
And the recipe was half-ruined.
I've got a plan.
Let's hear it.
Remember when we brewed a potion with dice?
We also placed the ingredients first.
Yes, the pot had some kind of automatic feeder.
I set the fire [em1]really low[/em1] at the start and left it.
I didn't stir at all.
And the [lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_1#Important"))] looked like it had been there beforehand.
Seems like it.
Let's try to make it.
Add the [lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion_Materials_1#Important"))], adjust the flame, then mix in the remaining ingredients.
Whoa! I actually made it!
Well, look at that.
See? <shake>Now</shake> you know how good I am!
<shake>Even a century-old potion</shake> is easy for me.
Are you... shaking?
<shake>Of course I'm shaking! It's a century-old potion!</shake>
Now that's done.
The next step is not something you can get from a dice game.
Now comes the important part.
Making the [lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion"))] [em1]shine[/em1].
Oh, right.
You have to know your target well before you can use it.
And once you do, the potion will start to glow.
Time to ask around.
Didn't you already do that?
What more will you learn by asking again?
Yeah, but I don't think we need groundbreaking info. Just personal details.
About Lisa Whitegarden, right?
What she likes, what she won't eat, how she sleeps… little things
Like what Kyla told you once.
I didn't think it mattered back then,
But knowing someone is about those little things.
Let's speak to everyone who might know Lisa.
Alright, I've asked everyone.
I think I know her better now.
The potion still isn't glowing, though.
Maybe a little...
But not enough.
Guess we need something decisive.
Maybe...
But we've talked to everyone already.
There's still one person left.
Who?
The [em1]White Cat God[/em1].
Didn't White Cat God hide Lisa?
Maybe, but they know her well.
Since they don't know about this potion, they'll answer without suspicion.
And if the potion glows, we'll use it right in front of the White Cat God!
Not the worst plan. Let's do it.
Since there are no other options, let's go see the White Cat God.
Finally! It's glowing!
Is that...?
The [lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion"))]. It can find someone,
But only if you truly understand them.
Find someone? <shake>Wait... don't tell me</shake>
That's right. [em1]Lisa, the one you've been hiding.[/em1]
Eli... hold on...
I'm going to find her. With this.
Huh? Why is the trail...?
Did you mess it up?
No... the trail's leading...
To you! [em1]White Cat God[/em1]?
This is... what's happening...?
<shake>My body...?</shake>
White Cat God?
She has now fallen into the blue river.
Face the deep blue night.
What is... this?
The White Cat God... turned into a person...?
Ellie, what in the world is going on?
[lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion"))] is supposed to reveal a thing's [em1]true essence[/em1]...
So... were you a human to begin with?
No, I'm...
<shake>No, I mean... yes. Wait, that's not...</shake>
Hold on... that face...
It's exactly like how people described [em1]Lisa[/em1]...
You're... Lisa Whitegarden?
...Eh! Ah...
<shake>Absolutely not.</shake>
That reaction says otherwise!
Enite told me Lisa can't make eye contact when she lies.
You really are Lisa, aren't you?
Since when...?
... I guess there's no hiding it now.
You really are remarkable, Ellie.
Once you set your mind on something, you make it happen. The prickly vines... the village... and me.
So you really are Lisa Whitegarden? The master witch who lived in Witch's House?
Yes. I am Lisa Whitegarden, master witch of the Wisteria Witch's House.
But how... why...? No, wait, I...
I have <shake>so</shake> many questions!
One at a time.
I was truly impressed by your skill.
I never thought you'd be able to recreate the potion from the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
School for Witches clearly trains excellent students.
Then what happened?
Why were you in the form of the White Cat God?
It's a long story... are you sure you want to hear it?
Of course! Hurry!
I used to make gardens for witches.
I've built so, so many gardens back then.
But every garden I made would crumble and wither after only a few years.
People would come to me each time, showing me the ruins and begging me to fix them.
I... couldn't stand it. I couldn't bear to watch my gardens fall apart anymore.
So I stopped making them.
Instead, I resolved to create a garden that would never die. A garden that would [em1]never wither[/em1].
So that's why you came to Wisteria.
That's right. Making marble that stays forever isn't that hard.
But plants... were another matter. I came to Wisteria for them.
Here, there were white prickly vines that would never die unless they were touched by moonlight.
After years of study, I combined them with Little Honey Pumpkins to create [em1]a new breed of prickly vine[/em1].
Vines that can't die unless you destroy their core.
Exactly. The same [em1]vines in the village[/em1] that you saw, and removed.
But how did they end up taking over the village?
After I finished the vines and began my [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))] research...
...I died.
<shake>Just like that?</shake> How?
Simply.
Simply?
I'd lived a long time already.
When I was studying the cave, my cough never stopped... Honestly, I could have died at any moment.
I passed away in my sleep at the camp in the cave.
Huh? Then what happened? What about the vines?
Everything after that is hazy. I'm not even sure myself.
I only... think I saw the [em1]Ritorings[/em1] planting the seeds I'd made.
<shake>The Ritorings!?</shake>
Those pests will plant anything they can get their hands on.
I was horrified...
...but part of me wanted to see the vines grow.
And grow they did. Just as I'd designed them.
They climbed the village walls like ivy, spreading... and spreading.
The villagers tried everything to remove them... but without destroying the core, they could never be rid of them.
And I... could do nothing but watch.
I saw the things I loved fall to ruin because of me... and I couldn't lift a finger.
So I prayed. Begged for someone to protect the village.
And the [em1]White Cat God[/em1] answered.
The White Cat God?
They lent me their body when I was nothing but a spirit.
That's how I came to wield divine power.
But by then, the village was nearly gone, and its people had left. A god without worshipers can do very little.
I tried all sorts of things, but nothing worked. All I could do was...
...watch the village slowly fall apart.
And then... [em1]a train[/em1] passed by.
That was me.
The only train on the continent always carries exceptional witches.
I used all my remaining strength to stop the train.
The rest... You already know.
But why didn't you just tell me the truth?
I wasn't sure about you back then.
Ellie doesn't exactly give off a trustworthy first impression.
And... I only wanted to restore the village.
Lisa Whitegarden had failed. And died.
The one standing here is... no one.
Nothing.
Such a person's story means nothing.
I only wanted to put things back the way they were... and then disappear.
But that's not true, is it?
Lisa Whitegarden didn't fail.
How could you say that...?
Lisa wanted to make an eternal garden.
She wasted a hundred years chasing that foolish dream, and never succeeded.
Lisa's time here wasn't wasted.
Lisa spent most of her life making those vines.
And with them, she destroyed the village she loved.
That... wasn't what I wanted...
<shake>I never wanted to live like that...</shake>
<shake>And yet</shake> you say I didn't fail?
I've learned a lot about you, Lisa.
I've lived in your house, seen what you left behind, and spoken with the people here.
If this is supposed to be comforting, don't bother.
My story already has an ending, and it's not a happy one.
No, this isn't just comfort.
Lisa Whitegarden truly didn't fail.
Oh?
Then where is [em1]Lisa's garden[/em1]?
If I didn't fail, then the [em1]garden[/em1] I dreamed of should be here.
The garden I... I... spent my life trying to create...
<shake>That damned [em1]eternal garden of mine[/em1]!!</shake>
I've wandered all around Wisteria.
The [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_GreenForest"))], [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_RainbowForest"))], the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))]... I've seen your touch in every place.
And talking to the villagers, I realized something.
They liked you back then. And they like you now.
Even now, when the vines seem to have been your doing, they still believe in you.
Lisa, this is [em1]your garden[/em1]. The forest, the buildings, the village and its people.
What...?
Yes. [em1]Wisteria[/em1].
This is the eternal, beautiful garden you've tended for a hundred years.
For a hundred years, I...
Yes. You haven't wasted your life.
You've been tending your eternal garden all along.
Ah... <shake>Ahh...</shake>
And now... It's nearly complete.
My... eternal garden...
How could I possibly claim this as mine?
I'm not worthy...
I'm the one who destroyed it.
To them, I'm just the wicked witch who ruined their home.
Maybe... for now.
Then the wicked witch should just fade quietly away...
No. You don't have to disappear. You just need to [em1]talk[/em1].
[em1]Talk[/em1]...?
Yes. Even if it's embarrassing, awkward, or painful... Apologize. Then share your stories with a smile.
I'm sure they'll love hearing them.
Hiding is easy. But nothing changes that way.
Like an untended garden, it'll just wither.
Trust the villagers.
Speak to them.
I'll help you.
You're right, Ellie.
Alright... I'll try.
I'll try... Just like you did.
Yes. Let's try together.
The villagers are kind. If you talk to them, it'll be fine.
I know that better than anyone.
Of course. You're the master witch, after all.
Yes... my apprentice witch, Ellie.
At last, a proper introduction.
I look forward to working with you, apprentice.
And I with you, master witch.
Hmm... now that I look closely, there are actually a few decent things here.
Still smells awful, though.
See if there's anything worth taking.
Yeah, yeah, I'm on it.
There's a lot of glittery powder... Is this [em1]star powder[/em1]?
And in all sorts of different colors.
And some wilted plants... more wilted plants... and something so far gone I can't even tell what it is...
<shake>Ugh!</shake>
Don't stick your head in so close. I'm closer than you are, remember?
Forget it.
The only useful thing here is the [em1]different-colored star powder[/em1].
Let's check somewhere else.
Hmm... there are ingredients stored inside.
Most of them aren't in great shape.
And they smell funny.
It's been more than 100 years.
I don't feel like touching ingredients that ancient.
Hm? What's this feeling?
I felt something warm and tender popping in my chest...
Don't tell me your lack of friends has rendered you unable to comprehend [em1]affection[/em1].
Hey, even I have friends!
That was not a figure of speech. I literally felt something.
That "something" is what we call affection.
I wish I had someone to ask...
This may perplex you, but people often mistake that warmth for—
It felt like something magical. Let's ask the [em1]Black Cat God[/em1].
"Magic."
Water! A jet of water!
Another guy babbling words I can't understand.
White splash...
Is this some sort of spirit?
Large drop. Large drop.
Spirits can sometimes be found dwelling in meticulously crafted items or buildings.
Which means there may be spirits in this region or local buildings.
Morning dews.
What does this spirit do?
It helps you repair, customize, and expand the Witch's House, and more.
What about this guy?
It makes flowers bloom, I guess.
It speaks Black Cat God? Fine.
I'll give you "Drop of Emotion."
Drizzle. Spring rain!
Could you make the flowers bloom if I give you this?
Drop, drop. Large drop.
Is that an assent?
Your conversation makes absolutely no sense to me.
That reveals your lack of empathy.
Ask it if it will make flowers bloom.
Round stone. Rounded stone!
Leaf, leaf! Tender leaf!
Pebble. Gravel!
Branch. Twig!
I don't know either.
Hello, what do you do?
Stream...
I don't think it's doing anything right now.
Let's come back later.
Can you really communicate with it...
Splash~
Stepping stone~
Sprout~
Pebble...
Tree knot...
Can it expand this just like how it expands the Witch's House?
I suppose each spirit has its own expertise.
Mossy stone.
Sprouting branch.
Round stone! Rounded stone!
Leaf! Wide leaf!
Is it a cousin of the one at the Witch's House?
Stepping stone...
Thick root...
Stone! Rolling stone!
Leaf! Fluttering leaf!
Can we really trust this guy?
Can you make flowers bloom?
Drifting clouds~
Spring rain! Spring rain!
It worked? I'll check again tomorrow.
Pebble! Pebble!
Branch! Twig!
Splashing water...
Maybe next time.
Flat stepping stone...
Moist soil~
Cracked bark~
Singing stream.
Done here.
Pebble.
Tree knot.
Singing stream...
There's nothing to do at the moment.
Small pebble...
Me? I'll keep being the White Cat God for a while yet.
At least until the White Cat God permits it... until my garden is finally complete.
Yes... and when that day comes, I'll return to where I truly belong.
Don't be too sad about it. The fact that we're here together now... that's already a blessing.
Right now, our focus should be on [em1]restoring the village[/em1].
And making peace with the villagers.
You always manage to slip in those lines even when you're being sentimental.
Haha! So, you will make peace, right?
...Yes. I'll try.
But give me some time.
First things first. We need to finish the garden.
I'll leave it to you.
Then I'll help fix up the village and come back.
I'll be here, waiting.
Alright, let's finish looking around here.
We'll grab whatever materials we can find and head out.
Okay, time to come up with a recipe.
So, what kind of potion are we making?
The [em1]Potion of Wishes[/em1].
Potion of Wishes? And what exactly does it do?
It holds a wish.
...Come again?
Exactly what I said. It holds a wish.
Like the coins tossed into a fountain, or a stone stacked on a wayside cairn.
The potion doesn't exactly grant the wish. That part's up to the person who made it.
Then how is that any different from tossing a coin?
Because it's crafted by me, a witch.
It's like the difference between a potion made by a witch and one made by... well, anyone else.
...I guess that does make some sense.
Right? Now, here's the process.
Since it's for a precious wish, start with the weakest flame.
Then add the wish-infused ingredients one by one.
After each addition, stir slowly, alternating hands, while focusing on the wish.
Finally, turn the flame high, and it's done.
That's it? Potions are supposed to have symbolic meaning in every step, heat, stirring, all of it.
And this one does. That's all it needs.
Now let's gather ingredients from the villagers!
How long are you going to mope?
There's still a tree to fix.
There's nothing we can do for Lisa now... right?
It's already in the past.
For her sake, we should see this through properly.
...Yeah, you're right.
[lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))]...
It's a place to bury a wish.
A wish? And how are you going to bury that?
Lisa told you, didn't she? I'm a witch, and I can make it happen.
With a potion, of course.
Why a potion?
Simply because I'm not good at much else yet.
So, I'll make a potion that can hold a wish.
That's what I'm best at.
Sure, you can infuse a potion with wish while brewing it. But what about everyone else?
The potion is going to be brewed by you alone!
We can make it together!
They'll each bring me [em1]wish-infused ingredients[/em1].
I've never heard of such a potion.
That's fine! I'll be the first to make it.
You're inventing the recipe yourself?
Yup. I made the [lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion"))] myself, didn't I?
You found the recipe for [lua(GetItemName("PolarisPotion"))], remember?
Did I? Well, whatever.
Everything has a first time.
I'm not sure this will work the way you think...
You never know until you try.
Who knows? Maybe it'll catch on, and people everywhere will use it.
You'll need the Potion Association's approval before you can sell it.
I'm not selling it, so stop nagging.
Come on! Let's go make the recipe.
We'll do it at the workbench.
Alright, we've got all the materials.
These are probably enough to carry the wish.
Will it really work...?
The wish should be satisfied with them.
What worries me is your crafting skill.
My skill is fine. Just relax.
I'll get to the crafting then.
<shake>Wait... this actually works?</shake>
And you're surprised now?
Hey, it's my first time making it!
That's because this potion didn't exist until you made it.
That's... <wave>weirdly touching</wave>.
Not quite the sentiment I was going for.
Anyway, now that the potion's done, let's head to where that prickly vine core was in [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))].
The [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))] might still be dangerous, so I'd better come with you.
Right now!
Alright... guess I should get ready for the festival too.
I'll need the recipes for [lua(GetItemName("FirecrackerPotion"))] and... [lua(GetItemName("SpotlightPotion"))].
Let's ask Diane.
Poor Diane, she's probably exhausted.
Buying the recipes is unavoidable.
...Wait. You know, we should invite her to the festival too.
She's helped us so much.
Actually, not just her, lots of people have.
I'll check with Enite first!
Perfect, [lua(GetItemName("FirecrackerPotion"))] is ready.
I'll split it up right before the festival.
And the [lua(GetItemName("SpotlightPotion"))] is done.
Think Lisa will like it?
Honestly? Probably not.
Too bad. She's getting the spotlight anyway.
...And that's what happened.
Wait, Lisa. Didn't you leave out something?
What "something"?
You know... her situation.
You mean that she's dead?
Yeah...
Pretty sure she didn't mention it.
Hah! Knew it. I figured it had to be some kind of mistake.
I never believed Lisa would do such a thing.
A mistake is still a mistake.
Hey, you said you forgave her earlier...
I did. Doesn't mean it wasn't wrong.
...Oh.
Arden's right.
Intentions aside, the vines didn't just vanish, and the buildings didn't rebuild themselves.
I don't want to pretend it never happened, even if it was an accident.
I made the mess. Ellie and all of you had to clean it up.
So I'm here to apologize, face-to-face.
Huh? Oh! Uh...
Hello! I'm Rex Eastchip.
I'm here in place of Mr. Brad.
Brad? Ah, the boy who ran the library. Pleased to meet you, Rex.
And I'm Arin, his friend.
Nice to meet you too, Arin.
You... you tried to make things right.
Not everyone would fight to fix their mistakes until the very end.
Yeah! Brad told me, "Don't worry, Lisa will set things right."
Thank you. Both of you.
Yeah! My parents always spoke highly of Lisa.
Mine too! They said Wisteria had an amazing witch.
If not for Ellie and all of you, I'd never have had the chance to make amends.
I'm grateful... and sorry.
The fact that I can be here is only possible thanks to you and Ellie.
Even if it started as a mistake...
Coming here to apologize in person is admirable.
Plenty of people just patch things up and move on without saying a word.
And my parents always said you'd come back one day to put things right.
It's the festival!
It's the festival.
Let's go to the village.
So... does this mean Lisa's back?
...You could say that.
That's such a relief.
I thought I'd never see her again.
...Enite.
You've aged.
Lisa, you've known Enite since she was a child?
Since before she was born. I was there when she came into the world.
I still remember her tiny hand gripping my finger, smiling.
And when she left the village, too...
Wait. Enite left the village?
When she was about your age.
That story is...
Heh. You should hear it from her directly.
Someday... maybe.
Still shy about it after all this time. You've grown up, but you're still that same girl inside.
You're the only one who still sees me that way, Lisa.
Anyway, I'm glad you're back.
...So am I.
Alright, Ellie. When you're done looking around and eating, let me know.
Shall we move on to the next part?
It's the concert.
Okay
Looks like everyone's had their fill. Let's start.
Not yet
Take your time then.
Lisa, are you sure you don't want to tell them?
Tell them what?
The thing you left out.
That you... died.
They deserve to...
Today's a happy day.
For me, and for all of us.
I wouldn't ruin that.
So what will you do?
I'll tell them myself. You keep quiet.
What are you two talking about?
About our wonderful village.
Ellie's done so much for us.
I'll leave you two to talk.
Well, look at that! You're tending bar here too.
That's right. I received the invitation.
And judging by your face, you must've gotten my letter too.
You mean the one you left behind back then?
Thanks to that, I found the village and fixed the tree.
I'm not sure what you mean, but if it helped, great.
So, how about a drink?
No thanks. I don't drink.
When are you finally going to be old enough for one?
Hmm... maybe the next time we meet?
Then I guess I'll have to stop by again.
You haven't set any fires here, have you?
I don't go around setting fires anywhere, you know.
You did at the School for Witches.
You still remember that?
Comes with the job.
Come to think of it, I don't think I ever caught your name.
And yours?
Ellie. Ellie Blueriver.
I already knew. Word gets around.
Then what's your name?
I'll tell you when you're old enough for a drink.
Would you believe she says she's older than me?
A gentleman shouldn't go around blurting out a lady's age.
Even a lady's subject to the drinking age, you know.
Which I already told you I'm well past.
So I poured her one.
She takes responsibility for herself.
And I'm more than capable of that.
Hehe! But what's with that look of yours?
You don't just look young... You look too young.
Every lady needs to keep one or two secrets.
It's because of a curse, isn't it?
Sharp one, aren't you?
You seem to have a long history with curses.
Don't put it that way.
When you trade in all kinds of goods, you can't avoid running into them.
Not working today?
Day off.
On a day this nice, even I deserve a little rest.
And I did get an invitation.
You've helped out a lot, too.
That was business.
A good deal, then.
Yeah. Looking at the village now, I'd say it really was.
You truly never gave up on this place.
Of course not. Why would I?
Anyone can say that, but almost no one actually does it.
You've earned the right to be proud.
Spoken like someone with a lot of years behind her?
Don't start teasing me about my age.
There you are! The star of the day! Haha!
Enjoying the festival?
Naturally! The drinks here are amazing!
Careful, Arden wouldn't like to hear that.
Oh, relax. He wouldn't pour me any even if he did! Hehe!
This terrace, your handiwork too?
Yep. It was a bit of work, but seeing everyone enjoy it makes it worth it.
Maybe the blueprints were just that good?
My merchandise is always top-notch.
And the builder's skill wasn't bad either, huh? Thanks.
How do you feel about it, Kyla?
Great! There's good liquor here, after all.
No, I mean. The village is finally complete.
Ah... right. Well...
Still great!
You don't have to force it, you know.
No, it's good. I'm happy seeing everyone else happy, and I do like Wisteria.
But building houses isn't really my calling.
It's hard to keep up the interest or sense of achievement.
Shame, with skills like yours.
Agreed. It'd be a waste not to use them.
Hehe! A bit late, but thanks.
I just have something else I want to do.
And that is?
That's a secret.
Every lady needs one, remember?
I've got to keep at least one for myself. Hehe!
Ah, the guest of honor arrives.
What were you all talking about?
Fine liquor, my friend!
This guy thought mead was actually star honey wine.
It's not a mistake! It is star honey wine!
But it's honey from bees, so it's mead!
That's not the point!
...And that's the discussion.
Fascinating debate.
So, Alvin, how does it feel seeing the village restored?
Every tale is a journey.
And when it's done, that's the ending.
All that's left is a gentle epilogue.
Not quite. Now everyone's gathered.
By your own logic, the stage is set and the cast is assembled.
I suppose you could see it that way.
The long, grand prologue is over.
Have you thought about what you'll do now?
I'm no actor. I'm the audience.
Sitting in the front row after the prologue's curtain falls...
Nodding in satisfaction, waiting for the next act to begin.
With such a fine stage and cast, it's bound to be exciting.
I'll be looking forward to it.
What does liquor taste like?
It's the taste of experience.
Haha! Well said, my friend!
I still don't get it.
That's fine. In time, you'll come to understand. There's no need to worry.
Ah, Ellie! Care to join me for a drink?
I'm... not old enough yet.
Ahh, of course. My apologies.
But what did you mean by "the taste of experience"?
It's just something drunkards like to say.
Nonsense!
Drink sweeps away the impurities of the mind.
Impurities of the mind?
Indeed.
The mind is always cluttered with worries. Those are the impurities.
What if that person hates me? What will I do tomorrow? How should I handle this?
And drinking makes those worries vanish?
Ha-ha-ha! Exactly!
But what's that got to do with experience?
The more you've lived, the more worries you carry.
And beneath those clouds of worry, an experienced mind runs deeper and clearer.
Which is why the more experience you have, the better the drink tastes! Hahaha!
Hearing all that makes me curious about its taste.
Then someday, when you're ready, we'll share a cup!
Great... one more drunkard in the village.
And what's wrong with that?
...Is it even alive?
"Barely alive," I think were Roy's exact words.
Hmm... It's been part of this village for ages. I really want to try and save it...
Anyone here know plants well? Roy, maybe?
Didn't seem like Roy knew much when I spoke with him earlier.
Then... ah! Lisa!
She's a witch who specializes in plants. She might know something.
True...
Though last time, her results looked more like a mess of prickly vines.
Everyone makes mistakes.
Let's ask her anyway.
Hello, Freddie.
I just happened to pass by.
Hohaha! You try to sound unconcerned, while you're actually enjoying it!
This dude is ruining my mood.
<shake>S-sorry!</shake>
He's just kidding.
Let's hope that's the case.
How do you like it?
It reminds me of the past.
What about the past?
Well... The hustle and bustle?
The warm and caring atmosphere.
Yeah, basically.
If so, just move in with us, Freddie!
No, I refuse.
That was cold!
I prefer being on my own.
Why? We're social creatures.
No, we need to keep some distance from each other.
That's not wrong.
Right? You'll bump into each other if you get too close.
No! Humans are supposed to be jammed together!
Don't count me as human then.
There are people and people.
I find the current distance comfortable.
Alright. I'll visit you from time to time, Freddie. I hope you can visit us in the village too.
I'll think about it.
Hohaha! Let's have another drink someday!
Let me know when this dude isn't around.
<shake>WHY!</shake>
How about this place? It looks so fun!
It looks dangerous to me.
Hmm... Does it...?
Hi there.
Jeez!
Why do you keep popping up from nowhere!
It's a festival, and I'm just wandering around.
What were you talking about?
The destination of my next exploration!
Arin finds every place dangerous. She won't let me go anywhere...
Because they really are dangerous.
I'm tough. I'll be fine...
Not tough enough for them.
See...
Arin really cares about Rex.
It's not like that...
You're like a mother to Rex.
I don't need a second mother!
Listen to Arin, will you? She says so because she cares for you.
I'd usually listen, but not this time.
I've got a goal to fulfill.
A goal? What is it?
It's a secret.
Right. I can't say it.
Oh, Ellie...
Are you having a good time?
I'm not asking you...
Well... I am, thanks to Rex.
Fine...
Arin, have you gotten used to life in the village?
Yes, although I've never managed a library alone...
I've been adapting, and I've received much help from the villagers.
I'm glad to hear that! I was worried that it might be too much work for a single person.
You didn't help out...
Ellie...
Will you always stay at Wisteria?
I don't think I'm leaving anytime soon.
I see...
Just let me know if you need any help.
Or let ME know!
Hi, Ellie.
Sure, it's so lively and fun.
I do enjoy the unpretentious bustle.
Roy! Have you had any donuts?
N-not yet...
Try one! You should eat Clala's donuts while they are hot!
O-okay...
Roy isn't good at dealing with kids.
(talking with mouth full)
You can swallow your food first.
Is it good? Is it good? Tell me it's good!
It's great.
It certainly is! Clala's donuts are the best!
It's as if Roy's getting a little sister.
A little sister...
Am I like a little sister to you?
You are! Everyone at Wisteria is family.
Great! Dana wants a big brother!
Family...
Right. Roy, you want to be family?
Well... I do. It's nice.
This tastes warm and sweet.
That's a carrot donut!
Roy! You've got to try this one as well!
Hm... alright...
And this one, this one as well. This one's also good!
Dana, you keep yourself busy even when at the festival.
Why not? I need to promote Clala's donuts to everyone!
Don't force them on anyone who doesn't want to eat.
Got it!
It's alright... You'll be forgiven for being a little bit pushy.
Okay! I'm on it!
Dana, you have a close bond with Clala.
Sure! There's nothing we can't achieve together!
How long have you been working with each other?
Hm... well... let's see...
Since long long ago! Ahaha!
Is it always Clala in charge of baking donuts and you in charge of delivering them?
That's right! Clala's donuts are warm and sweet!
Dana, don't you want to try your hand at baking donuts?
Well... I do.
But Clala needs me to do the delivery.
You're so reliable, Dana‌.
Ahah! So I am!
Ellie, you can have this one as well!
Welcome, Ellie. Would you like a donut?
Today's donuts are perfect.
It really is!
Woah, it smells like heaven.
You've got to have one.
I should be the one saying thank you.
Clala, are you enjoying the festival?
Festivals are the busiest days for me,
but I find the most enjoyment in work.
You're being rushed off your feet.
So I am. I need to prepare the ingredients, lay the baked batches out, and everything.
But the busiest hours have passed.
Clala, your life seems to revolve around baked goods.
Did she?
Right. You think about which bread to bake even when not at work.
It's my dream to bring the taste of my baked goods to new heights and expand the bakery.
You can do it!
I agree! I've got your back, Clala!
Even I can feel exhausted at times, but everyone's support has kept me going.
You have my support too.
Thank you. As long as you enjoy the food, I'm motivated.
I'll come for a donut more frequently then.
Diane seems to be warming up to the festival already.
Thanks to Ellie, I think I've found another bakery to put in my recommendation list.
It's my honor. Please try this one as well.
Diane, you're not working today?
No. It's been a while since I took leave.
For bakery hunting... I mean, I certainly won't turn down an invitation from Ellie!
This village looks picturesque.
The first time I came, there were prickly vines everywhere...
But see what it has evolved into.
You've come a long way, Ellie.
And you've helped me a lot, Diane.
I was just performing my duties.
Come on.
That said...
I know you've done more than your job requires.
You can be proud of yourself.
The village owes a large part of its current beauty to you, Diane.
Diane?
When I decided to transfer to administration, I made myself a target of gossip.
Many questioned my decision because there were better places to go.
And in the beginning, I suspected that they were right.
I didn't expect this job to give me a real sense of achievement!
Thank you, Ellie! You've revealed that to me!
You can work wonders in whatever job you choose, Diane.
Theo! There's a huuuge crowd!
You don't call that a huge crowd.
Where I used to live, there were ten times more people.
There were a hundred times more people at the festival of witches.
Really?!
There were a thousand times more people at the festivals I used to go to!
There were ten thousand times more people when the School for Witches held an event!
My goodness...!!
You liar. There can't be that many people.
I'm not lying! You can go see it with your own eyes.
Exactly how many would "ten thousand times more people" be?
A lot, period.
You won't want that. Participating in an event that crowded will only wear you out.
I wish I could be at a crowded festival one day.
I'll take you to one.
So will I.
Will you? It must be fun!
Have you had any donuts?
Not yet.
Go grab one then.
Clala may be garrulous, but her donuts are good, teehee.
I heard you.
Tsk, you have sharp ears.
Are you having fun?
Theo was caught trying to sneak a drink of wine.
Hey, don't you give me away!
Theo, you did it again?!
I'm just curious. Are you not, Ellie?
I don't care about alcohol.
Look who's talking.
Granny says that you need to come of age to drink.
What is come of age?
That's just a fib for kids.
Adults say so to keep all the delicious stuff to themselves.
Theo, you won't want to drink alcohol.
Because alcohol is super bitter.
No way!
It's true. I've tried some.
You have? But you aren't an adult yet!
My friend once made her own liquor...
Ellie started drinking before coming of age!
Ellie, I'm impressed!
It was just bitter as hell. I'll never want to drink again.
And I got a good scolding...
It's not worth your interest.
I won't know until I try it myself.
How about we make liquor together someday?
That's an absolute no.
So you did.
How's business going?
It's good.
So good that it's annoying.
That's what a festival is like.
That's why I've never been a fan of festivals.
By the way, Wisteria used to have a larger population?
Larger than now.
What were things like back then?
It was...
a bit nosier than now.
And there were many irritating fellows.
What about now?
Not as noisy.
After all, there are fewer people.
Not short of irritating fellows, though.
That's what makes a village cozy.
Has your impression of witches changed?
Why!
There are good witches and evil witches.
That's true...
Which type am I?
The annoying type...
Hey.
Vinch, why aren't you with anyone else?
I feel a bit uneasy at the festival.
But you always spend your days holed up at home painting.
You should at least come out and meet people once in a while.
I'm not really into loud places.
I'm glad the village is bustling, though.
So am I.
Vinch, what do you usually draw about?
Well... a bit of everything...
But chiefly flowers.
They must be beautiful.
Is there a reason why flowers are your favorite theme?
Drawing flowers feels calming...
Show me your flower drawings sometime.
Once I finish the painting I'm currently working on.
Really? What kind of painting is it?
A painting... of flowers, I suppose.
I don't know how long it will take, though.
It's my honor.
What a joyous festival! Hi, Ellie, hehehe...
Kent, it's you!
What do you think of this festival?
It's sincere and unpretentious.
I can see the efforts the villagers put in it, and your hard work as well, Ms. Ellie.
I didn't do anything special for this festival.
The villagers organized it all by themselves.
Hehehe... but isn't the village itself a gift from you, Ms. Ellie?
You do have a point.
In that case, traces of your hard work must also be somewhere in the village, Kent.
Ms. Ellie, that you're able to receive help from so many...
must be because you've earned the villagers' support with your efforts.
Although witches are taught to help those in their reach, only a few manage to put it into practice.
Kent, you've also helped me a lot.
I've only seen a handful of people who actually manage it...
And Ms. Ellie, of course you are one of them, hehehe...
It's so nice of you to say that, heh...
What about my mother?
Lady Aria is certainly not one of them.
Aria does follow that principle in a way.
But for Aria, only herself is in her reach.
Master Virgil is right. No one can be closer to a witch than herself.
Maybe Lady Aria should relearn her lessons, hehehe...
Mom is just following her heart.
Speaking of Lady Aria, she asked me to tell you that she's proud of you.
And that it upsets her that you didn't invite her to the festival.
But this festival is meant for people who have helped with the restoration.
"If Ellie says so," Lady Aria said, "tell her that I helped by giving birth to her!"
"You ungrateful girl!"
Please tell her that I'll make sure she receives an invitation next time...
Understood. I believe Lady Aria will look forward to it.
Or rather, she may come visit you soon, before another festival even takes place, hehehe...
<shake>Umm...</shake>
Huh?! You mean my mom? When?
Well, it will spoil the fun if I tell you now... hehehe...
Eek... do warn me in advance before she arrives, Kent!
Hehehe... what an eventful village.
<shake>Jeez! What was that?!</shake>
Something giant just dived into the soil!
Didn't catch it either.
Let's follow it!
Well... the prickly vine is extending downward.
Since the star has fallen off, Lisa should also be down there.
And the big guy you're after.
It's a cave in a cave.
That big guy's gone.
It dived even further in the blink of an eye?
After all, it doesn't need a step board to go down.
Alright, I'll look for a path that goes down.
There should be traces of prickly vines to guide me.
So smoothly have you changed your purpose to tracking down that guy...
Wait... I can't fit in more starry flashes.
It takes another 1 or 2 starry flashes to float something this size. What do I do now?
How about you get off?
I'm not that heavy. It won't float even if I'm not onboard.
And it defeats the purpose to float it by disembarking me.
If you can't lighten the load, you'll have to improve buoyancy.
Well... I need to [em1]achieve the effect of more starry flashes[/em1] without actually adding starry flashes.
Like a bigger flame?
Right, I need [em1]bigger flames[/em1]!
Keep following the prickly vines then.
This looks like a workbench.
There's nothing eye-catching.
And only a few tools remain.
Whoever used this place must have taken most of the tools with them.
All that remains is a pile of trash.
There can be hidden treasure in the trash.
Pieces of chalk, rocks, a broken wooden hammer...
Hey, this lantern looks decent.
It's old, but probably usable.
And it has a bit of oil left in it.
What if you light it?
It looks ordinary. I don't think it does anything unusual.
Try it then.
I don't have any match or flint.
Wait... Maybe I can...
Use a [em1]starry flash[/em1]?
I don't think a starry flash works like a flame.
But the lantern has a star pattern on it. It may work.
Judging by the map, we're quite close.
Now that the lantern is lit, we should look for the sculptures.
Should we try using the lantern to find Tanis’s statue?
Let’s do it later.
Here it is!
Light it with the lantern...
Is that an apple that's tangled in the prickly vines?
I've got a bad feeling about this.
Tanis has obviously done something.
I'll take the dice.
There's more writing.
I didn't know that a star had such power.
That such things could be produced with a star...
I certainly know that [em1]magic which interferes with life is prohibited[/em1].
But that wasn't intended. Therefore, I'm not to be blamed.
I was just sculpting... That's all...
What's that noise?
She did something with the star.
[em1]Magic which interferes with life[/em1]?
[em1]Immortal lives[/em1]?
Arin had mentioned it!
So, Tanis tried to achieve immortality with the power of the star?
And when Lisa found out, she came after Tanis?
But Lisa died.
Right... Lisa's chief purpose was to study prickly vines.
And she said that stars were not immortal lives.
But this isn't enough to reveal the whole picture.
Onto the next sculpture.
It's just an egg-shaped object.
With a smooth surface.
So smooth that it's creepy.
The dice... Here it is.
What does it say?
What on earth have I done?
The thing actually moved? And cried? It... is alive?
If I've created it... If it has come to life... No, if it has been born...
Firstly, you need a name.
You were born from a star, and you look like a whale. I shall name you [em1]Starwhale[/em1].
I'm sorry. I...
<shake>Starwhale?!</shake>
Is this what Tanis did? Is it what we read about at those sculptures?
You mean, Tanis created the Starwhales?
But Starwhales are living creatures. How could this be possible...
Think about what you read before.
[em1]Magic which interferes with life[/em1]!
That wasn't about achieving immortality.
It was about [em1]creating lives[/em1]!
Both are prohibited though.
But how did she do it?
Maybe she was good at dice rolling?
This is not funny, Virgil.
Different people may achieve different results even if they do the same things.
The world would have been full of star creatures already if everyone could turn random sculptures into flying whales.
How did Tanis do it then?
Like I said, she was good at dice rolling.
Are you saying... that she was lucky? Hmm...
Fortunately, Starwhales are elegant creatures.
Not necessarily.
Find the next sculpture first.
It's lighted. The starry flash ignited it!
So, starry flashes can replicate.
It may be some sort of [em1]special fuel[/em1].
But why's the flame so small?
You need to case it if you want a bigger flame.
I see. I'll try.
You're right. The flame has grown.
But has there always been a [em1]glowing paper sheet on the floor[/em1]?
The paper has always been there, but maybe not the writing on it.
Woah, the writing appeared when illuminated by the flame? That's amazing!
Starry flashes can both conceal and reveal. It's a trick that utilizes their nature.
Tanis was quite smart.
Let's give the workshop another thorough search with the light from the lantern.
I think we've checked everything.
And found nothing special.
You can now return to the shelves and books...
The <shake>lantern!</shake> I can light the lantern first!
It would be amazing if we could light it with a [em1]starry flash[/em1]!
If that doesn't work out, you'll have to check out the bookcases and shelves.
But the shelves smell funny, and there are too many books.
Either that or make a bucketful of Moon Tears.
Fine!
Anyway, I'll [em1]try to light the lantern with a starry flash[/em1].
There's something...
Is it a sculpture...?
It's too dim. I can't see clearly.
Is there a way to see better?
Ignite the sculpture?
I don't want to burn the sculpture down.
Wait, there seems to be an oil dish.
Maybe I can place part of the starry flash on it.
Wouldn't the lantern go out?
There's a switch for adjusting. It should be fine.
(Fiddling)
As bright as day!
So, the place can only be fully illuminated if you place the flame at the right location.
A [em1]transparent statue[/em1]. It's incredible.
Tanis must be a starry flash expert if she was able to make this.
That said... the sculpture looks unfinished.
More like destroyed on purpose.
It looks like a person getting down on one knee.
There's a writing.
Who to pray to?
There's a doodled line. Or maybe it's a note.
What did she mean by "pray"?
Maybe she had a wish to fulfill.
She could have gone to the Cat Gods.
Maybe her wish required more than that.
There's something more.
It's a dice. They are seriously everywhere.
Now I really want to find all 6 of them.
To craft a potion, you need that many.
Right, I'll gather all the ingredients first.
Something on the desk is glowing too. I'll take a closer look.
Virgil, look at this!
It was a blank sheet a moment ago, but light from the lantern has revealed patterns on it!
Tanis apparently did an in-depth study on the starry flash.
It's text. I'll read it.
Like how you may rid your stomach of poisoned food through vomiting,
you may also rid your mind of poisonous ideas through writing.
I'm putting these thoughts down in order to survive.
What does this mean?
There should be more records.
Not on this sheet.
Are there other sheets?
Words seem to have emerged on other blank sheets as well...
There are markings on the map.
For treasure?!
Or for something dangerous.
That would be equally fun.
I'll take it with me.
By the way, there's something unusual about the flame in this lantern.
These words weren't here when I used the starry flash, but they became visible once I lit the lantern.
[em1]The lantern's flame and the starry flash are similar yet not quite the same[/em1].
They each have their own use.
I wonder if there are more clues.
I've examined everything here...
I shall look for hidden sculptures marked on the map.
Excuse me?
You haven't forgotten about the prickly vine core, have you?
But with the little intel we have, we can't possibly remove a prickly vine core that huge.
You deliberately ignored the Moon Tears.
After seeing Lisa's messages, I realized that I could use something in the [em1][lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))] to remove the core[/em1].
That's why we need to gather [em1]information concerning the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))][/em1].
And Tanis seems to know the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))] really well.
One can tell by looking at the sculptures she made using starry flashes.
Something happened to Tanis here, and she wrote it down.
These records should give us insight.
You agree?
And it won't hurt if we can find some interesting stuff during the process.
And you're gathering dice too.
Three to go.
By the way, three is also the number of maps we have.
Alright, I shall get all the dice and put them in this pot.
I'll put out the lantern and light it again when necessary.
Since we seem to be running out of fuel.
And do bear Lisa's words in mind.
Which words?
[em1]Warnings[/em1] against Tanis.
Lisa seems to have sealed this place off due to [em1]something[/em1] left by Tanis.
And she mentioned some sort of curse.
Got it. I'll be cautious.
This one's in the shape of flowers and butterflies.
A nice-looking sculpture, finally.
Has the Starwhale problem been solved?
I don't think so...
Take the dice.
Let's see what it says.
Lives are born from nature.
Seeds buried in soil cannot sprout without rain and sunshine.
I'm just the rain and sunshine to you.
You and I and everyone else are part of nature.
Tanis...
She justified her doing.
She's not wrong though.
I won't be surprised if someone with such a problematic idea makes a terrible blunder.
But nothing has gone wrong.
Things don't get prohibited for no reason.
Can't argue with that...
You're too young to make a sound judgment on this.
But maybe that's true for all of us.
I need to think it over.
Think later. For now, focus on the task at hand.
Right, now that I've got all the dice, I can try crafting the potion.
Let me add the dice to the pot at Tanis's workshop.
But there's nothing here.
After all, we don't know what the potion does...
I got it! We can check with the lantern.
The lantern may reveal something again.
But there's nowhere to hold a starry flash.
This hook may be intended for a lantern.
Right, let me hang the lantern here.
That was the correct move.
The one at the bottom should be the real thing.
That's... a chest?
It has a large sheet of paper stuck to it...
The writing resembles what we saw in Lisa's tent.
What? Lisa wrote this?!
Tanis rolled a dice. A dice that could bring an endless supply of disasters.
A kick of hers, with carelessness and irresponsibility, brought Starwhales to this world.
Despite the accidental birth, Starwhales have grown up to be stunning creatures.
However, that proves to be a cursed beauty.
Had Starwhales been ugly, had they wreaked havoc on the [lua(GetLocalizedString("Common", "Common_Theme_StarSeaCave"))], nobody would have rolled that dice again.
However, Starwhales are so elegant, that everyone who sees them would think—
"What if I roll that dice? I may also create something elegant."
It is a curse. One that spreads like a plague.
We know how many dice have been rolled, and how many disasters caused.
This place must be sealed off, so that nobody ever sees Starwhales.
Nobody should witness this stunning view.
Anyone who has the luck of seeing it should ignore it, and forget it.
No one should ever roll that dice again.
You who have come here and seen this, please ignore it, and forget it.
<shake>[em1]Ellie Blueriver[/em1]</shake>
<shake>What? Why's my name in it?!</shake>
It's enchanted text. It displays the name of whoever reads it.
I saw a different name.
Gave me a scare.
Wait, come to think of it, the White Cat God has said it before.
[em1]"Whatever you see, just ignore it."[/em1]
So, this is what they meant!
The White Cat God may share Lisa's idea.
Lisa also told us to ignore.
She probably wanted us to focus on dealing with prickly vines.
Or maybe she didn't want a younger witch to be led astray.
Fair...
I've almost got the picture. Anyway, let's open the chest.
I don't plan to roll a dice that Tanis has rolled.
This chest is the last clue.
<shake>There's got to be something in it!</shake>
There are some random items...
All the items are labeled.
Are these Tanis's belongings?
This looks like an oil drum.
Starwhale Oil
Starwhales sometimes apply starry flashes to themselves, which will then spread across their bodies.
They dive into water a moment later, putting out the starry flashes.
This seems to be how Starwhales cleanse their bodies of waste.
Starry flashes don't usually stick to anything, but they stick to Starwhales, which is curious.
I've made a lamp that burns the oil-like substance secreted by Starwhales.
But the lantern's flame features properties slightly different from starry flashes.
It seems to contain even [em1]greater power of the night[/em1].
The lantern burns Starwhale oil!
They are not whales in the first place. I doubt that counts as oil.
But the drum is empty.
And what's this shiny thing?
A piece of glowing plate that has come off of a Starwhale's body.
